WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:31.600
Around the year 1333, the North African writer&nbsp;
and traveler Ibn Battuta went on a journey

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:37.520
around all of Asia that would take him&nbsp;
to India and over the sea to Sri Lanka,

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:45.360
Bangladesh, Malaysia, and eventually on to his&nbsp;
final destination of China. But the first leg

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:53.440
of this journey took him along the winding roads&nbsp;
over land from Constantinople. He traveled past

00:00:53.440 --> 00:01:00.720
the shores of the Black and Caspian Seas, over&nbsp;
vast grasslands, and on southwards through the

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:10.760
deserts of Central Asia in what is now Kazakhstan,&nbsp;
Turkmenistan, and Uzbekistan. Ibn Battuta had heard

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:16.920
marvelous stories about the opulent cities&nbsp;
that lay along the vast trade route known as

00:01:16.920 --> 00:01:25.880
the Silk Road, which laced across the continent&nbsp;
of Asia. These were the cities of Balkh, Bukhara, and

00:01:25.880 --> 00:01:36.000
Samarqand. First, he visited the city of Bukhara,&nbsp;
once the jewel of Islamic learning, a city

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:42.800
of enormous libraries and colleges. But&nbsp;
to his disappointment, when he arrived,

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:51.640
he found the city a much reduced&nbsp;
place, as he wrote in his

00:01:51.640 --> 00:02:00.000
journal. We traveled for a whole day&nbsp;
through contiguous orchards, with streams,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:07.920
trees, and habitations, and arrived at the city&nbsp;
of Bukhara. This city was formerly the capital

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:14.960
of the lands beyond the river Jaihiin, but was laid in&nbsp;
ruins so at the present time its mosques, colleges,

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:22.840
and bazaars are in ruins, all but a few, and its&nbsp;
inhabitants are looked down upon. There is not

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:29.840
one person in it today who possesses any religious&nbsp;
learning or who shows any concern for acquiring it.

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:40.480
Surprised at the sorry sight of&nbsp;
the once great city of Bukhara, Ibn

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:44.520
Battuta continued on to the opulent metropolis of

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:54.400
Samarqand. I journeyed to the city of&nbsp;
Samarqand, once one of the greatest and

00:02:54.400 --> 00:03:00.400
finest of cities, and most perfect of them in&nbsp;
beauty. It is built on the bank of the river

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:05.200
called the Wadil-Wassarin, along which there&nbsp;
are water wheels to supply water to the

00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:14.280
orchards. But when he arrived at the&nbsp;
oasis of Samarqand, he found it, too, was

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:20.640
in a much diminished state. The city&nbsp;
was sparsely inhabited, its legendary

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:29.760
walls torn down long ago, and its&nbsp;
grand buildings standing in ruins.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:37.880
There were formerly great palaces on the river&nbsp;
bank and constructions which bear witness to the

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:44.440
lofty aspirations of the townsfolk, but most of&nbsp;
this is obliterated, and most of the city itself

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:51.760
has also fallen into ruin. It has no city wall and&nbsp;
no gates, and there is vegetation growing inside

00:03:51.760 --> 00:04:04.840
it. Ibn Battuta soon left that melancholy place and&nbsp;
continued on his journey. Finally, he passed through

00:04:04.840 --> 00:04:12.680
the city of Balkh, now in northern Afghanistan.&nbsp;
This had once been another wealthy trade hub

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:20.480
and a center for the Zoroastrian religion. From a&nbsp;
distance, he could see its tall buildings rising

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:28.840
out of the river plains. But as he got closer,&nbsp;
he saw no smoke of cooking fires, no animals

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:37.520
in the fields, no traffic of people in its&nbsp;
streets. An eerie feeling must have crept up on

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:52.920
him. Next we crossed the river Jaihiin into the land of&nbsp;
Khurasan and marched for a day and a half, crossing

00:04:52.920 --> 00:05:00.560
the river through uninhabited desert and sands&nbsp;
to the city of Balkh. It is completely dilapidated and

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:06.480
uninhabited, but anyone seeing it would think it to&nbsp;
still be inhabited because of the solidity of its

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:14.400
construction, for it was a vast and important city.&nbsp;
Its mosques and colleges preserve their outward

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:19.400
appearance even now, with the inscriptions&nbsp;
on their buildings incised with lapis-blue

00:05:19.400 --> 00:05:30.240
paints. As he passed through this devastated&nbsp;
region, he heard stories about other ruined

00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:37.440
cities lying out in the desert, now so empty&nbsp;
of life that they could offer no shelter to

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:48.160
travelers. The great cities of Khurasan&nbsp;
are four; two of them are inhabited,

00:05:48.160 --> 00:06:00.040
namely Herat and Nishapur, and&nbsp;
two are in ruins, namely Balkh and Merv.

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:07.120
Had he journeyed out to the city of Merv, he would&nbsp;
have found an even more devastated ruin, just a

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:14.840
series of jagged earthen remains rising out of the&nbsp;
cracked salt flats of the desert, home only to

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:23.160
owls and wild dogs, where once a city of half&nbsp;
a million people had stood. Everywhere across

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:29.800
this region, the cities bore the scars of one of&nbsp;
the Middle Ages’ most momentous and world-changing

00:06:29.800 --> 00:06:39.520
events. This was the uniting of a nomadic&nbsp;
people who called themselves the Mongols. From

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:46.680
their homeland far away in the steppe grasslands&nbsp;
of East Asia, the Mongols had fused their anarchic

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:53.800
pastoral culture into a war machine that has had&nbsp;
few equals in history, and forged an empire that

00:06:53.800 --> 00:07:02.200
would stretch across much of the landmass of Asia,&nbsp;
the largest continuous land empire in history.

00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:09.880
In almost every land they touched, they would&nbsp;
bring destruction and death, fear and anguish,

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:18.080
but in places they also laid the foundation&nbsp;
for our modern world. As Ibn Battuta stood in

00:07:18.080 --> 00:07:25.120
the abandoned streets of Balkh, Samarqand, and Bukhara,&nbsp;
he must have wondered at the unlikely story of these

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:32.720
strange nomadic conquerors. He must have wandered&nbsp;
those ruined palaces and crumbled places of

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:39.880
worship, those empty markets and dilapidated&nbsp;
houses, and asked himself, where had these

00:07:39.880 --> 00:08:00.440
mysterious conquerors come from? What did they want,&nbsp;
and why had no one been able to stop them?

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:28.600
My name's Paul Cooper, and you're listening to&nbsp;
The Fall of Civilizations Podcast. Each episode,

00:08:28.600 --> 00:08:34.760
I look at a civilization of the past that rose&nbsp;
to glory and then collapsed into the ashes of

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:41.400
history. I want to ask, what did they have in&nbsp;
common? What led to their fall, and what did it

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:49.040
feel like to be a person alive at the time who&nbsp;
witnessed the end of their world? In this episode,

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:55.360
I want to tell one of the most remarkable and&nbsp;
unlikely stories from medieval history, the story

00:08:55.360 --> 00:09:02.240
of the Mongol Empire. I want to show how this&nbsp;
group of nomadic horse-riders united the

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:09.280
peoples of the Mongolian steppe and forged them&nbsp;
into a truly unique kind of state. I want to

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:15.640
describe how they conquered much of the lands&nbsp;
of Eurasia and brought the distant cultures of

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:22.680
China, Persia, the Middle East, and Europe into&nbsp;
contact, and I want to tell the story of how

00:09:22.680 --> 00:09:29.800
the world's largest land empire finally came&nbsp;
apart and left the world as we know it in its wake.

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:56.960
The Eurasian steppe is the largest grassland&nbsp;
on Earth. It's a vast corridor of seasonal savannas

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:05.280
that run virtually the entire length of Asia, and&nbsp;
covers around 7% of the planet's land surface.

00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:12.840
It stretches from Hungary and Poland in Eastern&nbsp;
Europe more than 8,000 km, passing over mountain

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:21.320
ranges and rolling hills, past salty inland seas&nbsp;
and sandy deserts, and over countless rivers until

00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:29.840
it reaches Northern China and the forests of&nbsp;
Manchuria on the Pacific Coast. The word steppe entered

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:37.840
English from the Russian language, with its origin&nbsp;
possibly rooted in the old Slavic word sutepi, which

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:46.160
means a place that is flat and bare. The Russian&nbsp;
author Anton Chekhov describes the landscape of the

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:59.240
steppe. A plain, broad, boundless, girdled by a chain&nbsp;
of hills, lies stretched before the traveler's eyes.

00:11:00.720 --> 00:11:09.120
The hills merge into rising ground, extending&nbsp;
to the very horizon, and disappearing into the

00:11:09.120 --> 00:11:19.960
lilac-hued far distance. On and on you travel, but&nbsp;
where it all begins and where it ends, you just

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:32.200
cannot make out. Coarse steppe grass, milkwood, wild&nbsp;
hemp; all are drenched in dew and caressed by the

00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:42.840
sun. The green forested lands of China and Europe&nbsp;
receive moisture from the winds blowing in from

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:50.080
the Pacific and Atlantic Oceans, meaning that they&nbsp;
can support large trees, forests, and all manner of

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:56.520
crops. But the lands of the steppe receive most of&nbsp;
their airflow from the north, from the frozen

00:11:56.520 --> 00:12:04.840
polar ocean of the Arctic. Cold air cannot hold&nbsp;
much moisture, and what little it contains falls

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:13.040
as rain in the northern mountains, where the&nbsp;
great, frozen pine forests of Siberia stretch.

00:12:13.040 --> 00:12:20.600
The low rainfall on the steppe means that trees&nbsp;
cannot survive, and even species of long grasses

00:12:20.600 --> 00:12:27.680
find it difficult to take root. As a result, all&nbsp;
that remains here are the hardiest species of

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:34.800
short grasses. For this reason, the steppe has&nbsp;
always supported massive herds of grazing

00:12:34.800 --> 00:12:45.160
animals. The first humans to set foot on the&nbsp;
steppe arrived about 40,000 years ago. They were

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:51.400
hunter-gatherers who lived off what the&nbsp;
land provided. In its rolling grassland,

00:12:51.400 --> 00:12:59.320
they hunted mammoths, then once those had&nbsp;
died out, boar, antelope, goats, and aurochs,

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:04.520
and one animal that lived in&nbsp;
the steppe in abundance; the wild

00:13:04.520 --> 00:13:14.840
horse. Horses evolved in North America around&nbsp;
4 million years ago, but had crossed over to

00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:23.760
Asia during one of the last ice ages, when a land&nbsp;
bridge existed between Alaska and Eastern Russia.

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:30.400
Humans and horses would one day form one of the&nbsp;
most successful partnerships in history, but

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:37.880
our fascination with them goes back even further.&nbsp;
Horses are the animal most frequently depicted

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:45.200
in the oldest prehistoric cave paintings, even in&nbsp;
those of Chauvet Cave in France, which are more than

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:53.520
30,000 years old, and predate the domestication of&nbsp;
the horse by 25 millennia. For all these thousands

00:13:53.520 --> 00:14:01.120
of years, humankind had looked on the horse&nbsp;
as a symbol of power, grace, and perhaps also

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:11.600
freedom. When people arrived on the&nbsp;
Eurasian steppe, they initially hunted horses

00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:18.360
for food like any other animal, with horse bones&nbsp;
showing up in slaughter sites from at least 10,000

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:26.640
years ago. But sometime around 6,000 years ago,&nbsp;
they began to be kept as livestock. Humans first

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:33.720
used horses for milk and meat alongside their&nbsp;
cattle, sheep, and goats, but over the following

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:39.720
thousand years or so, humans learned that if a&nbsp;
horse was sufficiently tamed, it would allow a

00:14:39.720 --> 00:14:49.440
human to ride on its back. We will never know which&nbsp;
daring young man or woman first leapt up onto the

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:56.640
back of a horse and braved the inevitable bucking&nbsp;
and kicking that every horse breaker must learn to

00:14:56.640 --> 00:15:05.720
endure, but when they did, they changed the course&nbsp;
of human history. Around 5,000 years ago, we begin

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:14.320
to see evidence of horse-riding on the Eurasian&nbsp;
steppe. One burial site in Botai in northern Kazakhstan

00:15:14.320 --> 00:15:20.200
contains the bones of horses, with the earliest&nbsp;
signs of wear on the teeth and jawbones that

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:25.960
suggest they had worn a metal bit in their mouths&nbsp;
for much of their life, which could be attached to

00:15:25.960 --> 00:15:36.440
reins for a rider. This development occurred at a&nbsp;
momentous time in human history. Around the world,

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:44.680
the earliest cities were just then coalescing in&nbsp;
Egypt, Mesopotamia, China, and elsewhere, and a new

00:15:44.680 --> 00:15:52.240
way of human life was taking shape. This new&nbsp;
lifestyle was based on the planting of grain,

00:15:52.240 --> 00:15:58.920
the making of pottery, and the building of fixed&nbsp;
dwellings. Soon came hierarchies and religions,

00:15:59.680 --> 00:16:07.680
priests and kings, armies and city walls. From&nbsp;
this settled way of life, the first written

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:15.280
words would be set down, cut into clay tablets&nbsp;
in the Sumerian cities of Ur and Uruk, carved

00:16:15.280 --> 00:16:23.840
into the stone temples of Egypt, and into shoulder&nbsp;
bones and tortoise shells in China. But it's clear

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:32.840
that in the vast expanse of the Eurasian steppe, an&nbsp;
equally dramatic revolution was taking place.

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:39.000
It's around this time that the first mention of&nbsp;
horses begins to appear in the written texts of

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:46.120
the Sumerians. They would call them by the name&nbsp;
anše-kurra, meaning donkey of the mountains, since

00:16:46.120 --> 00:16:53.920
they first arrived from the mountainous north.&nbsp;
One Sumerian text written more than 4,000 years

00:16:53.920 --> 00:17:00.760
ago is one of the first to mention this new&nbsp;
animal, describing the hero god Lugulbanda as

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:10.960
being as swift as a mountain horse. Holy&nbsp;
Lugulbanda came out from the mountain cave, and

00:17:10.960 --> 00:17:18.160
from that spot he sped away like a horse of&nbsp;
the mountains. Like a lone wild ass, he darted

00:17:18.160 --> 00:17:28.840
over the mountains; like a large, powerful donkey he&nbsp;
raced; a slim donkey, eager to run, he bounded along.

00:17:31.120 --> 00:17:35.520
Human life had just sped up considerably, and

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:39.640
the domestication of the horse&nbsp;
would change life on the steppe

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:50.400
forever. A herder traveling by foot can cover a&nbsp;
maximum of only about 30 km a day, which limits

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:57.160
how large his flock can be and how far he&nbsp;
could range in search of new grazing lands.

00:17:57.160 --> 00:18:03.480
But riding on the back of a horse meant you&nbsp;
could cover more than 100 km at a push, and

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:10.560
you could travel at five times the speed over&nbsp;
a short distance. With greater ability to cover

00:18:10.560 --> 00:18:16.280
large areas, you could also effectively&nbsp;
manage much larger herds, and with more

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:24.360
food available, you could establish ever bigger&nbsp;
families and social groups. While all around the

00:18:24.360 --> 00:18:31.280
world other peoples were settling down into&nbsp;
ever larger cities built of mudbrick and

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:39.120
stone, the people of the steppe were developing a&nbsp;
parallel way of life, a life constantly on the

00:18:39.120 --> 00:18:54.320
move. After the horse, people in the&nbsp;
Western steppe also likely invented the wheel,

00:18:54.320 --> 00:19:01.720
allowing them to transport bigger loads as well&nbsp;
as their families, the elderly, and children too

00:19:01.720 --> 00:19:09.600
young to ride. Whole communities could now become&nbsp;
completely mobile, living their lives from birth

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:19.600
to death without ever settling in one place.&nbsp;
This alternative way of life would meet with

00:19:19.600 --> 00:19:28.720
remarkable success. One legacy of that success&nbsp;
is the language that many of us speak today.

00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:38.720
Beginning perhaps around 4,000 BC, an enigmatic&nbsp;
population known only as the Proto-Indo Europeans

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:47.160
rode out of the Western portion of the steppe&nbsp;
in all directions. They brought their horses,

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:55.320
their wagons, and chariots with them. Wherever&nbsp;
they went, from India to Persia, Greece and

00:19:55.320 --> 00:20:04.320
Northern Europe, they conquered or settled and&nbsp;
left their language behind. Their lost dialect

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:14.840
is the ancestor of 445 languages that survive to&nbsp;
this day, from Hindi, Sinhala, Punjabi, and Farsi, to

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:23.920
Russian, Spanish, French, German, and English, and&nbsp;
in all of these languages they left traces of

00:20:23.920 --> 00:20:32.960
their way of life. Many languages in the Indo-&nbsp;
European family use similar words derived from

00:20:32.960 --> 00:20:44.240
Proto-Indo European for objects like wheel, axel, wagon,&nbsp;
chariot, and of course, horse. It's believed the

00:20:44.240 --> 00:20:51.600
Proto-Indo Europeans had two words for horses,&nbsp;
which have been reconstructed to something like

00:20:51.600 --> 00:20:58.600
‘ekwos’ and ‘marcos’, possibly to differentiate&nbsp;
between a wild horse and a tamed horse.

00:20:59.560 --> 00:21:08.840
Ekwos entered Latin as ‘equus’, from which we get&nbsp;
equestrian, and it entered Ancient Greek as ‘hippos’,

00:21:08.840 --> 00:21:16.800
from which we get hippodrome and hippopotamus,&nbsp;
and the word ‘marcos’ has survived in English as

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:24.960
the word for a female horse, a mare. This English&nbsp;
word can be found echoing on the other side of the

00:21:24.960 --> 00:21:33.320
world in Mongolia, where a single horse is called&nbsp;
‘mor’, and even in the non-Indo-European language of

00:21:33.320 --> 00:21:42.200
Mandarin Chinese, where a horse is called ‘ma’. Today,&nbsp;
these words connect people on every side of the

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:49.360
globe, and nearly half of the world's population&nbsp;
speaks a language descended from the Indo-European

00:21:49.360 --> 00:22:01.440
family. The Proto-Indo Europeans were the first&nbsp;
nomads to ride out of the steppe and leave

00:22:01.440 --> 00:22:08.480
their mark on history, but they were far from&nbsp;
the last. Still, there were drawbacks to the

00:22:08.480 --> 00:22:15.040
nomadic lifestyle. While the settled peoples&nbsp;
of the world developed alphabets and writing

00:22:15.040 --> 00:22:19.760
systems that allowed them to keep records&nbsp;
and recount their histories, the peoples

00:22:19.760 --> 00:22:26.040
of the steppe did not develop their own system&nbsp;
of writing. For this reason, for much of their

00:22:26.040 --> 00:22:32.320
history we can only detect their presence&nbsp;
through the writings of others, who often

00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:41.560
feared and hated them. In the 5th century BC,&nbsp;
the Greek historian Herodotus would write

00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:47.920
one account of the horse-riding nomads who&nbsp;
lived in the steppe around the Black Sea, and

00:22:47.920 --> 00:22:58.880
increasingly made armed raids into Central&nbsp;
Europe, a people the Greeks called the Scythians.

00:22:58.880 --> 00:23:03.200
Rather than build cities or walls, they&nbsp;
all carry their homes around with them

00:23:03.200 --> 00:23:07.960
on wagons, practice their archery from&nbsp;
horseback, and depend for their living

00:23:07.960 --> 00:23:15.800
on cattle rather than the fruits of the plow.&nbsp;
How, then, could they fail to defy every effort

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:23.720
made to conquer them or to pin them down?&nbsp;
Already the settled peoples of the world

00:23:23.720 --> 00:23:29.480
were encountering a paradox, that despite&nbsp;
all the technological advancement that

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:36.280
agricultural society had brought, these steppe&nbsp;
peoples were still exceptionally difficult to

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:47.080
fight. More than 800 years later, the&nbsp;
struggling Roman Empire was limping

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:54.840
through the remains of the 4th century, rocked&nbsp;
by crisis and civil war. It was at this point

00:23:54.840 --> 00:24:00.640
that they were menaced by a new threat,&nbsp;
a nomadic people who rode out of the

00:24:00.640 --> 00:24:10.440
steppe and sent waves of refugees fleeing in&nbsp;
their wake. They would be known as the Huns.

00:24:10.440 --> 00:24:17.320
The Roman writer Ammianus Marcellinus wrote with&nbsp;
distaste about these frighteningly ruthless

00:24:17.320 --> 00:24:25.880
nomads. The Huns are a race savage beyond&nbsp;
all parallel. They grow up without beards,

00:24:25.880 --> 00:24:31.840
with closely-knit and strong limbs. They are&nbsp;
all without fixed abode or settled mode of

00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:37.880
life. None of their offspring, when asked,&nbsp;
can tell you where he comes from, since

00:24:37.880 --> 00:24:43.920
he was conceived in one place, born far&nbsp;
from there, and brought up still farther

00:24:43.920 --> 00:24:54.680
away. The arrival of the Huns was a major factor&nbsp;
that contributed to the collapse of the Western

00:24:54.680 --> 00:25:01.280
Roman Empire. In the decades that followed,&nbsp;
under the rule of their leader Atilla, the

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:08.840
Huns would remake the balance of power in Europe.&nbsp;
They fleetingly captured large areas up to the

00:25:08.840 --> 00:25:19.080
banks of the Rhine, and left fire and destruction in&nbsp;
their wake. Part of the reason for the Huns’ success

00:25:19.080 --> 00:25:27.000
was their innovative use of the technological&nbsp;
development of the composite bow. Bows made of a

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:33.800
single piece of wood had a natural limit to their&nbsp;
power, but on the steppe, a good bow could mean the

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:41.280
difference between life and death, and so, people&nbsp;
had poured immense energy into developing them. By

00:25:41.280 --> 00:25:48.240
the time of the Huns, these were already intricate&nbsp;
constructions, combining multiple materials; a

00:25:48.240 --> 00:25:57.440
core of maple wood, bone, and antelope horn, knotted&nbsp;
with sinew, deer gut, and leather, all held together

00:25:57.440 --> 00:26:05.960
with a fish-based glue. The combination of these&nbsp;
materials created a bow with immense elasticity,

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:14.280
capable of hurtling an arrow at tremendous speeds&nbsp;
and over great distances, reportedly as far as 300

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:21.640
meters. If these accounts are accurate, then these bows&nbsp;
could shoot further than an English longbow, which

00:26:21.640 --> 00:26:28.240
stood taller than a man, but crucially was&nbsp;
compact enough to be drawn from horseback.

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:36.960
The combination of horse and composite bow would&nbsp;
make the steppe horse archer the deadliest single

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:42.920
entity on the planet, and in Europe, these&nbsp;
weapons would come to be known with fear

00:26:42.920 --> 00:26:58.400
and reverence as Hun bows. The people&nbsp;
of China struggled no less with their nomadic

00:26:58.400 --> 00:27:05.040
neighbors. During the period of the Han&nbsp;
Dynasty, a people they knew as the Xiongnu

00:27:05.040 --> 00:27:11.480
constantly menaced their borders for much of&nbsp;
the first millennium, and may even have been the

00:27:11.480 --> 00:27:21.880
same people as the European Huns. One Han period&nbsp;
Chinese writer, Sima Qian, describes their way of

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:32.840
life. The Xiongnu are mountain barbarians. They&nbsp;
move in search of water and pasture, and have no

00:27:32.840 --> 00:27:39.480
walled cities or fixed dwellings, nor do they&nbsp;
engage in any kind of agriculture. They wear

00:27:39.480 --> 00:27:46.440
clothes of hide or wraps made of fur or felt.&nbsp;
They have no writing, and even their promises

00:27:46.440 --> 00:27:53.040
and agreements are only verbal. The little boys&nbsp;
start out by learning to ride sheep, and shoot

00:27:53.040 --> 00:28:01.280
birds and rats with a bow. Thus, all the young&nbsp;
men are able to act as armed cavalry in time

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:12.160
of war. Around the 4th century, these&nbsp;
peoples also introduced the stirrup, straps for the

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:17.960
rider's feet that help them stay in the saddle&nbsp;
and allow them even greater control of their

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:28.120
horses. One medieval Chinese writer describes&nbsp;
the sight of a steppe horse warrior in action.

00:28:29.560 --> 00:28:34.680
When they ride at a gallop, they always stand&nbsp;
in the stirrups rather than sit in the saddle.

00:28:34.680 --> 00:28:39.600
They are swift as the onrush of a gale&nbsp;
and strong as the weight of a mountain.

00:28:39.600 --> 00:28:44.720
Wheeling left and cutting right like wings in&nbsp;
flight, they shoot with power enough to pierce

00:28:44.720 --> 00:28:55.840
armor. For the civilizations that lived on the&nbsp;
borders of the steppe in China, India, Persia, the

00:28:55.840 --> 00:29:04.720
Middle East, and Eastern Europe, these nomadic&nbsp;
peoples could be alien, frightening, and primitive.

00:29:04.720 --> 00:29:12.880
While they were divided, they could be contained,&nbsp;
controlled, and violently put down, but every few

00:29:12.880 --> 00:29:20.000
hundred years, they would unite into a force&nbsp;
large enough to flood out of the steppe. They

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:28.160
would come to conquer and settle, to wreak havoc&nbsp;
and sow destruction, but every time, to change

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:36.800
the course of history. The most dramatic of these&nbsp;
stories would take place as the 12th century came

00:29:36.800 --> 00:29:44.200
to a close, and the memory of Atilla's Huns&nbsp;
had faded to just another ghost story from

00:29:44.200 --> 00:29:51.760
classical history. It would come in the form of&nbsp;
a people who were perhaps the most unlikely of

00:29:51.760 --> 00:30:00.840
conquerers. When our story starts, they had many&nbsp;
names, but soon they would become known as the

00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:17.160
Mongols. To find the location of the beginning&nbsp;
of this story, we must travel to the east, along

00:30:17.160 --> 00:30:24.640
the wide expanse of the Eurasian steppe. For&nbsp;
thousands of kilometers, we would see only

00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:32.480
grassland and seasonal deserts. Then we pass&nbsp;
over the Altai Mountains, home to wolves, curly-

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:40.560
horned ibex, and eagles. Finally we would reach&nbsp;
the far eastern steppe on a high plateau of what

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:49.480
is today Mongolia. At the end of the 12th century,&nbsp;
the Mongols were just one of countless groups that

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:58.080
existed in this land, speaking Turkic languages&nbsp;
like Uighur and dialects of Mongolia, and worshiping

00:30:58.080 --> 00:31:04.840
any number of gods. But despite this variation,&nbsp;
many of them followed a similar way of

00:31:04.840 --> 00:31:14.440
life. Life on the steppe meant following&nbsp;
the natural cycles of the world. In the

00:31:14.440 --> 00:31:21.040
warm summers, the rains come, and the&nbsp;
grassland flushes green. During these

00:31:21.040 --> 00:31:27.920
months, the nomads’ herds of cattle, goats,&nbsp;
sheep, camels, and horses have plenty to eat,

00:31:28.600 --> 00:31:35.880
and they graze in their summer pastures on the&nbsp;
open grassland. But as the cold, dry winters descend,

00:31:35.880 --> 00:31:40.920
herders would move to their winter pastures&nbsp;
in the north, where the green valleys at the

00:31:40.920 --> 00:31:49.120
foot of the mountains remain shaded, and there&nbsp;
are still grasses growing. This natural cycle

00:31:49.120 --> 00:31:58.200
dictated every aspect of steppe life, as one&nbsp;
medieval Chinese writer, Zhao Gong, describes.

00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:05.960
In their custom, each time the grass grows green&nbsp;
is one year. So, if someone asks one of them his

00:32:05.960 --> 00:32:13.680
age, he says how many times the grass has greened.&nbsp;
Also, once when I asked one of them what month and

00:32:13.680 --> 00:32:20.240
day he was born, he laughed and replied, I can't&nbsp;
remember, nor did I ever know it in the first

00:32:20.240 --> 00:32:30.960
place. Winter on the steppe is harsh. During&nbsp;
these months, the wind blows straight from

00:32:30.960 --> 00:32:38.200
Siberia, and a layer of ice can often cover&nbsp;
the grasslands completely. When the grass is

00:32:38.200 --> 00:32:45.280
frozen, steppe peoples would allow their horses to&nbsp;
graze ahead of the other animals. They would use

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:57.840
their hooves to crack the ice, and then&nbsp;
other livestock like sheep could follow.

00:33:01.280 --> 00:33:08.920
In the flat, featureless landscape, people navigated&nbsp;
primarily using rivers, which interlace the steppe in

00:33:08.920 --> 00:33:17.800
countless waterways; among them the Orkhon, the&nbsp;
Selenge, and the Onon. By riding up and down

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:24.120
these rivers, the steppe peoples could find their&nbsp;
way, and would never be far from water for their

00:33:24.120 --> 00:33:32.400
horses. The knowledge of these river paths were&nbsp;
passed on from person to person by word of mouth,

00:33:32.400 --> 00:33:44.760
through poems and songs. The primary mode&nbsp;
of shelter in the steppe was the tent. One Chinese

00:33:44.760 --> 00:33:54.360
writer of the time named Li Xinchuan describes&nbsp;
these habitations. They have neither walls nor

00:33:54.360 --> 00:34:02.000
moats, nor houses nor mansions, but instead make&nbsp;
felt tents for which they choose dwelling places

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:10.760
that have the most beneficial water and
grass. In English, these tents are often called

00:34:10.760 --> 00:34:18.640
yurts, derived from a Turkic word, but in Mongolian&nbsp;
they are known as ‘ger’. Their structures are made

00:34:18.640 --> 00:34:25.560
of lattice of light but strong willow wands,&nbsp;
and their walls are made of felt, a material

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:33.200
created by pressing together layer upon layer of&nbsp;
sheep’s wool. These tents are warm during winter

00:34:33.200 --> 00:34:40.160
and cool during summer, and they are also&nbsp;
fully mobile, designed to be dismantled and

00:34:40.160 --> 00:34:49.280
rebuilt every day if necessary, and carried from&nbsp;
place to place on the back of carts. The Chinese

00:34:49.280 --> 00:34:57.640
observer Peng Daya wrote the following description&nbsp;
of seeing steppe people moving across the landscape.

00:34:59.080 --> 00:35:05.520
The yurts, that is felt tents in which they live,&nbsp;
have neither walls nor roof beams. They move them

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:11.880
to follow the grass and water, never staying&nbsp;
for long. Cattle, horses, or camels are used to

00:35:11.880 --> 00:35:17.560
pull their carts, on which it is roomy enough&nbsp;
to sit or recline. These carts are dispatched

00:35:17.560 --> 00:35:22.840
in groups of five, looking like columns of&nbsp;
ants as they wind along, extending out for five

00:35:22.840 --> 00:35:33.760
miles. Some of these carts could be huge, designed&nbsp;
to carry the tents of nobles on their back. One

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:41.040
European visitor to Mongolia in the Middle Ages,&nbsp;
William of Rubruck, described seeing carts as large

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:50.440
as 10 meters wide, about the length of a London bus.&nbsp;
These dwellings are constructed of such a size

00:35:50.440 --> 00:35:58.720
as to be on occasions 30 feet across. I myself once&nbsp;
measured a breadth of 20 feet between the wheel

00:35:58.720 --> 00:36:06.400
tracks of a wagon, and when the dwelling was on the&nbsp;
wagon, it protruded beyond the wheels by at least 5

00:36:06.400 --> 00:36:15.200
feet on either side. The wagon's axle was as large&nbsp;
as a ship's mast. I have counted 22 oxen to one

00:36:15.200 --> 00:36:23.960
wagon. These carts were insulated from the&nbsp;
changeable weather of the steppe, and those

00:36:23.960 --> 00:36:30.440
used to transport valuables were protected by&nbsp;
a special kind of felt that had been soaked

00:36:30.440 --> 00:36:37.880
in waxy tallow to keep out the rain. When their&nbsp;
day’s traveling was done, the steppe peoples would

00:36:37.880 --> 00:36:44.160
fortify their camp by placing their carts&nbsp;
in a ring, making a makeshift wall to keep

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:52.000
out raiders and thieves. Their ger tents were&nbsp;
always erected facing south so that the sun

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:57.720
would shine in through the doorway. The heads&nbsp;
of the house and people of high status would

00:36:57.720 --> 00:37:03.000
always sit on the north side of the tent&nbsp;
facing the door, while more junior members

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:11.720
of the clan would sit in the south. In the center&nbsp;
of the ger was a hearth fire made from burning

00:37:11.720 --> 00:37:19.760
pieces of dried dung. This was a resource in&nbsp;
infinite abundance among herders, but usually

00:37:19.760 --> 00:37:27.520
goat dung was preferred, since it burned cleanly&nbsp;
and gave off a pleasant smell like burning leaves.

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:37.080
Above this fire there was a smoke hole cut in&nbsp;
the felt roof. These smoke holes had a practical

00:37:37.080 --> 00:37:44.520
purpose as a chimney, but they also held a&nbsp;
kind of spiritual significance. The fire and

00:37:44.520 --> 00:37:50.840
the hole in the tent were considered to be a&nbsp;
means to communicate with the clan's ancestors,

00:37:50.840 --> 00:37:58.760
and was a ceremonial space for rituals. We can&nbsp;
imagine a Mongol family sitting around this

00:37:58.760 --> 00:38:06.400
fire with the vast darkness of the steppe at night&nbsp;
outside, watching the sparks of their fire drift

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:13.720
out through the hole in the roof, as the howling&nbsp;
steppe wind outside batters the felt walls of the

00:38:13.720 --> 00:38:32.840
tent. For those nomads who lived on the open grass-&nbsp;
lands of the steppe, life was good. Their vast herds

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:39.360
turned the virtually infinite supply of grass&nbsp;
into ample meat and milk, from which they could

00:38:39.360 --> 00:38:46.480
make a variety of cheese, yogurts, and other dairy&nbsp;
products, and into dung that could be burned in

00:38:46.480 --> 00:38:53.280
their fires. The steppe gave them everything they&nbsp;
needed to survive, and for everything else, they

00:38:53.280 --> 00:39:02.040
could trade with the lands of China to the south.&nbsp;
Nomadic peoples would buy silk, fine silver items,

00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:09.440
and carved furniture, along with all the comforts&nbsp;
of sophisticated society, and in return they would

00:39:09.440 --> 00:39:17.040
trade northern goods like furs, of which the most&nbsp;
valued was the delicate dark pelt of the sable, a

00:39:17.040 --> 00:39:24.440
kind of small pine marten, along with leather, bone,&nbsp;
and antler for carving, herd animals like cattle

00:39:24.440 --> 00:39:32.280
and sheep, and majestic tame hunting birds like the&nbsp;
golden eagle, taken from the forest as fledglings

00:39:32.280 --> 00:39:40.360
and trained to hunt small game. But above all, they&nbsp;
traded the thing that settled societies needed

00:39:40.360 --> 00:39:51.480
most and nomads had in enormous supply; horses. As&nbsp;
a result, these clans in the south of the Mongolian

00:39:51.480 --> 00:40:00.120
steppe, like the Tartars and the Kereyit, were richer and&nbsp;
lived more comfortable lives, and they defended

00:40:00.120 --> 00:40:08.280
their enviable positions with extreme ferocity.&nbsp;
In contrast, for much of their history, the Mongols

00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:16.520
were among the losers of the steppe world. While&nbsp;
other nomads thrived on the southern grasslands,

00:40:16.520 --> 00:40:23.640
the Mongols subsisted in the harsh north, on the&nbsp;
edge of the mountains and the endless Siberian

00:40:23.640 --> 00:40:32.760
forests, home to wolves, bears, and wild forest&nbsp;
peoples like the Merkit. Here, the grasses were

00:40:32.760 --> 00:40:39.960
meager and couldn't support large herds. As a&nbsp;
result, the Mongols supplemented their diets

00:40:39.960 --> 00:40:47.520
by hunting deer and small mammals like marmots,&nbsp;
gathering pine nuts in the forests, and fishing in

00:40:47.520 --> 00:40:57.240
the rivers. The medieval Persian historian, Ata-Malik
Juvaini, writes about the sorry state of this people.

00:40:58.400 --> 00:41:06.360
They had no chief or ruler. Each tribe lived&nbsp;
separately. They were not united with one

00:41:06.360 --> 00:41:12.520
another, and there was constant fighting and&nbsp;
hostility between them. Their clothing was of

00:41:12.520 --> 00:41:19.240
the skins of dogs and mice, and their food&nbsp;
was the flesh of those animals and other

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:27.240
dead things. Their wine was mares’ milk, and their&nbsp;
dessert the fruit of a tree shaped like a pine.

00:41:28.200 --> 00:41:35.880
The sign of a great king amongst them was that&nbsp;
his stirrups were made of iron. From that, one can

00:41:35.880 --> 00:41:44.520
form a picture of their other luxuries. Part of&nbsp;
the reason for their poor situation was that the

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:52.280
Mongols were among the most divided peoples of&nbsp;
the steppe, constantly fighting amongst themselves.

00:41:52.280 --> 00:41:59.480
Other steppe peoples had long ago formed large&nbsp;
confederations and adapted to the cultures of

00:41:59.480 --> 00:42:07.440
more settled societies around them, even taking on&nbsp;
their religions. Some, like the Khitan, had adopted

00:42:07.440 --> 00:42:13.320
Buddhism, while others had converted to Islam,&nbsp;
which had arrived in the southern steppe some

00:42:13.320 --> 00:42:21.200
centuries before, usually with traders passing&nbsp;
through. Others still like the Kereyit and the Naiman

00:42:21.200 --> 00:42:27.720
had even converted to the cult of a powerful&nbsp;
shaman from a far-away land, who was rumored

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:35.320
to have risen from the dead, a man named Jesus&nbsp;
Christ. Word of his teachings had been brought

00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:43.000
to Mongolia by Assyrian Nestorian missionaries&nbsp;
around the 11th century, and had appealed to many

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:49.480
people there, since the name Jesus reminded them&nbsp;
of the word ‘yesu’, which in Mongolian means the

00:42:49.480 --> 00:42:56.640
number nine, a number considered to be sacred and&nbsp;
to bring good luck. But the Mongols on the edge of

00:42:56.640 --> 00:43:04.400
the Siberian forests had adopted no such beliefs.&nbsp;
They maintained the ancient beliefs of their

00:43:04.400 --> 00:43:11.800
ancestors, worshiping the Earth mother goddess&nbsp;
and their ancient god of the Great Blue Sky, who

00:43:11.800 --> 00:43:20.840
they named Tengri. The 11th-century Muslim scholar&nbsp;
Mahmud al-Kashgari describes the worship of this

00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:27.280
god. Tengri means God. The infidel nomads

00:43:27.280 --> 00:43:32.520
call heaven Tengri, and likewise everything&nbsp;
natural that impresses them; for example, a

00:43:32.520 --> 00:43:39.720
high mountain or a large tree. They worship&nbsp;
such things, and they call a wise man Tengri-

00:43:39.720 --> 00:43:49.400
kaan. The god Tengri was believed to&nbsp;
reside particularly in the region of

00:43:49.400 --> 00:43:57.360
a vast freshwater lake known as Lake Baikal, and&nbsp;
it's here that the mythology of the Mongols

00:43:57.360 --> 00:44:05.840
begins. In the Mongol conception of&nbsp;
their own history, their story began

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:15.920
when a Siberian wolf mated with a roe deer, and gave&nbsp;
birth to the first of their royal line. This

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:23.400
founding myth is recounted in the enigmatic&nbsp;
document known as The Secret History of the

00:44:23.400 --> 00:44:27.040
Mongols.

00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:37.320
There was a blue-gray wolf born with a destiny&nbsp;
from heaven above. His wife was a beautiful red

00:44:37.320 --> 00:44:44.120
fallow doe. They came crossing the sea. They&nbsp;
made their home at the headwaters of the Onon

00:44:44.120 --> 00:44:59.680
River. With a surface area of more than 30,000&nbsp;
square kilometers, Lake Baikal is slightly larger than

00:44:59.680 --> 00:45:06.760
the country of Belgium, and is the largest&nbsp;
freshwater lake in Eurasia, and sitting as

00:45:06.760 --> 00:45:14.120
it does on a tectonic rift, it is also by far&nbsp;
the deepest on the planet, plunging to a depth

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:23.680
of more than 1,600 meters. As a result, it is also the&nbsp;
world's largest lake in volume, containing more

00:45:23.680 --> 00:45:31.760
than all the American Great Lakes combined. In fact,&nbsp;
this one lake is estimated to contain somewhere

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:39.880
between a quarter to a fifth of all the surface&nbsp;
fresh water on planet Earth. For most people

00:45:39.880 --> 00:45:46.040
of the steppe, this was the largest body of water&nbsp;
they would ever see, and on account of this, the

00:45:46.040 --> 00:45:56.960
Mongols would often simply refer to it as ‘the sea’.&nbsp;
When winter comes to the Siberian wastes, Lake Baikal

00:45:56.960 --> 00:46:04.440
freezes solid, with ice many meters thick, and&nbsp;
the snows blow in chaotic patterns over its

00:46:04.440 --> 00:46:14.200
surface. According to the story, eleven generations&nbsp;
after this unnatural coupling of wolf and deer

00:46:14.200 --> 00:46:22.560
on the shore of Lake Baikal, a woman known as&nbsp;
Alan Gua or Alan the Beautiful would give

00:46:22.560 --> 00:46:29.600
birth to five sons, and from these five men&nbsp;
were supposed to have descended the royal

00:46:29.600 --> 00:46:38.600
lineage of the Mongols. One day, the legend says,&nbsp;
Alan the Beautiful found her five sons arguing

00:46:38.600 --> 00:46:44.880
with one another. She gathered them together&nbsp;
and taught them a lesson that has passed into

00:46:44.880 --> 00:46:57.040
legend. She gave them each an arrow shaft, and&nbsp;
told them to break it. Each one was broken and

00:46:57.040 --> 00:47:05.160
let fall. Then she took five arrow shafts bundled&nbsp;
together, gave the shafts to them, and told them to

00:47:05.160 --> 00:47:12.000
break them. All five of them, one after another,&nbsp;
took the five arrow shafts joined together, but

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:18.080
were unable to do as she said and break it.&nbsp;
Then their mother Alan the Beautiful spoke

00:47:18.080 --> 00:47:27.000
words of admonition to her five sons. You, my five&nbsp;
sons, were born from a single womb. You are just

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:34.080
like the five arrow shafts; if you are alone,&nbsp;
one by one, you will be easily broken by

00:47:34.080 --> 00:47:40.280
anyone, but if you are joined in accord&nbsp;
as one, then how could you be broken by

00:47:40.280 --> 00:47:54.000
anyone? This story was told to generations of&nbsp;
Mongol children, and it contained a powerful

00:47:54.000 --> 00:48:00.840
truth about life on the steppe. Out there,&nbsp;
family was the most powerful connection

00:48:00.840 --> 00:48:06.600
that anyone had, and without it,&nbsp;
you were left alone, hungry, and

00:48:06.600 --> 00:48:15.880
defenseless. Mongols thought of their kin&nbsp;
relationships as a kind of branching tree

00:48:15.880 --> 00:48:25.360
or river. They traced their ancestry back to real&nbsp;
ancestors, a relationship known as Uruk, but the

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:32.400
Mongol elite also held to a kind of mythical&nbsp;
kinship, in which every person was descended from

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:39.000
one or other semi-mythical character who lived&nbsp;
in the vague and distant past, often one of the

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:46.720
sons of Alan the Beautiful. In this way, Mongols&nbsp;
considered themselves to belong to a wider clan

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:55.280
group that often had little to do with their&nbsp;
actual heritage. These they called their oboq.

00:48:55.280 --> 00:49:02.280
Accompanied with these two systems of relationship&nbsp;
was a third, one that people could freely choose

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:12.200
to enter into. This was known as anda, a kind of&nbsp;
blood brother. In this ritual, two close friends

00:49:12.200 --> 00:49:19.280
could swear an eternal allegiance, essentially&nbsp;
becoming family, and this relationship was taken

00:49:19.280 --> 00:49:28.640
just as seriously as any connection of kinship. One&nbsp;
Mongol text of the time records the depth of this

00:49:28.640 --> 00:49:42.800
bond. If we listen to the words of&nbsp;
the elders and the ancients, this is

00:49:42.800 --> 00:49:49.160
the way in which anda love each other.&nbsp;
People who are anda are as if they have

00:49:49.160 --> 00:49:56.640
one life without any separation, and&nbsp;
are lifelong saviors to each other.

00:50:00.460 --> 00:50:10.760
To survive in the harsh world of the steppe,&nbsp;
people had to be tough, but they also had to

00:50:10.760 --> 00:50:18.280
come together. To get a sense of the reality of&nbsp;
this life, there is no better example than the

00:50:18.280 --> 00:50:26.760
upbringing of one man born here on the steppe,&nbsp;
whose story we know in unprecedented detail,

00:50:26.760 --> 00:50:32.480
a man who would rise from the humblest&nbsp;
beginnings imaginable to change the course

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:56.640
of world history. His name was Temujin, but that&nbsp;
is not the name that history would know him by.

00:50:59.280 --> 00:51:07.720
It's worth mentioning that all of the story you&nbsp;
are about to hear was very nearly lost to history,

00:51:07.720 --> 00:51:18.040
but in 1866, a Russian monk working in the archives&nbsp;
of China uncovered a remarkable manuscript. It was

00:51:18.040 --> 00:51:25.920
a Chinese copy of a copy of a copy of a lost&nbsp;
Mongolian document written by an unknown author

00:51:25.920 --> 00:51:33.440
sometime in the 13th century. This book used&nbsp;
Chinese characters to recreate the phonetic

00:51:33.440 --> 00:51:39.720
sounds of the Mongolian language, and was used as a&nbsp;
kind of textbook to help Chinese scholars who were

00:51:39.720 --> 00:51:47.880
learning Mongolian. For this reason, its characters&nbsp;
appeared to be nonsense in Chinese, and so, it was

00:51:47.880 --> 00:51:55.240
lost among the archives. But once its contents&nbsp;
were deciphered, it transformed our understanding

00:51:55.240 --> 00:52:03.960
of this period. It was a document written only for&nbsp;
the eyes of the Mongolian royal family, telling in

00:52:03.960 --> 00:52:10.960
unprecedented detail the ups and downs of their&nbsp;
story, and for this reason, it came to be known

00:52:10.960 --> 00:52:19.160
as The Secret History of the Mongols. It's the&nbsp;
first and most important source ever written in

00:52:19.160 --> 00:52:26.520
the Mongolian language, and it blends narrative&nbsp;
history with flourishes of vaulting epic poetry.

00:52:28.600 --> 00:52:33.600
The story of the man named Temujin&nbsp;
begins in the second half of the

00:52:33.600 --> 00:52:37.920
12th century with his mother, a young woman named

00:52:37.920 --> 00:52:52.200
Oelun. She was from the Eastern Mongolian steppe,&nbsp;
to the southeast of Lake Baikal, and was probably

00:52:52.200 --> 00:53:01.480
no more than a teenager. She had just married a&nbsp;
man named Chiledu of the Merkit people. This young

00:53:01.480 --> 00:53:06.720
couple was in love, and she was now traveling&nbsp;
back to his homeland with him to live with his

00:53:06.720 --> 00:53:14.320
family in their camp, but things would not go&nbsp;
according to the young lovers’ plan. On their

00:53:14.320 --> 00:53:21.080
fateful journey home, they passed through the&nbsp;
lands of a warrior named Yesugei, the leader of a

00:53:21.080 --> 00:53:29.160
small Mongol band on the great Onon River. Yesugei&nbsp;
had once been a powerful leader, but had recently

00:53:29.160 --> 00:53:37.080
fallen on tough times. That day, he was out hunting&nbsp;
with his hawk when he saw the marriage procession

00:53:37.080 --> 00:53:46.640
pass by, and caught sight of the beautiful face&nbsp;
of Oelun. Yesugei already had a wife, but upon seeing

00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:54.360
Oelun, he became overcome with desire for her, and&nbsp;
as a Mongol warrior, he was used to taking what he

00:53:54.360 --> 00:54:01.960
desired. He rode back to his camp and gathered his&nbsp;
two brothers, and together they chased after the

00:54:01.960 --> 00:54:09.880
wedding party with murder in their hearts. When&nbsp;
Oelun and her husband saw the warrior brothers

00:54:09.880 --> 00:54:16.840
bearing down on them, she begged her husband to&nbsp;
flee and save his life, as The Secret History

00:54:16.840 --> 00:54:28.080
recalls. His bride, Madame Oelun, said to him, “You;&nbsp;
have you understood what those three men are

00:54:28.080 --> 00:54:35.440
about? Their looks say they want your life. As&nbsp;
long as you have your life, at least, you will

00:54:35.440 --> 00:54:46.640
find a woman to wed. Save your life.”&nbsp;
Chiledu listened to her pleas and fled across

00:54:46.640 --> 00:54:56.320
the grasslands, leaving Oelun to be captured. The&nbsp;
two of them would never see each other again.

00:54:57.320 --> 00:55:02.880
The three riders chased him from behind&nbsp;
over seven ridges until they drove him

00:55:02.880 --> 00:55:10.200
off. They came back, and Yesugei took Madame&nbsp;
Oelun by the tether, and she wailed in a

00:55:10.200 --> 00:55:16.960
great voice. She wailed until the Onon River&nbsp;
echoed it and the wooded valley rang with it.

00:55:16.960 --> 00:55:28.120
We don't know what happened to Oelun's husband,&nbsp;
Chiledu, but it seems he never made any attempt

00:55:28.120 --> 00:55:34.400
to recapture her. In the harsh world of the&nbsp;
steppe, a man only had rights to what he could

00:55:34.400 --> 00:55:43.720
defend, and Oelun was now no longer considered&nbsp;
his wife. As for Oelun, her heartbreak must have

00:55:43.720 --> 00:55:49.600
been overwhelming, but she seems to have&nbsp;
accepted her fate and settled into the

00:55:49.600 --> 00:55:56.440
new life that Yesugei had forced upon her at the&nbsp;
edge of the mountains and the great Siberian

00:55:56.440 --> 00:56:05.600
forest. Here, she would have to be tough to survive.&nbsp;
Yesugei already had a wife, and by then, this woman

00:56:05.600 --> 00:56:13.880
had borne him a son named Begter. Soon, Oelun too&nbsp;
became pregnant, and gave Yesugei their first

00:56:13.880 --> 00:56:21.720
child together. This child was a boy, and it said&nbsp;
that when he came screaming into the world, he

00:56:21.720 --> 00:56:31.520
was clutching a tiny but fearsome omen in his&nbsp;
little hand. When Madame Oelun was big

00:56:31.520 --> 00:56:39.800
with child, just then, when they were at Deli-un
Boldak on the Onon River, he was born. When

00:56:39.800 --> 00:56:48.720
he was born, he was born clutching a clot of&nbsp;
blood in his right hand, the size of a knuckle

00:56:48.720 --> 00:56:59.440
bone. To the Mongols, this was&nbsp;
an unmistakable sign that the boy would

00:56:59.440 --> 00:57:09.040
grow up to be a warrior. The year was around&nbsp;
1162; in the Chinese calendar, the Year of the

00:57:09.040 --> 00:57:24.400
Horse. At the time, the Mongols were at war with&nbsp;
another much more powerful steppe people, the

00:57:24.400 --> 00:57:31.360
Tartars, who lived closer to the border with&nbsp;
Northern China. Yesugei had recently captured a

00:57:31.360 --> 00:57:39.000
Tatar warrior named Temujin Uge in battle, and in&nbsp;
celebration of this feat, he decided to name the

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:48.200
new baby boy after his captured enemy. The name&nbsp;
Temujin likely meant blacksmith or iron worker, but

00:57:48.200 --> 00:57:56.120
in time it would come to gain a different&nbsp;
association; the iron one, or the man of iron.

00:57:56.880 --> 00:58:04.320
This captured man may even have been executed&nbsp;
at the naming ceremony, and his strength ritually

00:58:04.320 --> 00:58:13.800
given to the new baby boy. From this bloody&nbsp;
beginning, Temujin's childhood was a tough one,

00:58:13.800 --> 00:58:21.520
but it forged him into the man he would become.&nbsp;
Living at Yesugei's camp on the banks of the Onon

00:58:21.520 --> 00:58:29.040
River, he would have learned to hunt and fish, and&nbsp;
of course, how to ride a horse from a young age. One

00:58:29.040 --> 00:58:36.960
Chinese writer describes the life of a steppe child.&nbsp;
Even three-year-old toddlers are secured to the

00:58:36.960 --> 00:58:41.880
saddle with rope, and given something to grasp&nbsp;
with their hands so they can follow along as

00:58:41.880 --> 00:58:49.240
the rest dash about on horseback. In their fourth&nbsp;
and fifth years, they carry under one arm a small

00:58:49.240 --> 00:58:56.240
bow and short arrows, and when grown, they occupy&nbsp;
themselves during all four seasons with hunting

00:58:56.240 --> 00:59:06.440
game. Hunting on the steppe was done using a&nbsp;
system known as the nerge or noose, and these

00:59:06.440 --> 00:59:12.600
grand hunts would take place every year and&nbsp;
involve large numbers of different families

00:59:12.600 --> 00:59:19.280
and kin groups. Every Mongol learned from a&nbsp;
young age how to work together with other

00:59:19.280 --> 00:59:26.320
riders across a vast distance, encircling a&nbsp;
huge area of land, and driving all the wild

00:59:26.320 --> 00:59:33.760
animals within it into the center of their ring.&nbsp;
Then the noose tightened. They would drive the

00:59:33.760 --> 00:59:40.720
animals closer and closer together until there&nbsp;
was nowhere left to run. Then they would begin to

00:59:40.720 --> 00:59:49.800
fire hundreds of arrows into the mass of terrified&nbsp;
prey. Yesugei would have taught his young sons this

00:59:49.800 --> 00:59:58.360
skill from a young age, but Temujin's relationship&nbsp;
with his kidnapper of a father may have been

00:59:58.360 --> 01:00:07.920
a strained one. Yesugei already had an oldest son&nbsp;
by another woman, the boy named Begter, and Begter seems

01:00:07.920 --> 01:00:14.880
to have enjoyed reminding Temujin of his place.&nbsp;
When Temujin was nine years old, his father clearly

01:00:14.880 --> 01:00:21.640
worried about the divisions in his family. He&nbsp;
decided to take the young boy to find a wife

01:00:21.640 --> 01:00:29.720
of his own. They traveled out together and&nbsp;
met with the ruler of a nearby clan, who was

01:00:29.720 --> 01:00:38.120
also something of a shaman. He told Yesugei that the&nbsp;
boy who rode beside him was destined for great

01:00:38.120 --> 01:00:49.960
things. This boy of yours is a boy with&nbsp;
flame in his eyes and fire in his face.

01:00:49.960 --> 01:00:56.360
Last night I dreamt a dream; a white falcon&nbsp;
flew towards me clutching the sun and the moon,

01:00:56.360 --> 01:01:03.320
and alighted on my hand. This dream of mine was&nbsp;
showing me that you would come leading this boy of

01:01:03.320 --> 01:01:18.480
yours. The chief gave the young boy the&nbsp;
hand of one of his daughters, a girl named

01:01:18.480 --> 01:01:25.920
Borte. She was a year older than him, and at&nbsp;
the first sight of her, Temujin fell in love,

01:01:26.600 --> 01:01:34.680
a love that would never leave him. On his way home,&nbsp;
his father Yesugei must have been satisfied. He had

01:01:34.680 --> 01:01:42.320
found a good wife for his young son, and could now&nbsp;
head home to a family made at peace. But fate would

01:01:42.320 --> 01:01:51.520
conspire against him. That night, he stopped at a&nbsp;
camp belonging to some Tartar men. By this time, the

01:01:51.520 --> 01:01:59.040
Tartars and the Mongols were no longer at war, but&nbsp;
they were still bitter rivals. The customs on the

01:01:59.040 --> 01:02:04.840
steppe stated that whenever someone stopped at your&nbsp;
camp, you were required to set your differences

01:02:04.840 --> 01:02:12.880
aside and offer them hospitality, but these&nbsp;
Tartars had other ideas, as The Secret History

01:02:12.880 --> 01:02:24.200
accounts. Remembering their early grudge, they&nbsp;
plotted murder and mixed in poison for him.

01:02:24.200 --> 01:02:30.640
Feeling sick on the way, he went for three&nbsp;
days and arrived at his ger, and felt worse.

01:02:30.640 --> 01:02:40.800
Yesugei said, “My insides feel sick. I fell victim to a&nbsp;
plot, and now I feel sick inside.” Having spoken, he

01:02:40.800 --> 01:02:56.520
died. Hearing of this treachery from a&nbsp;
rider sent by his dying father, Temujin rode hard

01:02:56.520 --> 01:03:02.080
across the steppe, heading home to be with&nbsp;
his mother, and left his betrothed, Borte,

01:03:02.080 --> 01:03:11.600
behind. The death of Yesugei left this vulnerable&nbsp;
family exposed and alone in the cruel world of

01:03:11.600 --> 01:03:19.480
steppe politics. Yesugei's clan had been a mixture&nbsp;
of different peoples, including families of

01:03:19.480 --> 01:03:26.320
Mongols known as the Borjigin and Tayichyut, and
they had little holding them together other than

01:03:26.320 --> 01:03:34.720
Yesugei's leadership. Now they split into separate&nbsp;
parts and departed in all directions, and none

01:03:34.720 --> 01:03:42.720
of them had any room for a widowed woman and&nbsp;
her hungry children. They left Oelun and her

01:03:42.720 --> 01:03:51.200
children behind, alone, destitute, and starving on&nbsp;
the banks of the Onon River, as The Secret History

01:03:51.200 --> 01:04:00.280
records. The Tayichyut brethren moved camp&nbsp;
down along the Onon River to leave behind

01:04:00.280 --> 01:04:06.040
on the range Madame Oelun the widow, the&nbsp;
little ones and boys, the mothers and

01:04:06.040 --> 01:04:17.200
children. The Tayichyut took their livestock, their goats&nbsp;
and their sheep, and left them with only the few

01:04:17.200 --> 01:04:26.000
horses they owned. This was practically a death&nbsp;
sentence. When winter came to the steppe, this

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:37.520
feeble group would no doubt freeze and run out&nbsp;
of food. But remarkably, that's not what happened.

01:04:37.520 --> 01:04:48.320
That's because Oelun refused to let her children&nbsp;
starve. Madame Oelun, born both womanly and

01:04:48.320 --> 01:04:56.920
wise, finding food for her small boys, fixing up her&nbsp;
flowing skirts, flying up and down the Onon River's

01:04:56.920 --> 01:05:04.880
flood, finding wild fruits, crab apples, and cherries,&nbsp;
filled she the night and day their famished

01:05:04.880 --> 01:05:14.480
throats. They were well raised on wild garlic&nbsp;
and onion, lily bulbs, leeks, and onion

01:05:14.480 --> 01:05:23.640
leaves. At night, while they ate these meager foods,&nbsp;
she told them the stories of her ancestors, the

01:05:23.640 --> 01:05:28.600
stories that had been passed down to her&nbsp;
from her parents, the stories of Alan

01:05:28.600 --> 01:05:36.320
the Beautiful and her five unruly sons, and the&nbsp;
parable of the five arrows that could not be

01:05:36.320 --> 01:05:44.120
broken so long as they stayed together. At first,&nbsp;
the boys seem to have taken these lessons to

01:05:48.660 --> 01:06:00.480
heart. Saying to each other, we must feed our mother,&nbsp;
they sat on Mother Onon's muddy banks and mastered

01:06:00.480 --> 01:06:08.720
metal hooks and lures, catching maimed and motley fish.&nbsp;
Turning needles into hooks, they hooked trout and

01:06:08.720 --> 01:06:15.680
little white fish. They sifted pools for silver&nbsp;
minnows, and so they served back their mother's

01:06:15.680 --> 01:06:30.360
love. It was around this time that Temujin&nbsp;
met another boy of the same age, whose family

01:06:30.360 --> 01:06:39.080
would often camp near to their own settlement.&nbsp;
This boy's name was Jamuka. The two boys hunted

01:06:39.080 --> 01:06:44.720
and fished together, and became good friends.&nbsp;
In fact, they became so close that they swore

01:06:44.720 --> 01:06:52.080
to enter into that bond of chosen kinship, and&nbsp;
became what the Mongols called anda, a kind of

01:06:52.080 --> 01:06:58.800
blood brother. They most likely spilled a drop&nbsp;
of their blood into a cup of fermented mare's

01:06:58.800 --> 01:07:06.000
milk and both drank from it, swearing an oath&nbsp;
of eternal brotherhood, and always to fight on

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:13.280
one another's behalf. It must have been hard&nbsp;
to imagine at the time watching these two

01:07:13.280 --> 01:07:21.080
skinny boys playing in the hills or at games of&nbsp;
knucklebones beside the great river, but one day

01:07:21.080 --> 01:07:27.520
they would fight one another in a bitter civil&nbsp;
war over who would rule all the people of the

01:07:27.520 --> 01:07:42.800
Mongols. Soon, winter came to the&nbsp;
steppe. Snow fell, and the Onon River

01:07:42.800 --> 01:07:49.760
froze solid. The now reduced family&nbsp;
must have come close to death, but

01:07:49.760 --> 01:07:55.440
finally spring arrived on the steppe,&nbsp;
and the ice on the grasslands thawed.

01:07:58.600 --> 01:08:07.080
But by this time, all was not well among this&nbsp;
lonely family. Despite their mother's stories

01:08:07.080 --> 01:08:14.280
warning them to stay united, a bitter rivalry&nbsp;
had always existed between Temujin and Yesugei's

01:08:14.280 --> 01:08:22.720
oldest son Begter, who had been born of another&nbsp;
mother. This rivalry would only grow bitterer

01:08:22.720 --> 01:08:31.520
as their situation worsened and hunger set&nbsp;
in. As the older and larger boy, Begter often

01:08:31.520 --> 01:08:38.560
took for himself the best of the fish and&nbsp;
birds that they caught, until eventually

01:08:38.560 --> 01:08:46.920
Temujin had had enough. He and his younger&nbsp;
brother Qasar soon plotted to kill their

01:08:46.920 --> 01:08:55.680
older brother. It wasn't just Begter's selfishness&nbsp;
that motivated this decision. With their father

01:08:55.680 --> 01:09:04.160
dead, their mother Oelun was an unmarried woman. As&nbsp;
a result, she was considered available for marriage,

01:09:04.160 --> 01:09:10.800
and though it might seem strange to us, the most&nbsp;
likely candidate may have been her young stepson,

01:09:10.800 --> 01:09:19.560
Begter. Traveling to Mongolia a century later,&nbsp;
the Venetian explorer Marco Polo noted this

01:09:19.560 --> 01:09:29.880
peculiarity of Mongol marriage laws. The marriage&nbsp;
customs of Tartars are as follows; any man may take

01:09:29.880 --> 01:09:37.800
a hundred wives if he so please and if he be able&nbsp;
to keep them. But the first wife is ever held most

01:09:37.800 --> 01:09:46.040
in honor and as the most legitimate. They may marry&nbsp;
their cousins, and if a father dies, his son may

01:09:46.040 --> 01:09:55.480
take any of the wives, his mother always excepted.&nbsp;
That is to say, the eldest son may do this, but

01:09:55.480 --> 01:10:05.080
no other. If Begter married Oelun, he would&nbsp;
secure his position as the undisputed head

01:10:05.080 --> 01:10:13.880
of the family. Temujin and Qasar were determined&nbsp;
not to let that happen. The pair of them chose

01:10:13.880 --> 01:10:20.240
their moment carefully. They took their bows&nbsp;
and crept up on Begter while he sat on the hill,

01:10:20.240 --> 01:10:26.880
drawing their bowstrings taught. When he saw&nbsp;
them, he briefly pleaded for his his life, but

01:10:26.880 --> 01:10:33.760
they didn't listen. Temujin and Qasar shot him&nbsp;
with their arrows, and left his body to lie in

01:10:33.760 --> 01:10:41.760
the long grass of the steppe. When they returned to&nbsp;
their tent, their mother saw the murder in their

01:10:41.760 --> 01:10:57.320
eyes. When they came back into the ger, the&nbsp;
Madame Mother understood it all from

01:10:57.320 --> 01:11:06.560
the faces of her two children. “Murderers!” She&nbsp;
shouted. “When bursting out from my hot womb, he

01:11:06.560 --> 01:11:12.640
wielded in his hand a black blood clot.&nbsp;
Like a hound that devours its own, like

01:11:12.640 --> 01:11:18.760
a panther that pounces against a cliff, like a&nbsp;
lion that cannot restrain its wrath, like

01:11:18.760 --> 01:11:25.280
a wolf that stalks in the whirling&nbsp;
blizzard, you killed your own brother.”

01:11:25.280 --> 01:11:39.760
When summer came again that year, their&nbsp;
old tribe, the Tayichyut, returned, following their

01:11:39.760 --> 01:11:45.680
seasonal route as always. They must have&nbsp;
expected to find nothing but a collection

01:11:45.680 --> 01:11:50.960
of whitened bones littering the steppe, where&nbsp;
they had left the family of Oelun and her

01:11:50.960 --> 01:11:57.720
children to die, but they were astonished and&nbsp;
a little concerned to find these young men

01:11:57.720 --> 01:12:06.040
and their mother still living by the side of&nbsp;
the river. Somehow, they had clung to life. This

01:12:06.040 --> 01:12:13.240
could turn out to be a problem for the Tayichyut.&nbsp;
These boys were becoming stronger each year,

01:12:13.240 --> 01:12:19.920
and maybe one day they would be strong enough&nbsp;
to take revenge for abandoning them. Perhaps

01:12:19.920 --> 01:12:27.360
when the Tayichyut heard of Temujin's killing of Begter,&nbsp;
they used this as an excuse to hunt him down as

01:12:27.360 --> 01:12:36.280
an outlaw. Temujin ran, and they chased him high up&nbsp;
into the mountains. Fleeing for his life, he made

01:12:36.280 --> 01:12:44.040
for one peak in particular that held a great&nbsp;
significance, the sacred mountain named Burkan 

01:12:44.040 --> 01:12:54.760
Khaldun. Among the rocky slopes strewn with scree,&nbsp;
there grow forests of Siberian larch and pine,

01:12:54.760 --> 01:13:01.640
where it was possible for him to hide. For&nbsp;
a while, he evaded them among the forest's

01:13:01.640 --> 01:13:10.120
shady depths, but the Tayichyut posted guards in a&nbsp;
wide circle and slowly closed the net around

01:13:10.120 --> 01:13:21.240
him. Eventually they cornered him and dragged&nbsp;
him back to their camp as a prisoner.

01:13:21.240 --> 01:13:28.520
At first, the Tayichyut planned to execute Temujin, but&nbsp;
but they soon changed their minds. A young, strong

01:13:28.520 --> 01:13:34.920
boy like him would make a good worker, and so, they&nbsp;
brought the young man back to live as a slave in

01:13:34.920 --> 01:13:42.920
their camp. To humiliate him, they forced him to&nbsp;
wear a heavy wooden board around his neck. This

01:13:42.920 --> 01:13:51.920
prevented him from eating or sleeping comfortably,&nbsp;
and made his status as a slave known to everyone.

01:13:51.920 --> 01:13:58.480
It's not known how long he was held captive here,&nbsp;
but all that time, Temujin must have been thinking of

01:13:58.480 --> 01:14:07.560
his bride, Borte, and dreaming that they would one&nbsp;
day be reunited. Eventually he saw his chance to

01:14:07.560 --> 01:14:23.360
escape. One night, the Tayichyut feasted on the red disk&nbsp;
day, the 16th of the first moon of summer, on the

01:14:23.360 --> 01:14:32.600
banks of the Onon as the sun went down. A feeble youth&nbsp;
brought him to that feast. As the fellows at the

01:14:32.600 --> 01:14:38.400
feast were being sent away, he grabbed the wooden&nbsp;
board away from the feeble boy, struck him on the

01:14:38.400 --> 01:14:45.800
head once with it, and ran. He lay down on his&nbsp;
back on the river's edge, the moonlight bright as

01:14:45.800 --> 01:15:00.600
day. With the Tayichyut guards combing the steppe&nbsp;
for him, Temujin saw only one chance to escape.

01:15:00.600 --> 01:15:07.760
He leapt into the icy river, and the heavy&nbsp;
wooden board acted as a flotation device.

01:15:07.760 --> 01:15:13.240
When he climbed out of the water some way&nbsp;
downstream, he found a family of herdsmen

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:18.760
who helped him to remove the lock on the heavy&nbsp;
piece of wood, and he limped back home to his

01:15:18.760 --> 01:15:29.800
family. Oelun and his siblings must have been&nbsp;
overjoyed to see him when he returned, but

01:15:29.800 --> 01:15:36.040
he had other things on his mind. The first&nbsp;
thing he did when he returned was to ride

01:15:36.040 --> 01:15:42.520
out to claim his bride, Borte. He must have&nbsp;
feared the worst, that her father had gone

01:15:42.520 --> 01:15:48.200
back on his word and given her to someone else,
but perhaps the old shaman had remembered his

01:15:48.200 --> 01:15:55.760
vision and the fire he had seen in the eyes of&nbsp;
that young boy. All those years, he had kept his

01:15:55.760 --> 01:16:03.120
daughter for the man she was promised to. She&nbsp;
and Temujin were married. They had a daughter

01:16:03.120 --> 01:16:10.120
and lived together happily on the banks&nbsp;
of the Onon River, and that is where the

01:16:10.120 --> 01:16:17.280
story of Temujin might have ended; with a happy&nbsp;
family, with children and grandchildren, with

01:16:17.280 --> 01:16:24.920
a quiet death in a ger tent in the middle&nbsp;
of the steppe, and we would never know his name.

01:16:26.120 --> 01:16:37.280
But history had other plans, and the steppe was no&nbsp;
place for a quiet life. One day, a raiding party of

01:16:37.280 --> 01:16:44.240
the northern forest people known as the Merkit&nbsp;
swept down on their camp while Temujin was out

01:16:44.240 --> 01:16:54.840
hunting. This raid was a perfect example of the&nbsp;
tangled world of steppe rivalries and blood feuds,

01:16:55.400 --> 01:17:01.920
for in fact, these men were the brothers of&nbsp;
Chiledu, the man that Temujin's mother Oelun had

01:17:01.920 --> 01:17:09.480
once married, and who had lost his wife to&nbsp;
Yesugei. With Yesugei dead, these brothers of Chiledu

01:17:09.480 --> 01:17:16.080
were taking their revenge on the man's son,&nbsp;
instead. They burned his tents and took away

01:17:16.080 --> 01:17:22.360
his animals and what possessions he had,&nbsp;
and just as Yesugei had once stolen Oelun,

01:17:22.360 --> 01:17:28.200
these Merkit raiders now stole his wife,&nbsp;
Borte, away, and retreated with her back

01:17:28.200 --> 01:17:36.840
to the cover of the Siberian forests. With his&nbsp;
small band, Temujin had little hope of reclaiming

01:17:36.840 --> 01:17:46.320
her. But he did have one chance; that&nbsp;
was to reach out to the man who had

01:17:46.320 --> 01:17:51.680
once been his childhood friend on&nbsp;
the banks of the Onon River, a man

01:17:51.680 --> 01:17:58.840
who was now a rising warrior in the nearby&nbsp;
clan of the Kereyid, his anda blood brother,

01:17:58.840 --> 01:18:07.920
Jamuka. When Jamuka saw his old friend&nbsp;
after so many years, he was overjoyed, but

01:18:07.920 --> 01:18:14.240
he must have seen the pain in Temujin's&nbsp;
face, and when Temujin told him what had

01:18:14.240 --> 01:18:21.600
happened, Jamuka flew into a rage. The Secret&nbsp;
History records him giving the following

01:18:21.600 --> 01:18:24.760
promise.

01:18:24.760 --> 01:18:34.680
A black leather war drum with its&nbsp;
booming bellow I have beaten. A steed with

01:18:34.680 --> 01:18:43.400
swift steps have I saddled. A steel shirt&nbsp;
have I worn. A solid spear have I seized. A

01:18:43.400 --> 01:18:50.320
stinging arrow on my string have I strung.&nbsp;
To slaughter all the savage Merkit, I set out.

01:18:54.760 --> 01:19:07.120
The lord that Jamuka served was a man named&nbsp;
Toghril Khan, the Khan of the Kereyid people, and he

01:19:07.120 --> 01:19:14.400
agreed to help Temujin get his wife back. They&nbsp;
spent that year building an army, and set out

01:19:14.400 --> 01:19:22.200
in the autumn with a host over 30,000 strong,&nbsp;
riding north into the hostile forests where the

01:19:22.200 --> 01:19:30.840
Merkit lived. They waited until nightfall, and&nbsp;
then, under cover of darkness, they swept down

01:19:30.840 --> 01:19:37.960
on the Merkit camp in a surprise attack.&nbsp;
The Secret History records what happens

01:19:37.960 --> 01:19:52.120
next. They swarmed in to seize his girls in&nbsp;
a sudden swoop. They plundered his kingdom

01:19:52.120 --> 01:19:58.960
mercilessly…as the Merkit folk fled down the&nbsp;
Selenge River in the night, as our soldiers

01:19:58.960 --> 01:20:05.240
dogged the heels of the fugitive Merit through&nbsp;
the night, plundering and looting, and as Temujin

01:20:05.240 --> 01:20:13.600
called out, “Borta! Borta!”, they met. Madame&nbsp;
Borta was there among the fugitives. She

01:20:13.600 --> 01:20:20.520
recognized Temujin's voice, got down from the wagon,&nbsp;
and ran towards him, and they hugged each other in

01:20:20.520 --> 01:20:24.680
welcome.

01:20:24.680 --> 01:20:40.800
There was only one complication; Temujin soon&nbsp;
found out that his wife Borte had become pregnant.

01:20:40.800 --> 01:20:48.080
Since she had been captured and forcibly married&nbsp;
to a Merkit lord, Temujin could never know whether

01:20:48.080 --> 01:20:56.520
the child was his. Perhaps for this reason, when his&nbsp;
firstborn son came into the world, Temujin gave

01:20:56.520 --> 01:21:05.800
him the name Jochi, which in Mongolian means guest,&nbsp;
perhaps alluding to the question of his fatherhood.

01:21:05.800 --> 01:21:13.600
But they all agreed to put the issue behind them,&nbsp;
and Temujin accepted Jochi the guest as his eldest

01:21:13.600 --> 01:21:24.240
son. After this experience, it was now clear to&nbsp;
Temujin that a life of peace was impossible on

01:21:24.240 --> 01:21:33.320
the steppe. For protection, he and his family joined&nbsp;
Jamuka's camp, and the pair of anda blood brothers

01:21:33.320 --> 01:21:41.360
rode together as equals for a year and a half.
They hunted and fought together, and perhaps

01:21:41.360 --> 01:21:49.160
even played knucklebones together the way they&nbsp;
had as boys. Jamuka also introduced Temujin to his

01:21:49.160 --> 01:21:57.920
lord and patron, the ruler of the Kereyid clan, the&nbsp;
man named Toghril Khan. This time would have been crucial

01:21:57.920 --> 01:22:06.840
for Temujin. During his upbringing, he had known only&nbsp;
hardship and poverty, whereas Jamuka had become an

01:22:06.840 --> 01:22:16.920
experienced warrior and leader. He must have taught&nbsp;
Temujin all he knew. For a while, everything seemed

01:22:16.920 --> 01:22:24.520
to be going well, but eventually Temujin began to&nbsp;
detect a hint of resentment from his blood brother,

01:22:24.520 --> 01:22:34.880
perhaps even a glimmer of contempt. One day,&nbsp;
Jamuka ordered him to stay home and protect the

01:22:34.880 --> 01:22:43.680
clan's sheep herds, a clear sign that things were&nbsp;
beginning to sour between these old friends. The

01:22:43.680 --> 01:22:51.080
two quarreled, and Temujin's wife Borte advised&nbsp;
him to leave his friend and start out on his own.

01:22:54.480 --> 01:23:06.640
Madame Borta said, “Jamuka Anda is said&nbsp;
to be a person who easily gets

01:23:06.640 --> 01:23:11.160
tired of things. Now the time has&nbsp;
come that he has become tired of

01:23:11.160 --> 01:23:16.760
us. Let us not pitch camp. Let us make a&nbsp;
clean break and move away through the

01:23:16.760 --> 01:23:31.040
night.” With a heavy heart, Temujin agreed, and he&nbsp;
and his family prepared to leave. He would now

01:23:31.040 --> 01:23:38.360
be starting again from the beginning, alone on&nbsp;
the steppe. He expected to leave with just his

01:23:38.360 --> 01:23:46.520
wife and his small children, but to his surprise,&nbsp;
he had gained a great deal of popularity among

01:23:46.520 --> 01:23:54.480
Jamuka's people. In fact, when Temujin made to&nbsp;
leave Jamuka's camp, half of his blood brother’s

01:23:54.480 --> 01:24:04.040
followers asked to go with him. The loyalty that&nbsp;
Temujin clearly inspired was partly due to his

01:24:04.040 --> 01:24:12.080
reputation for generosity. When dividing up the&nbsp;
loot from a successful raid, steppe peoples had

01:24:12.080 --> 01:24:18.600
for thousands of years adhered to an ancient&nbsp;
system by which the elites and nobles took

01:24:18.600 --> 01:24:24.640
all the best plunder for themselves, and then&nbsp;
divided the rest among the other men as they

01:24:24.640 --> 01:24:32.560
saw fit. Common people were usually left out of this&nbsp;
system. In the harsh world of the steppe, strength

01:24:32.560 --> 01:24:40.760
was everything, and the strong took the lion's&nbsp;
share. But Temujin appears to have been different.

01:24:40.760 --> 01:24:46.720
He had grown up on the freezing bank of the Onon&nbsp;
River with his siblings, and learned to share

01:24:46.720 --> 01:24:53.960
everything in common. He had once killed his older&nbsp;
brother Begter partly for taking the best food for

01:24:53.960 --> 01:25:01.120
himself, and since then must have harbored a&nbsp;
distaste for this ancient system, and perhaps he

01:25:01.120 --> 01:25:09.000
had learned that inspiring loyalty in those around&nbsp;
him was worth any amount of gold or any number of

01:25:09.000 --> 01:25:21.480
horses. As a result, he pioneered a new and&nbsp;
somewhat radical system in the world of

01:25:21.480 --> 01:25:28.720
the steppe. In his party, loot would be shared&nbsp;
according to merit, and those who did well in

01:25:28.720 --> 01:25:35.040
battle were given a greater share, even&nbsp;
if they were just common people. Among

01:25:35.040 --> 01:25:41.760
his followers, he also at times introduced a&nbsp;
kind of insurance policy, decreeing that any

01:25:41.760 --> 01:25:46.840
soldier who was killed in battle would have&nbsp;
their share of the loot given to their widow

01:25:46.840 --> 01:25:54.440
and orphaned children, a policy perhaps inspired&nbsp;
by his own experience of losing his father and

01:25:54.440 --> 01:26:03.080
being plunged into poverty as a child. A certain&nbsp;
amount of loot was also distributed to the elderly

01:26:03.080 --> 01:26:12.160
and disabled. All of this meant that when he left&nbsp;
Jamuka's camp, a number of men wanted to follow him,

01:26:12.160 --> 01:26:18.280
but in taking half of his blood brother’s&nbsp;
people, Temujin had also gained a powerful

01:26:18.280 --> 01:26:29.040
enemy. Throughout this time, the Mongols&nbsp;
were still a fractured and divided people,

01:26:29.040 --> 01:26:35.120
but now these two rival warriors both&nbsp;
desired to make themselves ruler over

01:26:35.120 --> 01:26:44.720
all the Mongols, a title that had long been&nbsp;
known as Khan. In the summer of 1189, Temujin

01:26:44.720 --> 01:26:54.240
decided to take his chance. He summoned a&nbsp;
meeting of the clans known as a kuriltai.

01:26:56.520 --> 01:27:04.960
A kuriltai was a riotous event, part political&nbsp;
rally and part festival. This one took place on the

01:27:04.960 --> 01:27:12.720
shores of a place on the steppe known as the Blue&nbsp;
Lake. Here, the air would be filled with the sound

01:27:12.720 --> 01:27:20.880
of horses, laughter, and perhaps the mesmerizing&nbsp;
sound of Mongolian throat singing, a unique vocal

01:27:20.880 --> 01:27:27.760
form in which the singers summon sound from deep&nbsp;
in their larynx with such precision that they

01:27:27.760 --> 01:27:37.400
are able to sing two notes at once. The kuriltai&nbsp;
would have included games and feasts, the so-called

01:27:37.400 --> 01:27:45.440
three manly pursuits of horse races, wrestling, and&nbsp;
archery tournaments, and of course, the consumption

01:27:45.440 --> 01:27:54.440
of vast quantities of alcohol. It's likely&nbsp;
the attendants would have drunk airag or kumis,

01:27:54.440 --> 01:28:01.760
the alcoholic drink made from fermented&nbsp;
mare's milk. One Chinese diplomat named Zhao

01:28:01.760 --> 01:28:09.160
Gong, who attended a Mongol feast in the early&nbsp;
1220s, even records a kind of Mongol drinking

01:28:09.160 --> 01:28:18.400
game. They do not end their banqueting until&nbsp;
everyone is roaring drunk. Every time they drink

01:28:18.400 --> 01:28:26.760
wine, it is their custom that those who sit next to&nbsp;
each other should, after tasting, exchange cups. If

01:28:26.760 --> 01:28:33.480
one's counterpart holds the cup with one hand, it&nbsp;
means that I must taste a mouthful, and only then

01:28:33.480 --> 01:28:41.400
will he dare to drink. If he holds the cup in both&nbsp;
hands, then he wishes to switch cups with me. Then I

01:28:41.400 --> 01:28:49.320
have to drink his wine to the bottom and pour wine&nbsp;
to toast him. This made it very easy to get drunk.

01:28:49.320 --> 01:28:57.320
Whenever they see a foreign guest talk uproariously,
make noise, and act rudely in a drunken state, or else

01:28:57.320 --> 01:29:05.080
vomit or fall asleep, then they are very happy and&nbsp;
say, “The guest gets drunk, so his heart is one with

01:29:05.080 --> 01:29:14.880
ours!” But despite the revelry, the kuriltai&nbsp;
had a very serious purpose. By holding this

01:29:14.880 --> 01:29:23.000
gathering of the clans, Temujin was declaring&nbsp;
his intention to become Khan of the Mongols.

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:29.680
This was not a particularly prestigious title.&nbsp;
The Mongols were a weak and divided people, and

01:29:29.680 --> 01:29:35.840
any Khan who led them would still pay tribute&nbsp;
to the much more powerful Toghril Khan of the

01:29:35.840 --> 01:29:42.960
Kereyeits. But it was still a clear declaration of&nbsp;
war against the more likely claimant to the

01:29:42.960 --> 01:29:54.040
title and the man who commanded the support of&nbsp;
most Mongol nobles, his own blood brother, Jamuka.

01:29:54.680 --> 01:30:01.680
When Jamuka heard news about this kuriltai,&nbsp;&nbsp;
he must have been enraged. Clashes between

01:30:01.680 --> 01:30:09.120
the two men's followers intensified until one&nbsp;
day, one of Jamuka's relatives was killed in

01:30:09.120 --> 01:30:16.880
a castle raid. This was the excuse he&nbsp;
was looking for, to finally go to war

01:30:16.880 --> 01:30:23.960
and crush his blood brother Temujin.&nbsp;
The two sides gathered their forces.

01:30:27.760 --> 01:30:35.800
Temujin would finally meet his blood brother in&nbsp;
battle at a place called Dalan-baljut. The Mongol

01:30:35.800 --> 01:30:41.680
horsemen would have wheeled around each other in&nbsp;
great thundering packs, hailing one another with

01:30:41.680 --> 01:30:49.120
arrows before closing in and clashing with their&nbsp;
long lances. We can imagine the thundering of the

01:30:49.120 --> 01:30:56.480
hooves, the cries of the dying men and horses, the&nbsp;
whoops and battle cries, and the angry buzzing of

01:30:56.480 --> 01:31:04.920
arrows through the air. But here, Jamuka's greater&nbsp;
experience and years of warrior training easily

01:31:04.920 --> 01:31:13.800
overpowered the inexperienced Temujin. The&nbsp;
Secret History reports this loss in few

01:31:13.800 --> 01:31:26.720
words. They formed up into three units;&nbsp;
rode against Jamuka. He was forced

01:31:26.720 --> 01:31:30.720
back then by Jamuka, and escaped&nbsp;
into the Jerene Gorge on the Onon

01:31:30.720 --> 01:31:45.320
River. With Temujin defeated, the wrath of Jamuka&nbsp;
was terrible. In retribution for siding with

01:31:45.320 --> 01:31:52.720
the upstart, Jamuka ordered that 70 princes&nbsp;
of the Chinoa clan be boiled alive in great

01:31:52.720 --> 01:32:01.360
iron cauldrons. One leader's head was cut off, and&nbsp;
Jamuka tied it to his horse's tail and dragged

01:32:01.360 --> 01:32:11.560
it behind him as he rode. Temujin's situation was&nbsp;
now worse than ever. He was now an outlaw, and

01:32:11.560 --> 01:32:18.680
fled for his life with the riders of Jamuka&nbsp;
hot on his heels. He would not return to the

01:32:18.680 --> 01:32:27.240
steppe for another ten years, and those years are a&nbsp;
gap in his biography. But some historians think

01:32:27.240 --> 01:32:33.240
it likely that he went south to the lands&nbsp;
that lay across the great expanse of the Gobi

01:32:33.240 --> 01:32:53.840
Desert, a domain of large wealthy cities, artists,&nbsp;
merchants, poets, and emperors, the lands of China.

01:32:58.840 --> 01:33:08.040
China at the end of the 12th century was a divided&nbsp;
land. Since the days of the first emperors of the

01:33:08.040 --> 01:33:14.880
Qin and Han Dynasty, the settled people who lived&nbsp;
in the floodplains around the Yangtse and Yellow

01:33:14.880 --> 01:33:22.600
Rivers had fought bitterly with the nomadic horse-&nbsp;
riding peoples of the steppe, and since that time,

01:33:22.600 --> 01:33:29.000
China's emperors had built numerous defenses on&nbsp;
their northern border that would become known as

01:33:29.000 --> 01:33:37.080
the Great Wall. In the nearly ten centuries since&nbsp;
the time of the Han Dynasty, the Tang were the

01:33:37.080 --> 01:33:43.960
first to unite the area of the central Chinese&nbsp;
plains, but after the collapse of that dynasty, a

01:33:43.960 --> 01:33:52.000
period of chaos and dissolution followed known&nbsp;
as the Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period.

01:33:52.000 --> 01:34:01.480
Eventually, around the year 1000, the plains of&nbsp;
China united once more under the Song Dynasty. The

01:34:01.480 --> 01:34:08.080
Song were ethnically Han Chinese, the majority&nbsp;
ethnic group of China, and under their reign, the

01:34:08.080 --> 01:34:14.400
people of the central plains had flourished.&nbsp;
Over the next 100 years, China's population

01:34:14.400 --> 01:34:22.080
would double, so that by the year 1100, more than&nbsp;
100 million people, or one-third of the planet's

01:34:22.080 --> 01:34:29.840
entire human population, could be found there.&nbsp;
China at this time was the undisputed center of

01:34:29.840 --> 01:34:40.000
the world, and technologically the most advanced&nbsp;
civilization on Earth. But in the 1120s, disaster

01:34:40.000 --> 01:34:50.480
struck. The Jurchen were a people from the oak&nbsp;
and pine forests of Manchuria, near the border

01:34:50.480 --> 01:34:58.680
with Korea, where Siberian tigers were known to&nbsp;
roam, and to the Chinese in the south, these Jurchen

01:34:58.680 --> 01:35:06.840
were considered barbarians. They were mostly&nbsp;
not nomadic and lived in villages, but they

01:35:06.840 --> 01:35:13.200
were a horse-rearing people, and they rode and&nbsp;
fought as horse archers in much the same way

01:35:13.200 --> 01:35:20.760
as the Mongols. Once subservient to another&nbsp;
Manchurian people known as the Khitan, they

01:35:20.760 --> 01:35:26.320
had overthrown their former masters and now&nbsp;
swept across Northern China in a tide of

01:35:26.320 --> 01:35:35.960
conquest. The Chinese Song Dynasty, weakened by&nbsp;
internal divisions and taken by surprise, could

01:35:35.960 --> 01:35:45.720
do little to stop them. In a disaster that the Song&nbsp;
would rue for centuries, Jurchen horsemen swept south

01:35:45.720 --> 01:35:52.400
and seized the lands around the northern Yellow&nbsp;
River, pushing south, and even capturing the former

01:35:52.400 --> 01:36:01.800
Song capital of Kaifeng. From this point onwards, the&nbsp;
lands of Northern China would be ruled by these

01:36:01.800 --> 01:36:08.240
Jurchen, and their new emperor would crown himself&nbsp;
with a title that elevated him above the other

01:36:08.240 --> 01:36:17.680
peoples of the steppe. He was now the Golden Khan,&nbsp;
and his empire would be known as the Jin or Golden

01:36:17.680 --> 01:36:26.840
Empire. The Jurchen Jin Dynasty of Northern China&nbsp;
was what has been called a conquest dynasty; that

01:36:26.840 --> 01:36:34.640
is one founded by outside invaders, but throughout&nbsp;
Chinese history, these kinds of conquerors had

01:36:34.640 --> 01:36:42.440
always learned that military might was not the&nbsp;
only kind of power, that culture too had its own

01:36:42.440 --> 01:36:50.320
kind of force. Over time, the founders of these&nbsp;
conquest dynasties often adopted the Chinese

01:36:50.320 --> 01:36:58.040
language, began to live by Confucian ideals and&nbsp;
dress in Chinese clothes, intermarry with the locals,

01:36:58.040 --> 01:37:06.960
and gradually become every bit as Chinese as the&nbsp;
Chinese. The Jurchen were no different. In fact, over

01:37:06.960 --> 01:37:12.600
the century that they ruled Northern China, they&nbsp;
adopted the Chinese language so enthusiastically

01:37:12.600 --> 01:37:20.480
that very few written texts in the Jurchen language&nbsp;
have survived. Just 30 years after their conquest,

01:37:20.480 --> 01:37:27.320
one Jin emperor known as the Prince of Hailing&nbsp;
even began writing Chinese poetry and drinking

01:37:27.320 --> 01:37:35.080
Chinese tea, something that his hardy forbears&nbsp;
would have mocked. But no matter how many Chinese

01:37:35.080 --> 01:37:41.520
manners or customs they adopted, the Jin would&nbsp;
always be considered outside barbarians by the

01:37:41.520 --> 01:37:49.160
Song Chinese in the south, who referred to them&nbsp;
as slaves and dog-sheep, and dreamed of one

01:37:49.160 --> 01:37:59.240
day retaking their lost lands and uniting China&nbsp;
once more. For the next two centuries, China would

01:37:59.240 --> 01:38:07.520
be divided into these two halves, the Chinese Song in&nbsp;
the rugged and tropical south, and the Jurchen Jin in

01:38:07.520 --> 01:38:14.360
the dry and arid north, with their border along the&nbsp;
Huai River, roughly halfway between the Yangtse and

01:38:14.360 --> 01:38:21.240
Yellow Rivers. There was almost constant warfare&nbsp;
between them as they seized forts and border towns

01:38:21.240 --> 01:38:28.280
from one another whenever the opportunity arose,&nbsp;
but neither side was ever able to gain the upper

01:38:28.280 --> 01:38:36.600
hand. Since they themselves had once swept out of&nbsp;
the wilderness and seized the cities of China, the

01:38:36.600 --> 01:38:43.840
Jurchen rulers of the Jin Dynasty knew all too&nbsp;
well how quickly a new threat could develop in

01:38:43.840 --> 01:38:51.520
those wild lands, and they were determined not&nbsp;
to be caught by surprise as the Song had been. As

01:38:51.520 --> 01:39:01.200
a result, the Jin operated a policy of using&nbsp;
nomads to fight nomads. On their frontier, the Jin

01:39:01.200 --> 01:39:09.960
Dynasty employed what were called juyin. These were&nbsp;
their border guards, vassals, and subject states,

01:39:09.960 --> 01:39:16.320
along with mercenaries, who they paid handsomely&nbsp;
to create a buffer zone between them and the other

01:39:16.320 --> 01:39:24.960
peoples of the north. These juyin border guards would&nbsp;
raid and plunder other steppe peoples whenever they

01:39:24.960 --> 01:39:33.720
became too powerful, and suppressed any chance of&nbsp;
a united power emerging in the Mongolian steppe, and

01:39:33.720 --> 01:39:40.680
when any one group of juyin themselves became&nbsp;
too powerful, the Jin would shift their support

01:39:40.680 --> 01:39:48.280
to a different people and bring them tumbling&nbsp;
down in turn. The southern Chinese writer Zhao

01:39:48.280 --> 01:39:57.200
Gong recounts this practice, with the usual Song&nbsp;
contempt for their northern rivals. When the Tartars

01:39:57.200 --> 01:40:03.600
were in their original countries, during the&nbsp;
Jin cowards’ reign, there was a rumor spoken;

01:40:03.600 --> 01:40:10.760
the Tartars are coming. Every three years they would&nbsp;
dispatch troops to the farthest frontiers and wastes

01:40:10.760 --> 01:40:18.120
of the north to destroy and kill, and called&nbsp;
it decreasing the number of fighting men. The

01:40:18.120 --> 01:40:24.240
Tartars fled and concealed themselves in the sandy&nbsp;
deserts, and hatred entered the marrow of their

01:40:24.240 --> 01:40:34.880
bones. This brutal policy had been remarkably&nbsp;
successful. Constantly beset by punitive raids,

01:40:34.880 --> 01:40:40.680
the peoples of the north like the Mongols&nbsp;
had remained bitterly divided, crippled by

01:40:40.680 --> 01:40:49.520
blood feuds and rivalries, of which the life of&nbsp;
Temujin gives just a glimpse. Zhao Gong describes

01:40:49.520 --> 01:40:58.400
the chaotic state of the steppe during this time. At&nbsp;
present, the Tartars are very simple and wild, and

01:40:58.400 --> 01:41:04.840
they have almost no institutions. I have studied&nbsp;
and researched this, and have found that they

01:41:04.840 --> 01:41:14.720
prosper and decline, rise and are destroyed, with&nbsp;
no regularity. The brutal Jin policy had created

01:41:14.720 --> 01:41:23.560
immense hardship, but they also provided something&nbsp;
of a safety net. For any group facing extinction

01:41:23.560 --> 01:41:30.920
in the steppe, there always remained this one way&nbsp;
of surviving, to enter the service of the Jin and

01:41:30.920 --> 01:41:39.920
defend the borders of their empire. It's thought&nbsp;
that after losing his battle with Jamuka, Temujin

01:41:39.920 --> 01:41:46.880
may have fled south into the borderlands of the&nbsp;
Jin Empire with what remained of his followers,

01:41:46.880 --> 01:41:55.360
and there sold his services as a juyin. If this&nbsp;
is where Temujin spent those ten years, then it's

01:41:55.360 --> 01:42:05.680
here that he would hone his skills as a leader and&nbsp;
strategist, and he would learn lessons in brutality.

01:42:05.680 --> 01:42:15.400
In the winter of 1196, the Jin paid him to attack&nbsp;
the wealthy steppe people known as the Tartars.

01:42:15.400 --> 01:42:21.640
The Tartars had actually been juyin border guards&nbsp;
themselves, and had grown rich from all the loot

01:42:21.640 --> 01:42:28.160
they had plundered on behalf of the Jin, but now&nbsp;
the Jin Dynasty feared that their loyal attack

01:42:28.160 --> 01:42:37.000
dogs had become too powerful. They employed Temujin’s&nbsp;
Mongols and their overlords, the powerful Kereyit

01:42:37.000 --> 01:42:46.040
people, to attack the Tartars and reduce any threat&nbsp;
they might eventually pose. Since the Tartars had

01:42:46.040 --> 01:42:53.560
once poisoned his father, Temujin must have been&nbsp;
all too happy to accept, as The Secret History

01:42:53.560 --> 01:43:04.480
recalls. When he learned the news, Temujin said, “From&nbsp;
days of old, the Tartars have been a hateful folk

01:43:04.480 --> 01:43:10.240
who murdered the grandfathers and fathers. 
In this opportunity, let us join in on this

01:43:10.240 --> 01:43:20.080
attack.” The ruler of the Kereyits, Toghril
Khan, also had reason to hate the Tartars. He

01:43:20.080 --> 01:43:26.400
had once been the anda or blood brother&nbsp;
of Temujin's murdered father, Yesugei,

01:43:26.400 --> 01:43:33.680
and in this period would become something of a&nbsp;
father figure to Temujin. Together they rode out

01:43:33.680 --> 01:43:40.160
against their joint enemy, and in a surprise&nbsp;
attack swept into Tartar lands and plundered

01:43:40.160 --> 01:43:46.760
them mercilessly. The Mongols were amazed by&nbsp;
the rich trade goods they seized from the

01:43:46.760 --> 01:43:53.040
tents and treasure carts of the Tartars. They&nbsp;
noticed that even the children of the Tartars

01:43:53.720 --> 01:44:02.440
had gold rings in their noses and wore sable&nbsp;
cloaks stitched with gold. The Jin Dynasty

01:44:02.440 --> 01:44:11.520
were delighted with Temujin's work, and promoted him
to the rank of jeutau, or pacification officer. Looting

01:44:11.520 --> 01:44:19.120
the Tartars brought his band great wealth and&nbsp;
doubtless more followers, too, and it solidified

01:44:19.120 --> 01:44:27.560
his relationship with the powerful Toghril Khan. From&nbsp;
this point on, Temujin became his right-hand man, and

01:44:27.560 --> 01:44:38.240
his power began to grow. One people known&nbsp;
as the Jurkin had raided some of Temujin's camps

01:44:38.240 --> 01:44:45.640
while he was away on his war with the Tartars,&nbsp;
and so, when he returned home, he rounded on them.

01:44:45.640 --> 01:44:50.840
But instead of simply taking their animals and&nbsp;
chasing them off, as was usually the way on the

01:44:50.840 --> 01:44:59.800
steppe, he rounded up their leadership and executed&nbsp;
every one. Then, to the common people of the Jurkin,

01:44:59.800 --> 01:45:08.120
he gave an offer; to join the Mongols, not as slaves&nbsp;
as would have been usual, but as members of the

01:45:08.120 --> 01:45:17.200
clan. He even gave his mother an orphan Jurkin&nbsp;
boy to adopt, symbolically accepting him as his

01:45:17.200 --> 01:45:26.440
brother. The Jurkin must have been perplexed,&nbsp;
but many of them accepted his deal. This was a

01:45:26.440 --> 01:45:34.560
new way of doing things on the steppe, and suddenly&nbsp;
the established elite of Mongolia began to get

01:45:34.560 --> 01:45:46.000
nervous. These old, powerful Khans rallied around the&nbsp;
one person they thought could challenge Temujin,

01:45:46.000 --> 01:45:52.920
in fact, the only man who had ever beaten&nbsp;
him in battle; his own blood brother, Jamuka.

01:45:53.680 --> 01:46:01.640
These old Khans gathered and crowned Jamuka&nbsp;
with an ancient and powerful title, Gur Khan,

01:46:01.640 --> 01:46:09.800
meaning something like Khan over Khans. The only thing&nbsp;
standing between Jamuka and his final victory was

01:46:09.800 --> 01:46:18.760
Temujin. When Temujin and Jamuka met in&nbsp;
battle for the final time, the year was

01:46:18.760 --> 01:46:26.040
1201.Both sides gathered their horsemen,&nbsp;
who by now would have numbered in the

01:46:26.040 --> 01:46:33.400
many thousands. Wars in Mongolia were fought&nbsp;
with horse and spear, with bow and arrow and

01:46:33.400 --> 01:46:41.600
sword. One Chinese chronicler, Peng Daya, writes an&nbsp;
account of the typical equipment of a Mongol

01:46:41.600 --> 01:46:51.920
warrior. Their weapons and armor consist of scale&nbsp;
armor, chain mail with leather six layers deep, and

01:46:51.920 --> 01:46:59.440
tough sheep-horn bows. They whittle wood for&nbsp;
the shafts and take down birds of prey for the

01:46:59.440 --> 01:47:06.720
feathers. Their scimitars follow the Westerner&nbsp;
style; light and sharp. They have long and short

01:47:06.720 --> 01:47:13.880
spears with tips like drills, so that what is&nbsp;
speared does not slip off, and they can penetrate

01:47:13.880 --> 01:47:23.320
heavy armor. They have defensive shields of short-
stemmed bamboo or else of willow tied with leather.

01:47:23.320 --> 01:47:29.040
But as well as these physical weapons,&nbsp;
battles in Mongolia were also fought with

01:47:29.040 --> 01:47:39.320
magic. Both sides would bring their most&nbsp;
powerful shamans to the battlefield, and

01:47:39.320 --> 01:47:44.920
these holy men were considered to have&nbsp;
exceptional abilities at their disposal;

01:47:44.920 --> 01:47:53.040
to turn away enemy arrows, cause their shields and&nbsp;
bowstrings to break, and even use enchanted stones

01:47:53.040 --> 01:47:59.560
to control the weather. The great respect&nbsp;
that all Mongols held for these shamans

01:47:59.560 --> 01:48:05.040
meant that they actually had a very real&nbsp;
psychological effect on the battlefield.

01:48:05.040 --> 01:48:11.520
In a narrow contest that could go either way, an&nbsp;
impressive display of shamanic power could even

01:48:11.520 --> 01:48:17.600
make the difference between an army standing&nbsp;
and fighting or panicking and running, between

01:48:17.600 --> 01:48:25.200
victory and defeat. On the day of the battle, as&nbsp;
the horsemen clashed and arrows flew in angry

01:48:25.200 --> 01:48:33.320
swarms through the air, it was Temujin’s shamans&nbsp;
who seemed to win the day. As the battle wore

01:48:33.320 --> 01:48:39.920
on, the clouds darkened, and a great steppe&nbsp;
storm swept down over the bloodstained

01:48:39.920 --> 01:48:48.600
grasslands. When they were pushing each&nbsp;
other back and forth, up and down the

01:48:48.600 --> 01:48:55.560
slope, and reforming their own ranks, at&nbsp;
that very moment, the shamans of Jamuka

01:48:55.560 --> 01:49:01.040
performed the weather-stone magic. But&nbsp;
the weather magic reversed, and the magic

01:49:01.040 --> 01:49:07.440
fell on themselves. Then, saying to each&nbsp;
other, “Heaven is not pleased with us”, they

01:49:07.440 --> 01:49:23.720
scattered. Jamuka now fled just as Temujin once&nbsp;
had. Over the next few years, he would

01:49:23.720 --> 01:49:31.240
regroup with some of his men, but many could&nbsp;
now see which way the wind was blowing. Some

01:49:31.240 --> 01:49:36.840
of Jamuka's followers betrayed him, hoping that&nbsp;
if they handed him over to Temujin, they would

01:49:36.840 --> 01:49:44.080
curry favor with the new ascendant lord of the&nbsp;
steppe. When they came to Temujin with their captive,

01:49:44.080 --> 01:49:51.920
however, they were disappointed. For their reward,&nbsp;
Temujin had them all put to death, condemning them

01:49:51.920 --> 01:50:00.920
in the following terms. People&nbsp;
who laid hands on their own ruler, how can

01:50:00.920 --> 01:50:07.920
they be allowed to live? Who would befriend&nbsp;
such people? Execute them all, down to their

01:50:07.920 --> 01:50:21.640
offspring. But his rival Jamuka could not be&nbsp;
allowed to live. Despite their sworn bond, Temujin

01:50:21.640 --> 01:50:28.000
ordered that he be killed. Perhaps as a sign of&nbsp;
the love they had once held for one another, the

01:50:28.000 --> 01:50:35.560
deed was done in the most noble manner according&nbsp;
to Mongol tradition; that is without shedding any

01:50:35.560 --> 01:50:44.720
of his blood. Jamuka was likely strangled or his&nbsp;
back broken, and his body was buried. With the

01:50:44.720 --> 01:50:54.120
killing of Jamuka, Temujin's childhood died, too, and a&nbsp;
new man was born. The war of the Khans had come

01:50:54.120 --> 01:51:02.560
to an end, and now Temujin’s claim to be Khan of all&nbsp;
the Mongols faced no opposition. Before long, other

01:51:02.560 --> 01:51:11.360
peoples of the steppe fell before his horsemen; the&nbsp;
Naiman, the Jadaran, the Oirat, the Tayichyut, and the Tartars.

01:51:11.360 --> 01:51:18.600
In each clan that fell to him, the elites and nobles&nbsp;
were killed, but as with the Jurkin, the commoners

01:51:18.600 --> 01:51:26.000
were absorbed into the Mongol army, and Temujin's&nbsp;
mother Oelun would ceremoniously adopt an orphaned

01:51:26.000 --> 01:51:35.120
child of their people as Temujin's brother. As a&nbsp;
system, it was immensely symbolic and ruthlessly

01:51:35.120 --> 01:51:43.560
effective. Eventually, even his mentor Toghril, the&nbsp;
Khan of the Kereyit, recognized how powerful his

01:51:43.560 --> 01:51:52.520
protege had become. He turned on Temujin and tried&nbsp;
to have him killed, but he too was swept aside.

01:51:53.720 --> 01:52:00.560
Now around the age of seventy, Toghril was defeated
at a clash remembered as the Battle of the Burning

01:52:00.560 --> 01:52:09.440
Sands. Now there was no one left to stand&nbsp;
in Temujin's way. Temujin was the undisputed

01:52:09.440 --> 01:52:20.400
overlord of virtually all the peoples of Mongolia,&nbsp;
and the commander of as many as 100,000 horsemen.

01:52:20.400 --> 01:52:27.760
In a grand kuriltai ceremony in the year 1206,&nbsp;
he gathered all the peoples he had conquered, and

01:52:27.760 --> 01:52:37.160
declared himself the emperor of the eastern steppe. When&nbsp;
he was crowned, he chose to rule not with the old

01:52:37.160 --> 01:52:47.040
traditional title of Gur Khan that Jamuka had chosen,&nbsp;
but with a new title. This title would symbolize

01:52:47.040 --> 01:52:54.080
that things in the world of the steppe were about&nbsp;
to change, that Temujin would be the kind of ruler

01:52:54.080 --> 01:53:01.720
that Asia had never seen before. The meaning of&nbsp;
this title is much debated, and meant something

01:53:01.720 --> 01:53:12.440
like Great Khan, righteous king, or oceanic emperor.&nbsp;
But soon it would be known all around the world,

01:53:12.440 --> 01:53:52.440
a title that in the Mongolian language was&nbsp;
pronounced Chinggis Khan.

01:54:05.560 --> 01:54:11.840
The title that Temujin chose to rule under&nbsp;
has suffered much from translation through

01:54:11.840 --> 01:54:21.480
the ages. From Mongolian, it entered the Persian&nbsp;
language relatively unscathed as Chengiz Khan,

01:54:21.480 --> 01:54:30.840
but when these sources were translated into Arabic,&nbsp;
the confusion began. Arabic has no C-H, ‘ch’ sound,

01:54:30.840 --> 01:54:38.600
and so, they used their letter J to make it Jengiz
Khan. European scholars would later translate these

01:54:38.600 --> 01:54:45.720
sources into Latin, and eventually into English&nbsp;
in the 19th century, at which time the translators

01:54:45.720 --> 01:54:54.440
used the letter G to denote a soft sound like&nbsp;
in general or German. But due to the ambiguous

01:54:54.440 --> 01:55:02.840
pronunciation of the letter G in English, this soon&nbsp;
led to an extremely common mispronunciation, Genghis

01:55:02.840 --> 01:55:11.400
Khan. The mispronunciation is so widespread today&nbsp;
that Genghis Khan has arguably become the standard

01:55:11.400 --> 01:55:17.560
way that the name is pronounced in English, but&nbsp;
for the sake of correctness, in this episode I

01:55:17.560 --> 01:55:26.160
will pronounce the name Chinggis, as it is said in&nbsp;
Mongolia today. Beyond the pronunciation of his

01:55:26.160 --> 01:55:35.920
name, much else is mysterious about the figure&nbsp;
of Chinggis Khan, not least his appearance. No

01:55:35.920 --> 01:55:43.200
artistic representations were ever made of him&nbsp;
during his life or by anyone who met him. As a

01:55:43.200 --> 01:55:49.560
result, those imaginary depictions we do have&nbsp;
are deeply influenced by the artist's cultural

01:55:49.560 --> 01:55:58.200
background. In one Chinese portrait of the Great&nbsp;
Khan made after his death, he appears painted like

01:55:58.200 --> 01:56:07.360
a Chinese emperor, wearing a white Mongolian-style&nbsp;
robe. Meanwhile, in the Persian miniature paintings,

01:56:07.360 --> 01:56:13.400
he is depicted wearing a great golden crown,&nbsp;
or later as a Persian prince with a feathered

01:56:13.400 --> 01:56:22.520
turban, necklaces of pearls, or dressed in fine silk&nbsp;
and brocades. In Europe, too, he would be depicted

01:56:22.520 --> 01:56:30.480
with European features, with fine fur cloaks&nbsp;
and a gown of flowing silk, sporting a handsome

01:56:30.480 --> 01:56:40.040
moustache. Written descriptions of him could be&nbsp;
no less fragmentary. The Chinese writer Zhao Gong

01:56:40.040 --> 01:56:49.160
writes one rare account of his appearance. On the&nbsp;
whole, the Tartars are not very tall, the tallest

01:56:49.160 --> 01:56:57.960
not exceeding five feet and three or four inches.
They grow extremely little facial hair. The Tartar lord

01:56:57.960 --> 01:57:06.120
Temujin differs in that he is of a large and noble bearing,&nbsp;
with a broad forehead and long whiskers, and cuts a

01:57:06.120 --> 01:57:16.440
heroic, robust figure. The 13th-century Persian&nbsp;
writer, Minhaj al-Siraj Juzjani, writes another rare

01:57:16.440 --> 01:57:23.000
description of what he looked like, although he got&nbsp;
his account third-hand, and never saw the Great Khan

01:57:23.000 --> 01:57:33.840
himself. A man of tall stature, of vigorous build,&nbsp;
robust in body, the hair on his face scanty and

01:57:33.840 --> 01:57:41.800
turned white, with cat's eyes, possessed&nbsp;
of dedicated energy, discernment, genius,

01:57:41.800 --> 01:57:52.320
and understanding, awestriking, a butcher, just,&nbsp;
resolute, an overthrower of enemies, intrepid,

01:57:52.320 --> 01:57:59.560
bloodthirsty, and cruel. He was adept at magic&nbsp;
and deception, and some of the devils were his

01:57:59.560 --> 01:58:09.160
friends. Historians have never settled exactly&nbsp;
what Juzjani means when he says that Chinggis

01:58:09.160 --> 01:58:16.640
Khan had cat's eyes. This may have referred&nbsp;
to the epicanthic folds that are typical of

01:58:16.640 --> 01:58:22.440
the faces of Mongolians and many peoples in&nbsp;
East Asia, and may have been worthy of mention

01:58:22.440 --> 01:58:29.480
to the Persian chronicler, but it may also&nbsp;
indicate that Chinggis Khan had a striking

01:58:29.480 --> 01:58:36.000
and unusual eye color, perhaps a bright&nbsp;
yellow that occurs in rare cases, with

01:58:36.000 --> 01:58:45.440
a higher incidence in East Asia. Throughout these&nbsp;
sources, Chinggis Khan is elusive, insubstantial, and

01:58:45.440 --> 01:58:52.280
mysterious, but the changes he brought about&nbsp;
in the world would be immense, and after conquering

01:58:52.280 --> 01:59:07.300
much of the world of the steppe, the man who was&nbsp;
once Temujin began the work of building a

01:59:07.300 --> 01:59:24.120
state. The empire that Chinggis Khan would forge, he&nbsp;
would call the Yeke Mongol Ulus, or the Great Mongol

01:59:24.120 --> 01:59:32.840
State, but he also referred to it informally and&nbsp;
affectionately as the people of the felt walls,

01:59:32.840 --> 01:59:40.560
referring to the felt tents that characterized&nbsp;
the nomadic way of life. The empire was a vast

01:59:40.560 --> 01:59:47.440
confederation, covering a land area roughly the&nbsp;
size of Western Europe, and comprising at least

01:59:47.440 --> 01:59:56.680
one million people and probably 20 million herd&nbsp;
animals, but it was an empire of grass, an empire

01:59:56.680 --> 02:00:05.000
without cities, without governors or administrators.&nbsp;
To make sense of this organizational nightmare,

02:00:05.000 --> 02:00:14.160
Chinggis Khan embarked on a dramatic restructuring&nbsp;
of Mongol society. He would tear out the old system

02:00:14.160 --> 02:00:22.040
of clan loyalties and replace it with one based&nbsp;
around the military. He organized his warriors

02:00:22.040 --> 02:00:28.200
according to an old decimal system that had been&nbsp;
used for centuries on the steppe, going back to the

02:00:28.200 --> 02:00:36.320
time of the Xiongnu. His soldiers were placed&nbsp;
into squads of ten men called an arban, who lived

02:00:36.320 --> 02:00:45.520
together and fought as brothers. These squads were&nbsp;
typically led by the eldest man. Ten of these arban

02:00:45.520 --> 02:00:54.080
joined together to make a zagun, or a hundred men,&nbsp;
and these hundred voted to choose its leader. Ten

02:00:54.080 --> 02:01:03.720
zagun made a mingan, or a thousand men, and ten&nbsp;
mingan made a tumen, an army of 10,000 Mongol

02:01:03.720 --> 02:01:11.400
horsemen. This was considered to be a practical&nbsp;
size, large enough to be effective in battle, but

02:01:11.400 --> 02:01:18.600
not so large that it could not move quickly or&nbsp;
ran into problems with supply. The leaders of these

02:01:18.600 --> 02:01:27.680
tumen were chosen by Temujin personally. In this&nbsp;
way, the old messy clan system, which had fostered

02:01:27.680 --> 02:01:34.560
infighting and backstabbing, had been replaced by&nbsp;
a regimented system that promoted coordination

02:01:34.560 --> 02:01:42.240
and cooperation. The Persian scholar Ata-Malik
Juvaini, writing in the service of the Mongols in

02:01:42.240 --> 02:01:52.560
the 1250s, gushes about the great success of these&nbsp;
reforms. God Almighty in wisdom and intelligence

02:01:52.560 --> 02:02:00.480
distinguished Chingiz Khan in alertness of mind&nbsp;
and absoluteness of power, and exalted him above

02:02:00.480 --> 02:02:07.160
all the kings of the world so that all that had&nbsp;
been recorded touching the ways of the pharaohs

02:02:07.160 --> 02:02:15.000
and Caesars was by Chingiz Khan, invented from&nbsp;
the page of his own mind. He established a rule

02:02:15.000 --> 02:02:22.920
for every occasion and a regulation for every&nbsp;
circumstance, while for every crime he fixed a

02:02:22.920 --> 02:02:32.200
penalty. Every Mongol of all ages and genders&nbsp;
were now required to give one day a week of

02:02:32.200 --> 02:02:39.840
public service, either in the army or working on&nbsp;
public projects. These could be herding animals and

02:02:39.840 --> 02:02:47.760
collecting milk, gathering dung for fuel, or making&nbsp;
felt from wool. Sometimes their service could

02:02:47.760 --> 02:02:56.560
simply be to serve food at a feast, or to sing and&nbsp;
entertain the troops. Chinggis Khan worked to

02:02:56.560 --> 02:03:03.720
end the feuding that had for centuries defined&nbsp;
the harsh reality of Mongol life. Previously, the

02:03:03.720 --> 02:03:09.320
only justice on the steppe was the vengeance you&nbsp;
could exact on those who wronged you, which had

02:03:09.320 --> 02:03:16.920
the tendency to bring about cycles of reprisal&nbsp;
and violence that echoed down the generations.

02:03:16.920 --> 02:03:25.920
But Temujin introduced a series of laws that&nbsp;
he would call the Great Law or Yassa. Since the

02:03:25.920 --> 02:03:32.240
Mongols had no written script, they adopted the&nbsp;
writing system of the nearby Uighur people, and

02:03:32.240 --> 02:03:39.760
copied these laws down in a series of books with&nbsp;
bright blue bindings, as the Persian scholar Juvaini

02:03:39.760 --> 02:03:49.920
recalls. These rolls are called the Great Book of&nbsp;
the Yassa, and are kept in the treasury of the chief

02:03:49.920 --> 02:03:57.600
princes. Whenever a Khan ascends the throne, or a great&nbsp;
army is mobilized, or the princes assemble and

02:03:57.600 --> 02:04:04.840
begin to consult together concerning affairs of&nbsp;
state and the administration thereof, they produce

02:04:04.840 --> 02:04:14.280
these rolls and model their actions there on. Each&nbsp;
one of the new laws that Chinggis Khan wrote seemed

02:04:14.280 --> 02:04:22.000
to be directly influenced by his own experiences&nbsp;
in earlier life. One of his first laws was to

02:04:22.000 --> 02:04:29.240
forbid the kidnapping of women on the Mongol steppe.&nbsp;
He had come close to losing his wife Borte in this

02:04:29.240 --> 02:04:38.200
way, and knew the pain of it firsthand, and his own&nbsp;
mother Oelun had been kidnapped by his father. In

02:04:38.200 --> 02:04:44.480
this way, it must have been a deeply personal issue,&nbsp;
but kidnapping was also one of the main causes of

02:04:44.480 --> 02:04:52.040
friction on the steppe, and had sparked countless&nbsp;
bitter feuds. Outlawing it completely would bring

02:04:52.040 --> 02:04:59.680
peace, where before there had been only conflict.&nbsp;
He also outlawed the taking of other Mongols as

02:04:59.680 --> 02:05:07.000
slaves. After being kept as a slave by the Tayichyut,&nbsp;
this issue seems to have arisen from his own

02:05:07.000 --> 02:05:16.000
bitter memories, although there would be no law&nbsp;
against taking slaves from other steppe peoples.

02:05:16.000 --> 02:05:23.000
He also outlawed the theft of animals, and brought&nbsp;
in regulations on when people could hunt,

02:05:23.000 --> 02:05:28.840
banning hunting throughout the breeding season,&nbsp;
so that stocks of game animals would not become

02:05:28.840 --> 02:05:37.080
depleted. Finally, he began the introduction of what&nbsp;
would become a law that guaranteed a degree of

02:05:37.080 --> 02:05:44.840
religious protection to his subjects, perhaps the&nbsp;
first law of its kind in the Middle Ages, as Juvaini

02:05:44.840 --> 02:05:55.240
records. Being the adherent of no religion and&nbsp;
the follower of no creed, he rejected bigotry

02:05:55.240 --> 02:06:02.600
and the preference of one faith to another, and the&nbsp;
placing of some above others. Rather, he honored and

02:06:02.600 --> 02:06:10.520
respected the learned and the pious of every sect,&nbsp;
recognizing such conduct as the way to the court

02:06:10.520 --> 02:06:21.840
of God. These laws may sound idealistic&nbsp;
to us today, but they were also pragmatic. Religious

02:06:21.840 --> 02:06:27.440
conflicts could cause ruptures between&nbsp;
different families and clans, and damage

02:06:27.440 --> 02:06:35.160
the cohesion of the empire. But now all the steppe&nbsp;
peoples, whether Muslim, Christian, Buddhist, or

02:06:35.160 --> 02:06:41.840
like him, a worshipper of Tengri and the Great&nbsp;
Blue Sky, would all share equal protection under

02:06:41.840 --> 02:06:49.400
the law. Certain religious practices like the&nbsp;
slaughter of halal meat were outlawed, sometimes

02:06:49.400 --> 02:06:55.240
on penalty of death, so it has been contested&nbsp;
how much we can really call this religious

02:06:55.240 --> 02:07:01.880
freedom, but it was still a radical new vision&nbsp;
for what kind of state the Mongol Empire could

02:07:01.880 --> 02:07:18.480
be. On top of these reforms, Chinggis Khan&nbsp;
created a new inner heartland for the

02:07:18.480 --> 02:07:24.720
empire. This was the original homeland
of the Mongols, the region where the rivers

02:07:24.720 --> 02:07:31.840
Onon, Kherlen, and Tuul found their source, and&nbsp;
where he had once sheltered from the Tayichyut

02:07:31.840 --> 02:07:40.880
warriors who had hunted him. This was the land&nbsp;
centered around the mountain Burkan Khaldun. Only

02:07:40.880 --> 02:07:46.400
members of his close family and inner court&nbsp;
were allowed to venture into this private

02:07:46.400 --> 02:07:52.680
land, and it was here that Mongol royalty&nbsp;
would bury their dead for centuries to

02:07:52.680 --> 02:08:03.600
come. At the head of Mongol society sat Chinggis&nbsp;
Khan and his inner court, which in Mongolian was

02:08:03.600 --> 02:08:10.840
known as an ordu, a word that means something&nbsp;
like great tent, and is the origin of the

02:08:10.840 --> 02:08:20.760
English word horde. The word Mongol itself has a&nbsp;
somewhat uncertain origin, perhaps deriving from

02:08:20.760 --> 02:08:30.240
the Mongolian phrase ‘Mongkhe-tengri-gal’, meaning&nbsp;
eternal sky fire, or from the word ‘mongu’, meaning

02:08:30.240 --> 02:08:39.480
silver. It had been used for some time about all&nbsp;
the scattered clans like Yesugei’s and Temujin’s, but

02:08:39.480 --> 02:08:46.880
now everyone who lived in the empire was&nbsp;
considered a Mongol citizen. But much to

02:08:46.880 --> 02:08:53.040
the Mongols’ frustration, they struggled to get&nbsp;
anyone outside of the steppe to call them by that

02:08:53.040 --> 02:09:01.560
name. For much of their history, people in China,&nbsp;
Persia, the Middle East, and Europe all insisted

02:09:01.560 --> 02:09:06.960
on calling them by the name of what had been up&nbsp;
until then the largest and most powerful of the

02:09:06.960 --> 02:09:15.400
steppe peoples, the Tartars. They did this sometimes&nbsp;
out of calculated disrespect and sometimes out of

02:09:15.400 --> 02:09:22.240
genuine confusion, and despite Mongol insistence&nbsp;
that they were not Tartars but Mongols, the

02:09:22.240 --> 02:09:31.640
name stuck. Still, despite all the reforms of&nbsp;
Chinggis Khan, Mongol society still remained a

02:09:31.640 --> 02:09:39.400
fragile entity, and its people still lived lives&nbsp;
of poverty and subsistence in the harsh land of

02:09:39.400 --> 02:09:48.360
the steppe. Chinggis Khan knew that his people would&nbsp;
remain united only as long as they had an enemy

02:09:48.360 --> 02:09:56.320
to fight together, and if no such enemy arose,&nbsp;
they would return to their old ways; fight one

02:09:56.320 --> 02:10:05.840
another and tear his new empire apart. Partly for&nbsp;
this reason, he began to cast his gaze beyond the

02:10:05.840 --> 02:10:21.320
high plateau of the Mongolian steppe, and hunger for&nbsp;
wars of conquest and the riches they could bring.

02:10:31.720 --> 02:10:37.720
While the Jin and Song divided the river&nbsp;
plains of China between them, there was

02:10:37.720 --> 02:10:45.920
a third smaller kingdom to their west, known as&nbsp;
the Western Xia. This was located partly in the

02:10:45.920 --> 02:10:51.360
hilly upper reaches of the Yellow River&nbsp;
and the dry desert regions to the north

02:10:51.360 --> 02:10:58.640
of the Tibetan Plateau, known as the Hexi&nbsp;
Corridor. This had been a strategic trade

02:10:58.640 --> 02:11:04.560
route for the past thousand years, since the&nbsp;
time of the Han Dynasty, and it's through this

02:11:04.560 --> 02:11:12.120
narrow passage that the vast majority of Silk&nbsp;
Road goods passed on huge caravans of Bactrian

02:11:12.120 --> 02:11:22.560
camels. Like the Jin, the Western Xia were a&nbsp;
conquest dynasty, ruled by a people known as

02:11:22.560 --> 02:11:31.320
the Tanguts, nomadic Buddhists from the region&nbsp;
of Tibet. Their society was a hybrid, including

02:11:31.320 --> 02:11:39.360
both nomadic herders not unlike the Mongols,&nbsp;
and the settled cities full of Chinese, Turkic, and

02:11:39.360 --> 02:11:47.280
Tibetan peoples, with a booming economy based&nbsp;
on Silk Road trade. This was the smallest and

02:11:47.280 --> 02:11:54.360
weakest kingdom bordering the steppe, and it had&nbsp;
recently sheltered some enemies of Chinggis Khan,

02:11:54.360 --> 02:12:02.320
who had fled from his conquest. For this reason, the&nbsp;
Tanguts were the first prey upon which he set his

02:12:02.320 --> 02:12:13.200
sights. At first, the Mongols initiated a series&nbsp;
of raids on their border forts, testing their

02:12:13.200 --> 02:12:21.200
defenses, but in the year 1209, Chinggis Khan&nbsp;
gathered his horde and descended on their borders.

02:12:21.200 --> 02:12:37.200
When they got news that the Khan was&nbsp;
marching on their lands, the Tanguts sent

02:12:37.200 --> 02:12:42.720
out messengers begging for help from&nbsp;
their neighbors, the powerful Jin and

02:12:42.720 --> 02:12:51.240
Song Dynasties in the south, but neither the&nbsp;
Jin nor the Song sent any aid. The ruler of

02:12:51.240 --> 02:12:58.920
the Jin Dynasty, known as Prince Shao of Wei, is even&nbsp;
recorded to have sent the following dismissive

02:12:58.920 --> 02:13:06.960
reply. It is to our advantage when our enemies&nbsp;
attack one another. Wherein lies the danger to

02:13:06.960 --> 02:13:16.640
us? As we will see, this pattern would repeat itself&nbsp;
in almost all the lands that the Mongols arrived

02:13:16.640 --> 02:13:25.040
in. At various points, a coordinated and united&nbsp;
response might have stopped their advance, but

02:13:25.040 --> 02:13:33.360
everywhere, local rivalries prevented anyone from&nbsp;
uniting against them. In the desert regions, the

02:13:33.360 --> 02:13:41.240
Mongols easily overwhelmed the Tangut armies,&nbsp;
but the walled cities of Western Xia proved to

02:13:41.240 --> 02:13:48.040
be a much greater obstacle. The Mongols had&nbsp;
no siege equipment, no ladders or battering

02:13:48.040 --> 02:13:55.640
rams, no catapults or engineers, and so, all they&nbsp;
could do was surround the fortresses, gaze up at

02:13:55.640 --> 02:14:04.960
their towering walls, and try to starve the Tangut&nbsp;
people into surrender. This was highly unpalatable

02:14:04.960 --> 02:14:12.080
for Mongol warriors, who delighted in moving&nbsp;
quickly, striking fast, and always finding new

02:14:12.080 --> 02:14:21.680
grasslands for their horses. The Mongols encircled&nbsp;
the Tanguts in their capital of Yinchuan, but it was

02:14:21.680 --> 02:14:29.400
a powerful fortress guarded by an army of&nbsp;
150,000 soldiers. At the sight of the Mongol

02:14:29.400 --> 02:14:37.800
army, the Tanguts simply disappeared behind their&nbsp;
walls and refused to be baited out for battle. In

02:14:37.800 --> 02:14:44.440
an act of desperation, at one point the Mongols&nbsp;
even attempted to dam the Yellow River in the

02:14:44.440 --> 02:14:51.960
hope of redirecting it into the city, flooding it&nbsp;
and undermining the foundations of its walls. But

02:14:51.960 --> 02:15:01.640
the river instead flooded the Mongols’ camp. Still,&nbsp;
the Tanguts had enough of the destruction,

02:15:01.640 --> 02:15:10.080
and soon sued for peace. The Secret History of&nbsp;
the Mongols records their plea to the Great

02:15:10.080 --> 02:15:22.720
Khan. If Chinggis Khan shows us favor, then&nbsp;
we the Tangut people shall bring

02:15:22.720 --> 02:15:27.720
forth many camels reared in the shelter&nbsp;
of the tall feather grass. We shall weave

02:15:27.720 --> 02:15:33.560
woolen material and make satin, and then we&nbsp;
shall give them to you. Training falcons to

02:15:33.560 --> 02:15:38.240
fly loose at game, we shall gather them,&nbsp;
and all the best ones we shall send to you.

02:15:38.240 --> 02:15:53.440
Sources in southern Song China recorded&nbsp;
the subjugation of the Tanguts with a

02:15:53.440 --> 02:15:59.720
mixture of contempt and amusement.
From their perspective, a hated rival

02:15:59.720 --> 02:16:08.840
had been bested by mere barbarians. The Song&nbsp;
writer Li Xinchuan records this event with a

02:16:08.840 --> 02:16:18.000
sneer. The black Tartars became increasingly&nbsp;
powerful. Having gradually unified the clan

02:16:18.000 --> 02:16:24.240
lands, they then raised a great army and&nbsp;
attacked Hexi. Within several years, all

02:16:24.240 --> 02:16:30.760
the districts and prefectures of Hexi had been&nbsp;
sacked. They even forcibly carried off a false

02:16:30.760 --> 02:16:36.600
princess of the Xia kingdom in departing,&nbsp;
and the Xia actually had to serve them as

02:16:36.600 --> 02:16:45.600
vassals. In the decade that followed, the&nbsp;
situation would not seem so amusing to the

02:16:45.600 --> 02:16:57.040
Song. The conquest of the Western Xia had proven&nbsp;
the effectiveness of the Mongol war machine, but

02:16:57.040 --> 02:17:04.960
it had also exposed a number of glaring weaknesses.&nbsp;
Walled cities had frustrated and slowed the Mongol

02:17:04.960 --> 02:17:11.960
advance, and it became clear that if they hoped to&nbsp;
tackle even larger prey, something would have to

02:17:11.960 --> 02:17:21.160
change. One Chinese writer, Xu Ting, records&nbsp;
how the Mongol conquest of the Tanguts

02:17:21.160 --> 02:17:28.920
set the stage for ever greater expansion. The&nbsp;
Tartars in the beginning were primitively

02:17:28.920 --> 02:17:35.040
ignorant and lacked even a single of the&nbsp;
known crafts. Only later, when they conquered

02:17:35.040 --> 02:17:42.160
the Westerners, did they begin to have products,&nbsp;
craftsmen, and mechanisms. The craftmanship of

02:17:42.160 --> 02:17:50.840
the Westerners is extremely refined. Especially&nbsp;
fine are their instruments of siege warfare.

02:17:51.920 --> 02:17:57.000
But the Tanguts simply ruled over the trade&nbsp;
corridor that transported the goods from

02:17:57.000 --> 02:18:03.800
east to west. Chinggis Khan knew that even&nbsp;
greater wealth could be found in the lands

02:18:03.800 --> 02:18:12.840
where those goods were actually produced; the&nbsp;
lands of China. All he needed was an excuse for

02:18:12.840 --> 02:18:20.760
war, and that would come with the death of the&nbsp;
Golden Khan of the Jin Dynasty in the year 1208 AD.

02:18:20.920 --> 02:18:47.600
When the old Golden Khan of the Jin died,&nbsp;
his young son, Prince Shao of Wei, took the

02:18:47.600 --> 02:18:54.720
throne. This young man had heard of the&nbsp;
rise of Chinggis Khan to the north of the Gobi

02:18:54.720 --> 02:19:02.800
Desert, the mysterious character who had united&nbsp;
the peoples of the steppe, but it had so far not

02:19:02.800 --> 02:19:09.920
particularly troubled him, other than the annoying&nbsp;
fact that this new ruler had stopped paying him

02:19:09.920 --> 02:19:18.720
tribute. The new Golden Khan ruled a sprawling&nbsp;
empire of more than 50 million people, perhaps

02:19:18.720 --> 02:19:27.600
the most populous and powerful in the world at&nbsp;
the time. Their armies totaled 600,000 men, mostly

02:19:27.600 --> 02:19:34.760
comprised of armored pikemen and crossbowmen.&nbsp;
They commanded perhaps the most technologically

02:19:34.760 --> 02:19:42.280
advanced forces on Earth, even experimenting with&nbsp;
early gunpowder weaponry, and on top of that, their

02:19:42.280 --> 02:19:49.439
steppe roots in the region of Manchuria meant that&nbsp;
they still fielded a mighty cavalry force of

02:19:49.439 --> 02:19:59.479
more than 150,000 horsemen, dispersed as cavalry&nbsp;
divisions among their various armies. The Mongols

02:19:59.479 --> 02:20:07.919
looked weak in comparison. Their forces totaled&nbsp;
no more than about 100,000 horse-archers, with

02:20:07.920 --> 02:20:13.680
not a single footsoldier among them, and&nbsp;
the Jin were confident that no one could

02:20:13.680 --> 02:20:21.560
lead an army across the Gobi Desert large enough&nbsp;
to threaten them. For this reason, this young Jin

02:20:21.560 --> 02:20:32.800
emperor had every reason to be confident. One Song&nbsp;
Chinese writer, Zhao Gong, recalls their attitude. The

02:20:32.800 --> 02:20:39.479
Jin said about the Tartars, “Our country is like&nbsp;
the sea. Your country is like two handfuls of

02:20:39.479 --> 02:20:50.759
sand. How could you shake us?” The Tartars to this&nbsp;
day, young and old, can all remember these words.

02:20:50.760 --> 02:20:53.840
It's perhaps this confidence that would lead

02:20:53.840 --> 02:20:57.920
to the terrible mistake he&nbsp;
would make in the year 1210 AD.

02:20:57.920 --> 02:21:13.080
Every new emperor began his reign by&nbsp;
sending out envoys to the empire's subjects, those

02:21:13.080 --> 02:21:19.240
kingdoms and peoples who had sworn allegiance&nbsp;
to his father, to ask them to swear loyalty to

02:21:19.240 --> 02:21:27.160
him in turn and recommit to whatever tribute&nbsp;
they had previously been paying. As part of this

02:21:27.160 --> 02:21:34.559
process, he sent one envoy across the Gobi Desert&nbsp;
to demand that their previous juyin border guard,

02:21:34.560 --> 02:21:41.160
Chinggis Khan, come south and make a gesture&nbsp;
of loyalty and submission to the new Golden

02:21:41.160 --> 02:21:50.680
Khan of the Jin. When the envoys arrived, they would&nbsp;
have met with Chinggis Khan, who was now nearly 50

02:21:50.680 --> 02:21:59.160
years old. If he had ever seen the value in bowing&nbsp;
and scraping to the lords of the south, those days

02:21:59.160 --> 02:22:06.760
were now very much behind him. When the Chinese&nbsp;
envoys met him, they asked him to send word of his

02:22:06.760 --> 02:22:17.880
submission to the Jin. The later Chinese source,&nbsp;
the Yuan Shi, describes what happened next. Chinggis

02:22:17.880 --> 02:22:25.240
Khan asked the Jin messengers, “Who is the new&nbsp;
emperor?” The messengers of the emperor replied, “The

02:22:25.240 --> 02:22:34.000
Prince of Wei.” Chinggis Khan turned his face to the&nbsp;
south, spat in that direction, and said, “I thought

02:22:34.000 --> 02:22:40.600
that the Emperor of the Middle Kingdom should be&nbsp;
a man blessed by Heaven. Can he be such an ordinary

02:22:40.600 --> 02:22:50.440
and weak man? Why should I show him respect?”&nbsp;
Then he mounted his horse and rode to the north.

02:22:51.160 --> 02:22:59.000
The Jin envoys left, shaken at their encounter,&nbsp;
and Chinggis Khan deliberated on his course of

02:22:59.000 --> 02:23:07.200
action. His insult to the Jin would likely&nbsp;
bring a military response; that is, unless

02:23:07.200 --> 02:23:14.479
he moved first. But he must have been full&nbsp;
of doubts and fears about taking on such a

02:23:14.479 --> 02:23:24.839
powerful enemy. To find the best course of action,&nbsp;
he would need to speak to his god. To do this, he

02:23:24.840 --> 02:23:32.560
climbed up the slopes of the sacred mountain,&nbsp;
Burkan Khaldun, through the forests of larch and

02:23:32.560 --> 02:23:40.560
elegant Siberian pine, and there on its stony&nbsp;
peak, surrounded by twisted rock formations, he

02:23:40.560 --> 02:23:49.200
prayed to Tengri, the god of the Great Blue&nbsp;
Sky, to ask him what to do. According to The

02:23:49.200 --> 02:23:55.760
Secret History, when the sun rose on the&nbsp;
fourth day, Chinggis Khan emerged with his

02:23:55.760 --> 02:24:04.800
answer. The eternal blue sky&nbsp;
has promised us victory and

02:24:04.800 --> 02:24:16.880
vengeance. In the spring of 1211, the vast horde&nbsp;
of the Mongols gathered and set out on its march

02:24:16.880 --> 02:24:27.000
south across the Gobi Desert. The sight of this&nbsp;
force would have been terrifying. Overhead, pennants

02:24:27.000 --> 02:24:34.840
and banners flew, and at the head of the army flew&nbsp;
the great spirit banner of Chinggis Khan, woven from

02:24:34.840 --> 02:24:43.880
the tail hairs of hundreds of black horses. Every&nbsp;
Mongol warrior rode with five spare mounts at a

02:24:43.880 --> 02:24:49.920
time, so with an army of 100,000 horsemen, they&nbsp;
would have brought with them an extra half a

02:24:49.920 --> 02:24:58.040
million horses, and probably the same number of&nbsp;
sheep and goats. With them also came giant supply

02:24:58.040 --> 02:25:07.600
carts pulled by as many as twenty oxen and thousands&nbsp;
of Bactrian camels, some carrying enormous drums that

02:25:07.600 --> 02:25:14.640
were beaten to signal the men and rally them&nbsp;
for battle. This was an invasion force, but it

02:25:14.640 --> 02:25:22.319
was also a mass migration, an enormous traveling&nbsp;
city designed to flatten everything in its

02:25:22.319 --> 02:25:32.359
path. The people who would have stood and watched&nbsp;
this pandemonium approaching across the desert in

02:25:32.359 --> 02:25:40.160
a great cloud of dust were known as the Ongut.
They were a desert people that for years had

02:25:40.160 --> 02:25:48.920
been serving as juyin border guards for the Jin,&nbsp;
keeping their empire safe from steppe raiders. But

02:25:48.920 --> 02:25:56.800
upon seeing the enormous Mongol army approaching,&nbsp;
the Ongut reassessed their position. These border

02:25:56.800 --> 02:26:03.960
nomads welcomed the Mongols as brothers, and even&nbsp;
showed them the most direct route south through

02:26:03.960 --> 02:26:20.240
the narrow mountain passes, right into the heart&nbsp;
of the Jin lands. The invasion of China had begun.

02:26:23.359 --> 02:26:30.639
The Mongols’ strategy was always to attack&nbsp;
in multiple places at once, sowing maximum

02:26:30.640 --> 02:26:36.640
fear and confusion, and giving the appearance&nbsp;
that their forces were much more numerous than

02:26:36.640 --> 02:26:44.560
they were. For this reason, while Chinggis Khan&nbsp;
led his forces in the west, his general Jebe

02:26:44.560 --> 02:26:52.720
led an army into the east. The Song Chinese&nbsp;
writer Zhao Gong describes what happened

02:26:52.720 --> 02:27:01.319
next. Temujin, indignant over their&nbsp;
bullying and insults, invaded the

02:27:01.319 --> 02:27:07.719
frontier. The frontier prefectures&nbsp;
were all conquered, and their people

02:27:07.720 --> 02:27:19.720
killed. The Mongols took these border forts and&nbsp;
then crossed through the mountains. They first met

02:27:19.720 --> 02:27:28.279
Jin resistance at a place called Badger’s Mouth Pass,&nbsp;
and there they smashed the Jin army sent to face

02:27:28.279 --> 02:27:41.040
them. The Mongols broke through the mountains&nbsp;
by autumn of 1211, and spilled out into the

02:27:41.040 --> 02:27:47.640
Chinese heartland. For the next three years,&nbsp;
the Mongols pillaged the entire North

02:27:47.640 --> 02:27:53.000
China plain, and for much of this time,&nbsp;
the Jin were powerless to stop

02:27:53.000 --> 02:28:05.040
them. Part of the reason for this was the&nbsp;
immense mobility of Mongol armies. Jin

02:28:05.040 --> 02:28:11.640
armies were enormous and well-equipped, but they&nbsp;
were also slow. Typically containing twice as

02:28:11.640 --> 02:28:18.200
many infantry as cavalry, they lumbered across&nbsp;
the land at a snail's pace, and needed to be

02:28:18.200 --> 02:28:25.679
constantly supplied with food brought by wagon&nbsp;
along precarious supply routes. Meanwhile, the

02:28:25.680 --> 02:28:32.399
Mongols could disappear and reappear anywhere&nbsp;
they liked, allowing them to ambush and destroy

02:28:32.399 --> 02:28:40.120
whole Jin armies in the field, and everything&nbsp;
the Mongols needed they brought with them.

02:28:40.120 --> 02:28:47.519
Their horseback armies lived on milk and meat&nbsp;
from their animals, and in times of difficulty

02:28:47.520 --> 02:28:53.000
would even open up a vein on their horses&nbsp;
necks and drink the blood directly from their

02:28:53.000 --> 02:29:00.160
mounts. They would place strips of raw meat under&nbsp;
their saddles in the morning so that the flesh

02:29:00.160 --> 02:29:06.279
was tenderized throughout the day of riding,
so that it could be eaten raw in the evening.

02:29:06.279 --> 02:29:11.840
In this way, they could camp without lighting&nbsp;
fires that would give away their position to

02:29:11.840 --> 02:29:20.040
enemy scouts. One Jin officer, Tu Shanyi, gave the&nbsp;
following appraisal of the desperate situation.

02:29:23.640 --> 02:29:26.560
Since the Mongolian army is on horseback, it goes

02:29:26.560 --> 02:29:35.800
into the plain in only one body, but we&nbsp;
defend ourselves divided. Our defeat is

02:29:35.800 --> 02:29:46.080
certain. The Mongols relied on surprise and&nbsp;
deception in a way that completely blindsided

02:29:46.080 --> 02:29:51.880
the Jin generals, who conducted their wars&nbsp;
according to a long-established system

02:29:51.880 --> 02:30:01.319
of martial honor. One Song Chinese writer named&nbsp;
Peng Daya describes their array of inventive and

02:30:01.319 --> 02:30:09.319
unscrupulous tactics. The Tartars do things that&nbsp;
are not addressed in the ancient techniques. If

02:30:09.319 --> 02:30:14.599
the enemy puts up a strong defense that all&nbsp;
the Tartars’ plans fail to penetrate, they drive

02:30:14.600 --> 02:30:21.720
cattle at them or lash wild horses toward them,&nbsp;
using animals to disturb the enemy's ranks. Seldom

02:30:21.720 --> 02:30:27.760
does it fail to defeat them. When their own troops&nbsp;
are few, sometimes the Tartars will drag branches

02:30:27.760 --> 02:30:33.359
behind them, making dust rise to the heavens, and&nbsp;
leading the enemy to suspect that their troops

02:30:33.359 --> 02:30:40.839
are many. When victorious, they dog the enemy's tail&nbsp;
until the last man is killed, not permitting any

02:30:40.840 --> 02:30:46.479
to escape, but if they are the ones defeated,&nbsp;
they scatter in all four directions, beyond

02:30:46.479 --> 02:30:56.040
pursuit. The Mongols had learned how to turn the&nbsp;
Jin's great strengths against them. One of these

02:30:56.040 --> 02:31:03.359
strengths was their large population, and the&nbsp;
other, their powerful walled cities. But these

02:31:03.359 --> 02:31:11.559
could also be weaknesses. The Mongols exploited&nbsp;
these by borrowing tactics that they had learned

02:31:11.560 --> 02:31:19.960
hunting animals on the steppe. They would devastate&nbsp;
the countryside for miles around, which drove

02:31:19.960 --> 02:31:29.880
vast numbers of refugees towards the only safe&nbsp;
places left; the walled cities. Soon, they would be

02:31:29.880 --> 02:31:37.600
flooded with desperate and hungry people, and&nbsp;
their storehouses ran out of food. These mighty

02:31:37.600 --> 02:31:46.760
fortresses now became tombs from which no one&nbsp;
could escape. The Mongols also rounded up huge

02:31:46.760 --> 02:31:53.240
numbers of peasants from the countryside and forced&nbsp;
them to work, filling in defensive ditches and

02:31:53.240 --> 02:32:02.040
moats, pushing siege engines, and dismantling the&nbsp;
city's defenses. Each Mongol warrior was tasked

02:32:02.040 --> 02:32:09.240
with gathering up ten peasants for this purpose.&nbsp;
The defenders on the city walls were left with

02:32:09.240 --> 02:32:16.439
the brutal choice of allowing their defenses to&nbsp;
be destroyed by these unwilling laborers, or using

02:32:16.439 --> 02:32:25.960
up their arrows to slaughter their own people. The&nbsp;
Chinese writer Li Xinchuan describes this ruthless

02:32:25.960 --> 02:32:37.200
tactic. In the cities, villagers were drafted as&nbsp;
soldiers and sent up onto the walls to defend them.

02:32:37.200 --> 02:32:44.359
The Tartars drove their family members on to the&nbsp;
attack, and fathers and sons and older and younger

02:32:44.359 --> 02:32:51.719
brothers would often shout at each other from afar&nbsp;
in mutual recognition. For this reason, the people

02:32:51.720 --> 02:32:58.560
had no will to fight, and all the walled towns that&nbsp;
the Tartars reached surrendered at the first drum

02:32:58.560 --> 02:33:08.160
roll. Prisoners of war were also conscripted to&nbsp;
fight for their Mongol captors, with the promise

02:33:08.160 --> 02:33:14.599
that if they proved themselves in battle, they&nbsp;
would be freed and allowed to join the Mongol

02:33:14.600 --> 02:33:22.880
army. But despite their reputation for brutality,&nbsp;
Chinggis Khan and his warriors also practiced

02:33:22.880 --> 02:33:32.520
the judicious use of restraint. Sieges were costly&nbsp;
and time consuming, and he hoped that by showing

02:33:32.520 --> 02:33:37.840
mercy to those cities that surrendered without a&nbsp;
fight, he would increase the likelihood of others

02:33:37.840 --> 02:33:44.920
doing the same. Cities that opened their gates&nbsp;
to the Mongols were thoroughly looted of their

02:33:44.920 --> 02:33:52.439
treasure, but their people were spared. Still,&nbsp;
those cities that resisted were slaughtered

02:33:52.439 --> 02:34:00.559
mercilessly, and in the countryside, the death&nbsp;
and destruction was rampant, as Li Xinchuan

02:34:00.560 --> 02:34:12.600
describes. The massacre of the people was almost&nbsp;
total. Gold, silk, boys, girls, cattle, sheep, horses,

02:34:12.600 --> 02:34:19.560
and other livestock, all were rolled up like a mat&nbsp;
and carried off. Houses and cottages were burned

02:34:19.560 --> 02:34:29.399
down. The walls and ramparts became deserted&nbsp;
ruins. It's likely that the Mongols had

02:34:29.399 --> 02:34:35.879
not intended to undertake a full invasion of&nbsp;
China, but more like a series of large raids

02:34:35.880 --> 02:34:44.439
into these wealthy lands. But the more success&nbsp;
they met with, the longer they decided to stay.

02:34:44.439 --> 02:34:52.120
As the war entered its second and third years&nbsp;
and the Mongol armies still rampaged unchecked,

02:34:52.120 --> 02:35:00.040
the Jin became desperate. They began drafting&nbsp;
civilians into their army en masse, and even

02:35:00.040 --> 02:35:08.560
pardoned any criminal who would take up arms and&nbsp;
fight. But the Mongols could not be stopped. Soon,

02:35:08.560 --> 02:35:15.160
they were pushing far enough south to reach the&nbsp;
Jin capital on the site of modern Beijing, then

02:35:15.160 --> 02:35:25.519
known as Zhongdu. They laid eyes on the walls of the&nbsp;
city in the year 1214, three years after the war had

02:35:25.520 --> 02:35:34.720
started. Beijing at the time was among the&nbsp;
largest cities on Earth. Records show that

02:35:34.720 --> 02:35:42.680
it had a population of nearly a million people, and&nbsp;
was defended by an 18-km rectangle of rammed Earth

02:35:42.680 --> 02:35:54.840
walls, rising up to twelve meters high, broken by twelve&nbsp;
gates and 900 guard towers, ringed by a triple moat. Its

02:35:54.840 --> 02:36:01.600
walls were topped with powerful crossbows and&nbsp;
trebuchets capable of hurling projectiles more

02:36:01.600 --> 02:36:10.880
than 300 meters. The Mongols laid siege of the city,&nbsp;
but had little success in breaking through its

02:36:10.880 --> 02:36:20.960
defenses. Even for them, this final prize must&nbsp;
have seemed like a step too far. They were now

02:36:20.960 --> 02:36:27.840
dangerously overstretched, a long way from home,&nbsp;
and facing some of the world's most formidable

02:36:27.840 --> 02:36:37.479
fortifications. On top of that, the climate didn't&nbsp;
suit them. Summer in this part of the world was

02:36:37.479 --> 02:36:44.719
hot, and plague was beginning to spread among&nbsp;
their army. Their men and horses were exhausted,

02:36:44.720 --> 02:36:53.040
and they increasingly longed to return to the&nbsp;
cool lands of Mongolia. Chinggis Khan sent word to

02:36:53.040 --> 02:36:59.680
the Jin emperor that he was willing to accept&nbsp;
terms for peace, with the following demands for

02:36:59.680 --> 02:37:10.279
tribute. God has made you so weak that should I&nbsp;
further molest you, I fear how Heaven would judge

02:37:10.279 --> 02:37:19.519
me. I'm willing to withdraw my army. What provision&nbsp;
will you make to still the demands of my officers?

02:37:20.680 --> 02:37:28.160
Many in the Jin court urged the emperor to&nbsp;
keep fighting. They argued that the shame of

02:37:28.160 --> 02:37:34.240
surrendering to these barbarians would be too&nbsp;
great for the dynasty to bear, and the city of

02:37:34.240 --> 02:37:41.920
Beijing could never be taken while a determined&nbsp;
force defended it. But luckily for the Mongols,

02:37:41.920 --> 02:37:49.520
the political situation in the Jin Empire was&nbsp;
rapidly disintegrating. Having lost the confidence

02:37:49.520 --> 02:37:56.359
of his court after two years of failure, the young&nbsp;
Golden Khan of the Jin, the Prince of Wei, had been

02:37:56.359 --> 02:38:03.960
assassinated the year earlier, and his nephew was&nbsp;
placed on the throne by a military coup. This man,

02:38:03.960 --> 02:38:12.160
named Xuanzong of Jin, was now facing another&nbsp;
plot in the palace that threatened to topple him.

02:38:12.160 --> 02:38:17.639
Rather than deal with both the Mongols and&nbsp;
his own treacherous courtiers, he decided to

02:38:17.640 --> 02:38:26.040
finally sue for peace. He accepted a humiliating&nbsp;
series of conditions, recognizing himself as a

02:38:26.040 --> 02:38:31.880
vassal to Chinggis Khan, giving the Khan one of&nbsp;
his daughters to marry, and massive amounts of

02:38:31.880 --> 02:38:41.520
gold, silver, and silk, along with 500 young men and&nbsp;
women of the court to take away as slaves. With

02:38:41.520 --> 02:38:49.440
these crushing terms, the war came to an end. The&nbsp;
lands of Northern China breathed a sigh of relief,

02:38:50.040 --> 02:38:59.960
and the Mongols rode north towards the Gobi Desert&nbsp;
and home. The Jin emperor had seemingly averted

02:38:59.960 --> 02:39:09.439
further disaster, but he would soon make a critical&nbsp;
mistake. Summer was still here, and the Gobi Desert

02:39:09.439 --> 02:39:16.799
was too hot to cross. For that reason, Chinggis&nbsp;
Khan camped on the southern side of the desert,

02:39:16.800 --> 02:39:22.080
and waited for the cool months to come&nbsp;
before they could return to Mongolia with the

02:39:22.080 --> 02:39:30.680
vast treasure of their successful raid in tow. But&nbsp;
then the Khan got news of something that would send

02:39:30.680 --> 02:39:41.600
him flying into a rage. Word reached him that the&nbsp;
new Jin emperor was fleeing Beijing. The embattled

02:39:41.600 --> 02:39:48.520
ruler was taking his forces and what remained of&nbsp;
his treasury with him, and retreating far into the

02:39:48.520 --> 02:39:55.640
south to the old fortress of Kaifeng on the other&nbsp;
side of the Yellow River, an obstacle that the

02:39:55.640 --> 02:40:03.800
Mongols had not yet been able to cross. This seemed&nbsp;
like a clear sign that the Jin did not intend to

02:40:03.800 --> 02:40:14.319
keep their word. One chronicler recalls the enraged&nbsp;
words of Chinggis Khan. The Jin emperor made an

02:40:14.319 --> 02:40:22.920
agreement with me, but now he has moved his capital&nbsp;
south. Evidently he mistrusts my word, and has

02:40:22.920 --> 02:40:32.080
used the peace to deceive me. Instead of crossing&nbsp;
the desert and returning to his own lands, Chinggis

02:40:32.080 --> 02:40:40.479
Khan wheeled his forces back around and marched&nbsp;
once again to the capital of Beijing. The writer

02:40:40.479 --> 02:40:52.160
Li Xinchuan describes what happened next. In moon five,&nbsp;
the Jin ruler moved the capital to Kaifeng. The Tartars

02:40:52.160 --> 02:40:59.120
heard about this and said, “To move right away after&nbsp;
making peace? This shows they are suspicious and

02:40:59.120 --> 02:41:06.920
still harbor resentment. They purposely talked&nbsp;
peace only as a means to forestall us.” In the

02:41:06.920 --> 02:41:15.520
autumn, moon eight, they again led troops to attack the&nbsp;
counties and prefectures of the central plains.

02:41:15.520 --> 02:41:24.439
With the emperor gone, along with all his&nbsp;
personal troops, the city's people were left all

02:41:24.439 --> 02:41:32.960
but defenseless. The remaining citizens’ garrison&nbsp;
of Beijing held out for eight agonizing months of

02:41:32.960 --> 02:41:43.439
siege. Starvation soon spread. The Jin made several&nbsp;
attempts to relieve the city from the south, but

02:41:43.439 --> 02:41:51.040
each army they sent was intercepted and ambushed&nbsp;
on the road. For the city’s defenders, it soon

02:41:51.040 --> 02:41:58.880
became clear that no reinforcements would be&nbsp;
coming. On this realization, whole divisions

02:41:58.880 --> 02:42:07.319
of Jin soldiers, particularly of the semi-nomadic&nbsp;
Khitan people, simply switched sides and joined the

02:42:07.319 --> 02:42:19.359
Mongols. On the 1st of June 1215, the Mongols&nbsp;
finally broke through the walls. As a punishment

02:42:19.359 --> 02:42:27.679
for holding out so long and for the betrayal&nbsp;
of the Jin emperor, the Mongols sacked the city,

02:42:27.680 --> 02:42:35.920
and huge numbers of its people were put to&nbsp;
the sword. The writer Li Xinchuan describes the

02:42:35.920 --> 02:42:45.600
destruction. The grandeur and beauty of Beijing's&nbsp;
palaces were the crowning achievement of ancient

02:42:45.600 --> 02:42:52.240
and modern times. When the Tartars saw them, they&nbsp;
were so stunned and frightened, they did not

02:42:52.240 --> 02:42:59.679
dare look up. Yet, not long afterward, the fires&nbsp;
set by their soldiers would burn for over a

02:42:59.680 --> 02:43:09.319
month. What had once been the golden Jin&nbsp;
Empire now fractured into countless feuding

02:43:09.319 --> 02:43:15.519
warlords fighting over territory, some&nbsp;
loyal to the Mongols; others defecting

02:43:15.520 --> 02:43:23.240
to the Song Chinese in the south, and many&nbsp;
others still simply out for themselves. All

02:43:23.240 --> 02:43:31.559
imperial authority north of the Yellow&nbsp;
River collapsed. One Jin Dynasty poet,

02:43:31.560 --> 02:43:38.800
a blind man named Zhao Yuan, wrote a poem&nbsp;
about this time that he called the Song of

02:43:38.800 --> 02:43:49.120
Helplessness. The eastern barbarians charge&nbsp;
and raid the fields of the western mountains.

02:43:49.120 --> 02:43:57.599
God willing, they will fester, but how so, I&nbsp;
do not ever know. As I sip wine and watch

02:43:57.600 --> 02:44:05.399
the years fleet by, I stumble, drunk, atop&nbsp;
the plateau, and sing the Song of Helplessness.

02:44:05.399 --> 02:44:16.759
With Beijing in ruins, Chinggis Khan&nbsp;
left one of his generals behind in China to mop up

02:44:16.760 --> 02:44:24.040
the remnants of the Jin, but it would not be&nbsp;
as easy as he thought, and the final conquest

02:44:24.040 --> 02:44:33.560
of Northern China would take many more years. In&nbsp;
the south, the Song Chinese watched the destruction

02:44:33.560 --> 02:44:41.800
with delight. Their old enemies had been utterly&nbsp;
smashed, and with the delightful irony that it

02:44:41.800 --> 02:44:51.600
had come at the hands of another barbarian people.&nbsp;
The writer Zhao Gong describes with amusement how

02:44:51.600 --> 02:44:58.040
members of the former Jin government and royal&nbsp;
family were now reduced to the level of manual

02:44:58.040 --> 02:45:04.720
laborers. There are great men of the&nbsp;
vanquished Jin who have gotten mixed

02:45:04.720 --> 02:45:11.160
up in odd jobs, falling as low as butchering&nbsp;
and peddling, or leaving to become bandits. All

02:45:11.160 --> 02:45:15.800
of them are still referred to by their&nbsp;
old government titles. One family has a

02:45:15.800 --> 02:45:20.560
number of men who push carts around the towns,&nbsp;
and who still call themselves Commissioner of

02:45:20.560 --> 02:45:29.080
Transport. The destruction of the Mongol&nbsp;
invasion left its marks everywhere in the

02:45:29.080 --> 02:45:37.000
landscape. City walls had been torn down. In&nbsp;
places, crops had been destroyed, since the

02:45:37.000 --> 02:45:42.399
Mongols deliberately rode their horses over&nbsp;
the fields so that the land could return to

02:45:42.399 --> 02:45:51.040
pastures for their animals. And the event sent&nbsp;
reverberations around the world. Sometime

02:45:51.040 --> 02:45:57.560
afterwards, a delegation of diplomats traveled&nbsp;
to China from the region of Central Asia to

02:45:57.560 --> 02:46:04.960
investigate what had happened. They arrived at&nbsp;
the ruins of Beijing, and the scenes of carnage

02:46:04.960 --> 02:46:11.359
that they witnessed, they later related to the&nbsp;
Persian scholar Juzjani, who recounts them like

02:46:11.359 --> 02:46:19.040
something out of a nightmare. When we arrived&nbsp;
near to the seat of the government of the Golden

02:46:19.040 --> 02:46:27.000
Khan, from a considerable distance, a high white&nbsp;
mound appeared in sight. We supposed that that

02:46:27.000 --> 02:46:32.800
white eminence was perhaps a hill of snow, and&nbsp;
we made inquiries of the guides and the people

02:46:32.800 --> 02:46:41.840
of that part about it. They replied, “The whole&nbsp;
of it is the bones of men slain.” When we had

02:46:41.840 --> 02:46:49.319
proceeded onwards another stage, the ground had&nbsp;
become so greasy and dark from human fat that it

02:46:49.319 --> 02:46:55.399
was necessary for us to advance another three&nbsp;
stages on that same road until we came to dry

02:46:55.399 --> 02:47:03.559
ground again. Through the infections arising from&nbsp;
that ground, some of our party became ill, and some

02:47:03.560 --> 02:47:13.080
perished. When they reached the city&nbsp;
walls, they found similar scenes of slaughter.

02:47:13.080 --> 02:47:21.439
On reaching the gate of the city,&nbsp;
we perceived in a place under a bastion

02:47:21.439 --> 02:47:29.399
of the citadel an immense quantity of human&nbsp;
bones collected. Inquiry was made, and people

02:47:29.399 --> 02:47:37.200
replied that on the day the city was captured,&nbsp;
60,000 young girls threw themselves from this

02:47:37.200 --> 02:47:42.120
bastion of the fortress and destroyed&nbsp;
themselves, in order that they might not

02:47:42.120 --> 02:47:48.840
fall captive into the hands of the Mongol&nbsp;
forces, and that all these were their bones.

02:47:54.279 --> 02:48:01.120
The scholar Juzjani was a fierce critic of&nbsp;
the Mongols, and has been criticized for his

02:48:01.120 --> 02:48:06.840
colorful exaggerations that occur&nbsp;
throughout his writings. He didn't

02:48:06.840 --> 02:48:13.279
witness these scenes himself, and may have&nbsp;
exaggerated stories told to him. But either

02:48:13.279 --> 02:48:19.240
way, it's clear that the destruction of&nbsp;
the Jin Dynasty left a terrible human

02:48:19.240 --> 02:48:30.399
toll. When summer ended, Chinggis Khan rode back&nbsp;
across the Gobi Desert with all the gold and

02:48:30.399 --> 02:48:38.359
assorted riches of Northern China packed on the&nbsp;
backs of his camels, leaving untold suffering

02:48:38.359 --> 02:48:47.439
behind him. The bounty of silk alone was so&nbsp;
great that Mongol soldiers ran out of uses

02:48:47.439 --> 02:48:55.040
for it. They began to use it as packing material&nbsp;
and rope to tie up their horses, and used silver

02:48:55.040 --> 02:49:03.120
jugs as water troughs for their animals.&nbsp;
Precious metals, slaves, and other treasure

02:49:03.120 --> 02:49:13.160
poured north back to Mongolia in a river of gold&nbsp;
that seemed never to end. The year was 1215; in the

02:49:13.160 --> 02:49:20.960
Chinese calendar, the Year of the Pig, and the&nbsp;
Mongol Empire was now among the wealthiest on

02:49:20.960 --> 02:49:37.720
Earth. History has remembered Chinggis Khan&nbsp;
as a bloodthirsty conqueror, a man hellbent

02:49:37.720 --> 02:49:45.520
on subjugating the known world, but in fact, most&nbsp;
sources suggest that when he left China, conquest

02:49:45.520 --> 02:49:54.600
was not the first thing on his mind. In fact, he&nbsp;
seemed satisfied. He had made his people wealthier

02:49:54.600 --> 02:50:02.720
than they had ever dreamed, and destroyed all&nbsp;
nearby rivals. He now controlled a vast swathe of

02:50:02.720 --> 02:50:09.960
territory that covered almost the entire length&nbsp;
of the Mongolian steppe and the Silk Road trade

02:50:09.960 --> 02:50:18.640
that flowed across it. The Persian scholar&nbsp;
Ata-Malik Juvaini elegises this time of relative peace.

02:50:20.760 --> 02:50:25.920
In the latter part of his reign, he had&nbsp;
brought about complete peace and quiet,

02:50:25.920 --> 02:50:34.040
and security and tranquility, and had achieved&nbsp;
the extreme of prosperity and well-being. The

02:50:34.040 --> 02:50:41.040
roads were secure and disturbances allayed, so&nbsp;
that whatever profit or gain was displayed

02:50:41.040 --> 02:50:48.640
in the uppermost west or the furthermost&nbsp;
east, there merchants would bend their steps.

02:50:50.680 --> 02:50:57.200
Chinggis Khan's empire now connected the wealthy&nbsp;
production areas of Song China with the rich

02:50:57.200 --> 02:51:04.080
markets of Persia, Central Asia, and the Near East,&nbsp;
and he wanted to make the most of this profitable

02:51:04.080 --> 02:51:10.160
route. When it came to the settled societies&nbsp;
that bordered him, he seems to have treated

02:51:10.160 --> 02:51:18.639
his neighbors not as enemies to be conquered,&nbsp;
but as potential future customers. For years now,

02:51:18.640 --> 02:51:24.040
he had been exchanging diplomatic missions&nbsp;
with his neighbors to the west, and in the

02:51:24.040 --> 02:51:32.920
year 1218, this culminated in the sending of&nbsp;
a great trade delegation. This was a caravan

02:51:32.920 --> 02:51:42.200
of hundreds of Bactrian camels, along with 450&nbsp;
merchants led by an Indian man named Jafar, who

02:51:42.200 --> 02:51:48.800
were ordered to head into the west and contact&nbsp;
the wealthy empires that existed there in what is

02:51:48.800 --> 02:51:55.720
today Iran, Turkmenistan, and Uzbekistan.&nbsp;
With them, they brought an enormous

02:51:55.720 --> 02:52:02.479
wealth of goods to trade, as Juzjani recounts,&nbsp;
with perhaps some of his characteristic

02:52:02.479 --> 02:52:10.839
exaggeration. Among the rarities and presents that&nbsp;
the Chenggis Khan sent was a nugget of pure gold as

02:52:10.840 --> 02:52:17.640
big as a camel's neck. Also, he dispatched 500&nbsp;
camels laden with gold, silver, and silks, beaver

02:52:17.640 --> 02:52:26.760
furs, sable, and elegant and ingenious things of&nbsp;
China and the desert regions. This trade delegation

02:52:26.760 --> 02:52:33.720
was a clear statement of the new empire's power&nbsp;
and wealth, all of it looted from the coffers of

02:52:33.720 --> 02:52:41.319
Northern China. It's likely that a large portion&nbsp;
of the Mongol elite had invested their treasure

02:52:41.319 --> 02:52:48.719
in this expedition and had bet heavily on its&nbsp;
success. For this reason, Chinggis Khan's reputation

02:52:48.720 --> 02:52:55.960
among the Mongol lords was also at stake.&nbsp;
During the cooler autumn months, this trade

02:52:55.960 --> 02:53:02.200
caravan traveled for several weeks through&nbsp;
Mongolia, across the Altai Mountains, and over

02:53:02.200 --> 02:53:09.840
the grasslands and deserts of what is today&nbsp;
Kazakhstan. Finally, in November, they arrived

02:53:09.840 --> 02:53:18.440
at the border of what was then the largest&nbsp;Muslim
kingdom in the world, the empire of Khwarazm.

02:53:24.960 --> 02:53:34.120
Khwarazm was a relatively new power. Only a century&nbsp;
earlier, it had been a small kingdom centered on

02:53:34.120 --> 02:53:42.519
the powerful city of Gurganj in the Khwarazmian
oasis. Here, the lands are watered by the two great

02:53:42.520 --> 02:53:50.800
rivers Syr Darya and Amu Darya, which flow down from&nbsp;
the Tian Shan mountains of Kyrgyzstan and

02:53:50.800 --> 02:54:00.080
the Pamir mountains north of the Hindu Kush. The&nbsp;
oasis cities along these two rivers, Balkh and Bukhara,

02:54:00.080 --> 02:54:08.080
Samarqand and Merv, were enticing stops after the long&nbsp;
weeks on the desert roads, and for centuries they

02:54:08.080 --> 02:54:16.640
had swelled with wealth from Silk Road trade. With&nbsp;
these riches they had irrigated their arid lands

02:54:16.640 --> 02:54:23.680
until they bloomed and fed vast and thriving&nbsp;
populations. But over the preceding century,

02:54:23.680 --> 02:54:30.600
the Turkic rulers of Gurganj had formed a fruitful&nbsp;
partnership with the nomadic people known as the

02:54:30.600 --> 02:54:37.760
Kipchaks, and had recently used their powerful&nbsp;
cavalry armies to expand into Turkmenistan and

02:54:37.760 --> 02:54:46.399
Afghanistan, and spilled south into the mountains&nbsp;
of Persia. The Khwarazmian Empire was now the largest

02:54:46.399 --> 02:54:54.439
and wealthiest Muslim power on the planet. The&nbsp;
Persian scholar Ata-Malik Juvaini records the

02:54:54.439 --> 02:55:04.080
beauty of this region. Khwarazma to me is the best of&nbsp;
lands. May its rain-giving clouds never be blown

02:55:04.080 --> 02:55:11.880
away. It was the site of the throne of the sultans&nbsp;
of the world. Its corners supported the shoulders of

02:55:11.880 --> 02:55:18.319
the great men of the age. Its mansions were&nbsp;
resplendant with every kind of lofty idea,

02:55:18.840 --> 02:55:25.439
and its regions and districts were so many&nbsp;
rose gardens; such was the state of that country.

02:55:25.439 --> 02:55:37.200
The ruler of the new empire of Khwarazm was&nbsp;
known as the Khwarazm-Shah, and his name was Ala ad-Din

02:55:37.200 --> 02:55:46.000
Muhammad. He was a warrior and a conqueror, and&nbsp;
proud of it. He had inherited a powerful kingdom

02:55:46.000 --> 02:55:52.560
from his father, and over the last two decades&nbsp;
had expanded its borders even further into a true

02:55:52.560 --> 02:56:00.720
empire. Some in his court even flattered him that&nbsp;
he was the new Alexander, that legends of his

02:56:00.720 --> 02:56:10.160
conquests would be told for centuries to come.&nbsp;
This flattery made him bold, but also rash and

02:56:10.160 --> 02:56:18.319
impulsive. This proud Shah had agreed to receive&nbsp;
the Mongol trade delegation, along with Chinggis

02:56:18.319 --> 02:56:27.599
Khan's offer of friendship, as Juzjani recalls. The&nbsp;
Chenggis Khan sent a great number of offerings and

02:56:27.600 --> 02:56:35.279
said, “Say unto the Khwarazm-Shah, I am the sovereign&nbsp;
of the sunrise, and thou the sovereign of the

02:56:35.279 --> 02:56:42.359
sunset. Let there be between us a firm treaty of&nbsp;
friendship and peace, and let traders and caravans

02:56:42.359 --> 02:56:52.960
on both sides come and go.” But when the merchants&nbsp;
arrived in the borderlands of Khwarazm, they ran into

02:56:52.960 --> 02:57:06.279
trouble. The first Khwarazmian town they arrived in&nbsp;
was named Otrar. It sat in the middle of an oasis

02:57:06.279 --> 02:57:13.040
on the Syr Darya River, and as a crucial junction&nbsp;
of several major roads, it was a quintessential

02:57:13.040 --> 02:57:19.000
Silk Road trading town. If you walked its streets&nbsp;
during this time, they would have been heaving

02:57:19.000 --> 02:57:25.439
with merchant traffic, sounds of prayer from&nbsp;
the mosques, vendors crying their wares, and the

02:57:25.439 --> 02:57:32.879
sounds of camels noisily watering after long&nbsp;
days on the desert roads. But the governor of

02:57:32.880 --> 02:57:41.640
Otrar had a foolhardy nature. His name was&nbsp;Inalchuq,
and he was an uncle of the Khwarazm-Shah,

02:57:41.640 --> 02:57:48.439
the brother of the Shah's mother, and this&nbsp;
gave him a great deal of power. The Shah

02:57:48.439 --> 02:57:54.799
Ala ad-Din Muhammad had a complicated relationship&nbsp;
with his mother, and she had amassed a great deal

02:57:54.800 --> 02:58:02.720
of influence at court. Some even whispered that&nbsp;
she was the real power behind the throne, and so,

02:58:02.720 --> 02:58:10.600
her brother Inalchuq may have believed he could&nbsp;
do whatever he pleased. When he saw the Mongol

02:58:10.600 --> 02:58:18.160
caravan passing through his lands, packed with&nbsp;
gold and fine silks, Inalchuq hungered after their

02:58:18.160 --> 02:58:28.760
cargo. Some sources claim that he acted on the&nbsp;
orders of the Shah himself, while others say

02:58:28.760 --> 02:58:35.520
that he acted alone, but we know that when the&nbsp;
caravan passed through Otrar, Inalchuq accused

02:58:35.520 --> 02:58:44.880
the merchants of being spies. He ordered that they&nbsp;
be arrested immediately and their goods seized. In

02:58:44.880 --> 02:58:50.840
the struggle, the merchants were killed, and their&nbsp;
gold and silks and other goods were taken to the

02:58:50.840 --> 02:59:01.000
great market town of Bukhara, where they were sold,&nbsp;
and the governor, Inalchuq of Otrar, took his cut.

02:59:01.000 --> 02:59:07.479
He had just become a great deal richer, he might&nbsp;
have thought, and what were a bunch of barbarian

02:59:07.479 --> 02:59:18.239
horsemen 3,000 km away going to do about it? Ata-Malik
Juvaini describes the magnitude of this man's

02:59:18.239 --> 02:59:29.840
mistake. In executing his command, he deprived&nbsp;
these men of their lives and possessions. Nay;

02:59:29.840 --> 02:59:36.680
rather, he desolated and laid waste a whole&nbsp;
world. For every drop of their blood, there

02:59:36.680 --> 02:59:43.960
would flow a whole river. In retribution for&nbsp;
every hair on their heads, a 100,000 heads

02:59:43.960 --> 02:59:54.620
would roll in the dust at every crossroad. In&nbsp;
exchange for every dinar, a thousand were

02:59:54.620 --> 03:00:00.880
exacted. Far away in the Mongol heartlands, on the

03:00:00.880 --> 03:00:05.720
banks of the Onon River, a storm&nbsp;
was brewing in the court of the Khan.

03:00:05.720 --> 03:00:19.880
Chinggis Khan was naturally offended when he&nbsp;
got word of the attack on his merchants,

03:00:19.880 --> 03:00:26.479
but he assumed there must have been some mistake.&nbsp;
He sent an envoy of three ambassadors to seek an

03:00:26.479 --> 03:00:35.040
audience with the Khwarazm-Shah, and to ask for his&nbsp;
uncle Inalchuq to be handed over for punishment. But

03:00:35.040 --> 03:00:44.880
the Khwarazm-Shah, perhaps feeling his mother breathing&nbsp;
down his neck, refused the Khan's demands, and to

03:00:44.880 --> 03:00:52.239
make matters worse, he attempted what he must have&nbsp;
hoped would look like a show of strength. When

03:00:52.239 --> 03:01:00.239
the Khan's ambassadors came before him, he had one&nbsp;
of them killed on the spot. Then he rounded on the

03:01:00.239 --> 03:01:07.760
other two. He ordered that their beards be shaved&nbsp;
and that they be sent back to Mongolia with their

03:01:07.760 --> 03:01:15.359
humiliation as an answer to the Khan. When these&nbsp;
ambassadors returned to Mongolia with their

03:01:15.359 --> 03:01:25.960
faces shorn and the Shah's words on their lips,&nbsp;
Chinggis Khan's rage was seismic. Just

03:01:25.960 --> 03:01:32.560
as he had done before his invasion of China, he&nbsp;
climbed to the top of the sacred mountain Burkan

03:01:32.560 --> 03:01:39.800
Khaldun, up through the broken stones and whispering&nbsp;
pine needles, and there with the Mongolian wind

03:01:39.800 --> 03:01:48.239
battering around him, asked the god of the Great&nbsp;
Blue Sky what he should do. The Secret History

03:01:48.239 --> 03:01:57.239
records what answer he received. These tidings&nbsp;
had such an effect upon the Khan's mind that

03:01:57.239 --> 03:02:03.719
the whirlwind of anger flared up with such&nbsp;
a flame that it could be quenched only by

03:02:03.720 --> 03:02:10.439
the shedding of blood. In this fever, Chinggis&nbsp;
Khan went up alone to the summit of a hill,

03:02:10.439 --> 03:02:18.200
bared his head, turned his face towards the Earth,&nbsp;
and for three days and nights offered up prayer,

03:02:18.200 --> 03:02:25.040
saying, “I was not the author of this&nbsp;
trouble. Grant me strength to exact

03:02:25.040 --> 03:02:47.840
vengeance.” Thereupon, he descended from the hill,&nbsp;
meditating action, and making ready for war.

03:02:53.760 --> 03:03:03.880
In the year 1219, Chinggis Khan gathered a vast&nbsp;
force of warriors. At perhaps as many as 200,000

03:03:03.880 --> 03:03:10.560
men, it may have been twice the size the&nbsp;
force that had devastated Jin China. Along with

03:03:10.560 --> 03:03:18.239
his usual horde of nomadic horsemen, he brought&nbsp;
powerful new units of Chinese siege engineers,

03:03:18.239 --> 03:03:24.760
experts at cracking open city walls with&nbsp;
a variety of ingenious engines, and with

03:03:24.760 --> 03:03:32.800
that horde, he marched west. Ahead of him&nbsp;
was a journey of thousands of kilometers,

03:03:32.800 --> 03:03:47.840
over deserts and mountains, but steadily&nbsp;
the doom of the Khwarazmian Empire drew near.

03:03:47.840 --> 03:03:55.319
Juvaini describes the sight that the governor of Otrar&nbsp;
saw arriving one day in December in a thunderous

03:03:55.319 --> 03:04:05.679
cataclysm outside his city walls. He bit the back&nbsp;
of his hand in amazement at the unexpected sight,

03:04:05.680 --> 03:04:11.600
for he perceived that the plain had become a&nbsp;
tossing sea of countless hosts and splendid

03:04:11.600 --> 03:04:17.880
troops, while the air was full of clamor and&nbsp;
uproar and the neighing of armored horses and

03:04:17.880 --> 03:04:26.120
the roaring of mail-clad lions. The air became&nbsp;
blue, the Earth ebony; the sea boiled with the

03:04:26.120 --> 03:04:33.840
noise of the drums. With his fingers he pointed to&nbsp;
the army on the plain, a host to which there was no

03:04:33.840 --> 03:04:47.800
end. The Khwarazm-Shah had expected the arrival of&nbsp;
the Mongol forces, but he had dramatically

03:04:47.800 --> 03:04:53.439
miscalculated the kind of response that&nbsp;
Chinggis Khan would give him. He himself

03:04:53.439 --> 03:04:59.759
commanded a force of perhaps 400,000 men,&nbsp;
twice the size of the Mongol armies, and

03:04:59.760 --> 03:05:06.200
his cities were among the most fortified in&nbsp;
the world. He was sure that if he shut up his

03:05:06.200 --> 03:05:12.599
armies in his great walled fortresses, the&nbsp;
Mongols would soon run out of farms to burn

03:05:12.600 --> 03:05:20.479
and sheep herders to rob, and would eventually&nbsp;
go home, but this would not turn out to be the

03:05:20.479 --> 03:05:32.719
case. The moment the Mongols arrived, their Chinese&nbsp;
siege engineers began to build their engines. Otrar's

03:05:32.720 --> 03:05:40.560
defenses were formidable, but even these didn't&nbsp;
hold out for long. The Persian scholar Juzjani, a

03:05:40.560 --> 03:05:47.000
citizen of the Khwarazmian Empire, who would flee to&nbsp;
India after the Mongol invasion, writes about

03:05:47.000 --> 03:05:57.439
what happened next. In a short time, they took Otrar.&nbsp;
They put both small and great, young and old, to the

03:05:57.439 --> 03:06:07.839
sword, and left not a soul alive. They martyred the&nbsp;
whole of them. The governor of Otrar, Inalchuq, was

03:06:07.840 --> 03:06:16.160
taken alive. To punish him for his greed in seizing&nbsp;
the merchant's gold, Chinggis Khan ordered that he

03:06:16.160 --> 03:06:25.239
be executed with a cruelly-fitting punishment. He had&nbsp;
a great quantity of silver melted down, reaching

03:06:25.239 --> 03:06:34.000
temperatures of nearly 1,000°, and then poured the&nbsp;
searing molten metal into the man's mouth, eyes,

03:06:34.000 --> 03:06:42.880
and ears. The city of Otrar was destroyed and its&nbsp;
people slaughtered, its remains a shattered sight

03:06:42.880 --> 03:06:52.866
rising from the arid plains in ragged heaps of&nbsp;
fallen stone. But the rage of the Khan had only just

03:06:52.880 --> 03:07:21.920
begun. Otrar sat on the Syr Darya River,&nbsp;
which formed the northernmost border

03:07:21.920 --> 03:07:29.920
of the Khwarazmian Empire. Several hundred
kilometers to the south, another river, the Amu

03:07:29.920 --> 03:07:35.840
Darya, ran almost parallel to it, and on its&nbsp;
banks stood the wealthiest cities of

03:07:35.840 --> 03:07:47.440
the region; the booming metropolis of Samarqand&nbsp;
and the scholarly religious heart of Bukhara.

03:07:50.439 --> 03:07:57.799
The 10th-century Iranian author, Istakhri, who traveled&nbsp;
in the region, provides a vivid description of its

03:07:57.800 --> 03:08:07.160
pleasant landscape. I know no place in it or in&nbsp;
Samarqand itself where if one ascends some elevated

03:08:07.160 --> 03:08:15.760
ground, one does not see greenery and a pleasant&nbsp;
place. The land extends eight days’ travel through

03:08:15.760 --> 03:08:23.080
unbroken greenery and gardens along both sides of&nbsp;
the river, and beyond these fields is pasture for

03:08:23.080 --> 03:08:31.239
flocks. Every town and settlement has a fortress.&nbsp;
It is the most fruitful of all the countries of

03:08:31.239 --> 03:08:39.439
Allah. In it are the best trees and fruits. In&nbsp;
every home are gardens, cisterns, and flowing

03:08:39.439 --> 03:08:48.519
water. It was on these cities&nbsp;
that Chinggis Khan now set his

03:08:48.520 --> 03:08:58.319
sights, but reaching these wealthy cities would&nbsp;
be no easy feat. Between the Mongol armies and

03:08:58.319 --> 03:09:08.160
the walls of Samarqand and Bukhara lay more than 500&nbsp;
km of sandy desert known as the Kyzylkum, a name

03:09:08.160 --> 03:09:16.439
which means ‘red sands’ in Turkic languages.&nbsp;
This desert was baking hot, and even trade

03:09:16.439 --> 03:09:23.799
caravans would skirt around its edges rather&nbsp;
than risk death in the wastes. The citizens of

03:09:23.800 --> 03:09:30.040
Bukhara and Samarqand had heard about the arrival&nbsp;
of the Mongols in the north, but they were not

03:09:30.040 --> 03:09:36.319
particularly worried. Tribal nomads had raided&nbsp;
along the northern riverlands before, but no

03:09:36.319 --> 03:09:47.319
large army could cross the Kyzylkum Desert. But&nbsp;
they had severely underestimated the Mongols.

03:09:49.319 --> 03:09:57.399
Chinggis Khan left his two middle sons, Chaghatai&nbsp;
and Ogedei, to finish up the siege of Otrar, with

03:09:57.399 --> 03:10:05.200
his eldest son Jochi taking an army north&nbsp;
towards the Aral Sea. Meanwhile, he sent

03:10:05.200 --> 03:10:12.040
two small armies southward into the Fergana&nbsp;
Valley, with instructions to hunt down and

03:10:12.040 --> 03:10:19.439
kill the Shah Muhammad. But Chinggis Khan&nbsp;
himself, accompanied by his youngest son

03:10:19.439 --> 03:10:26.239
Tolui, was determined to do what others had&nbsp;
considered impossible; to cross the Kyzylkum

03:10:26.239 --> 03:10:33.960
Desert with 30,000 horses and strike right at&nbsp;
the heart of the empire, the religious center of

03:10:33.960 --> 03:10:43.960
Bukhara. The crossing would have been hard. Chinggis&nbsp;
Khan employed local men who knew the hidden paths

03:10:43.960 --> 03:10:51.880
through the wastes and the best time of year to&nbsp;
make the journey. In the colder winter months, dew

03:10:51.880 --> 03:10:59.680
would sometimes form on the ground in certain&nbsp;
places, and small plants could grow. With this

03:10:59.680 --> 03:11:06.680
help, the army successfully made the crossing, and&nbsp;
arrived on the other side on the 7th of February

03:11:06.680 --> 03:11:17.240
1220.Ata Malik Juvaini describes the sight that the&nbsp;
citizens of Bukhara saw outside their city walls.

03:11:19.399 --> 03:11:27.239
In the morning, Chinggis Khan arrived unexpectedly&nbsp;
before the town. When the inhabitants, unaware,

03:11:27.239 --> 03:11:33.639
beheld the surrounding countryside choked with&nbsp;
horsemen and the air black as night with a dust

03:11:33.640 --> 03:11:41.640
of cavalry, fright and panic overcame them,&nbsp;
and fear and dread prevailed. His troops

03:11:41.640 --> 03:11:50.000
were more numerous than ants or locusts, being&nbsp;
in their multitude beyond estimation or computation.

03:11:50.000 --> 03:11:57.319
Detachment after detachment arrived, each like&nbsp;
a billowing sea, and encamped round about the

03:11:57.319 --> 03:12:07.439
town. At the sight of this force, the 20,000&nbsp;
or so soldiers stationed at Bukhara lost all

03:12:07.439 --> 03:12:14.200
hope of defending their city. When night&nbsp;
fell, they attempted to flee under cover

03:12:14.200 --> 03:12:20.279
of darkness, but the Mongols spotted&nbsp;
them and simply chased them down on

03:12:20.279 --> 03:12:26.519
the plains. By the light of the moon, the&nbsp;
Mongol horsemen hunted and killed every

03:12:26.520 --> 03:12:33.439
single soldier as though chasing deer on&nbsp;
the steppe. The city of Bukhara surrendered

03:12:33.439 --> 03:12:40.919
within three days and opened its gates, with only a&nbsp;
determined core of soldiers holed up in its inner

03:12:40.920 --> 03:12:51.520
citadel. Intriguingly, it's in this moment that we&nbsp;
have the only purported instance of Chinggis Khan

03:12:51.520 --> 03:12:57.720
ever setting foot inside a city. Usually when&nbsp;
it became clear that a settlement was about to

03:12:57.720 --> 03:13:03.840
fall to his soldiers, the Khan would leave one of&nbsp;
his generals to loot the place, while he would

03:13:03.840 --> 03:13:11.920
return to his camp and his felt-walled tent, his&nbsp;
job done. It's clear he had a powerful distaste

03:13:11.920 --> 03:13:19.520
for cities and for anyone who would voluntarily&nbsp;
imprison themselves within their walls and foul-

03:13:19.520 --> 03:13:27.960
smelling streets. But when Bukhara opened its great&nbsp;
gate, the Persian sources describe him riding into

03:13:27.960 --> 03:13:36.200
its streets. Bukhara was one of the religious centers&nbsp;
of the Muslim world at the time, and its reputation

03:13:36.200 --> 03:13:44.080
was known far and wide, but the Khan likely hated&nbsp;
what he saw. We can imagine him wrinkling his

03:13:44.080 --> 03:13:50.720
nose at the pungent aromas of the medieval city;&nbsp;
the rats scuttling through the sewers and fish

03:13:50.720 --> 03:13:58.239
markets and tanneries, the clouds of flies circling&nbsp;
over rotting midden heaps and dung hills, all of

03:13:58.239 --> 03:14:06.359
it so different to the fresh, open grasslands&nbsp;
that he knew and loved. He went straight to the

03:14:06.359 --> 03:14:12.920
largest and grandest building, the great mosque&nbsp;
of the city, which was famed across the Muslim

03:14:12.920 --> 03:14:22.160
world for its size and opulence. This, he assumed,
must be the house of the king, as Ata-Malik Juvaini

03:14:22.160 --> 03:14:31.279
recounts. Chinggis Khan asked those present&nbsp;
whether this were the place of the sultan. They

03:14:31.279 --> 03:14:38.399
replied that it was the house of God. Then he, too,&nbsp;
got down from the horse, and mounting two or three

03:14:38.399 --> 03:14:46.399
steps of the pulpit, he exclaimed, “The countryside&nbsp;
is empty of food. Fill our horses’ bellies.” The

03:14:46.399 --> 03:14:52.799
Mongols brought the cases in which the Korans&nbsp;
were kept out into the courtyard of the mosque,

03:14:52.800 --> 03:15:02.660
where they cast the Korans right and left, and&nbsp;
turned the cases into mangers for their horses.

03:15:02.660 --> 03:15:10.359
Then Chinggis Khan gathered&nbsp;
the common people of the city in

03:15:10.359 --> 03:15:16.960
the great mosque of Bukhara, with the pages&nbsp;
of the Korans still littering the floor.

03:15:17.960 --> 03:15:25.680
The people must have been terrified, shaking&nbsp;
with fear, praying, and weeping softly. Then, over

03:15:25.680 --> 03:15:34.680
their heads, the Great Khan's voice rang out.
He mounted the pulpit in the festival prayer

03:15:34.680 --> 03:15:42.319
space and said, “Oh people, know that you are great&nbsp;
sinners and your leaders are at the head of the

03:15:42.319 --> 03:15:50.359
pack in sin. You ask me why I say this; I say&nbsp;
it because I am the scourge of God. If great

03:15:50.359 --> 03:15:57.080
sins had not been committed by you, the great&nbsp;
God would not have sent you one like me as a

03:15:57.080 --> 03:16:07.519
torment.” We don't know if this event truly&nbsp;
took place as Juvaini describes. He was not

03:16:07.520 --> 03:16:14.319
old enough to witness it himself, but may have&nbsp;
heard it secondhand, or perhaps this episode

03:16:14.319 --> 03:16:20.160
was an invention of the writer, designed&nbsp;
to make sense of what happened and explain the

03:16:20.160 --> 03:16:26.120
destruction of the Mongol invasion in terms&nbsp;
that his Muslim readers could understand, as

03:16:26.120 --> 03:16:34.199
a judgment of God. But either way, we know&nbsp;
what happened next. The citizens of Bukhara

03:16:34.199 --> 03:16:41.359
were rounded up and driven towards the citadel,
where the Shah's forces were still resisting.

03:16:41.359 --> 03:16:47.040
Just as in China, the citizens were forced&nbsp;
to dismantle their own city's defenses, and

03:16:47.040 --> 03:16:55.160
their bodies piled up below the walls. Against&nbsp;
this onslaught, the citadel of Bukhara didn't

03:16:55.160 --> 03:17:03.399
last long. Chinggis Khan now wielded an army that&nbsp;
combined the strength and mobility of the steppe

03:17:03.399 --> 03:17:12.160
warrior with the technological ingenuity of the&nbsp;
Chinese. The combination was terrifying, as Juvaini

03:17:12.160 --> 03:17:21.559
describes. On the outside, catapults were&nbsp;
erected, bows bent, and stones and arrows

03:17:21.560 --> 03:17:28.720
discharged, and on the inside, ballistas&nbsp;
and pots of naphtha were set in motion. It

03:17:28.720 --> 03:17:34.239
was like a red-hot furnace fed from&nbsp;
without by hard sticks, while from the

03:17:34.239 --> 03:17:39.840
belly of the furnace, sparks shoot into&nbsp;
the air. For days they fought in this manner.

03:17:39.840 --> 03:17:49.479
When the citadel finally fell, Chinggis Khan&nbsp;
ordered the city walls to be demolished utterly,

03:17:49.479 --> 03:17:56.559
and all the soldiers inside were slaughtered. But&nbsp;
in return for their speedy surrender, the citizens

03:17:56.560 --> 03:18:04.760
of the wider city were spared. Juvaini recalls&nbsp;the
simple proposition he offered to the Khwarazmian

03:18:04.760 --> 03:18:16.160
people. Let the emirs and great ones and the&nbsp;
numerous common people know this; that all the

03:18:16.160 --> 03:18:25.840
face of the Earth, from the going up of the sun to&nbsp;
his going down, I have given unto the Khan. Whosoever

03:18:25.840 --> 03:18:34.359
shall submit, mercy shall be shown to him and&nbsp;
to his wives and children and household, but

03:18:34.359 --> 03:18:46.719
whosoever shall not submit shall perish together&nbsp;
with all his wives and children and kinsmen.

03:18:47.319 --> 03:18:54.399
This strategy of calculated leniency and&nbsp;
brutality was ruthlessly effective, but

03:18:54.399 --> 03:19:01.559
it could only work if word got around. For&nbsp;
this reason, Chinggis Khan would always allow

03:19:01.560 --> 03:19:08.279
refugees to flood into other cities around the&nbsp;
region, filling people's heads with stories of

03:19:08.279 --> 03:19:16.880
the vast destruction visited on all who opposed&nbsp;
the Khan, and his mercy to those who bent the knee.

03:19:16.880 --> 03:19:23.319
The Arab writer Ibn Al-Athir, living in Mosul&nbsp;
at the time, recounts the effect of these

03:19:23.319 --> 03:19:32.399
increasingly outlandish rumors. These Tartars,&nbsp;
may God confound them, came from the east and

03:19:32.399 --> 03:19:39.279
wrought deeds which horrify all who hear of&nbsp;
them. Stories have been related to me which the

03:19:39.279 --> 03:19:46.639
hearer can scarcely credit as to the terror of the&nbsp;
Tartars, which God Almighty cast into men's heart.

03:19:49.479 --> 03:19:54.239
This was one of the most effective&nbsp;
propaganda campaigns in history, and

03:19:54.239 --> 03:20:01.719
the strategy paid off. With the siege of&nbsp;
Bukhara completed, Chinggis Khan now swung

03:20:01.720 --> 03:20:05.319
around and bore down on the wealthy metropolis of

03:20:05.319 --> 03:20:16.880
Samarqand. Samarqand was not just a booming trade hub;
it was also a mighty fortress, and considered by many to

03:20:16.880 --> 03:20:25.840
be impregnable. It was defended by a large army,&nbsp;
even including twenty war elephants brought from India,

03:20:25.840 --> 03:20:31.880
but at the sight of the Mongol force approaching,&nbsp;
and with refugees in its streets spreading tales

03:20:31.880 --> 03:20:40.920
of terror, the army tasked with guarding its walls&nbsp;
simply threw down their spears and surrendered. At

03:20:40.920 --> 03:20:47.000
the time of prayer, they opened the gate and&nbsp;
closed the door of resistance. The Mongols

03:20:47.000 --> 03:20:53.840
then entered and that day busied themselves with&nbsp;
the destruction of the town and its defenses. The

03:20:53.840 --> 03:21:00.160
inhabitants drew their feet beneath the&nbsp;
skirt of security, and the Mongols in no

03:21:00.160 --> 03:21:10.639
way molested them. The fall of Samarqand provided&nbsp;
uncountable amounts of loot, and the Mongols

03:21:10.640 --> 03:21:18.479
now found themselves the new owners of some&nbsp;
exotic novelties, the twenty Indian war elephants

03:21:18.479 --> 03:21:25.439
that the Shah had used in his army. But&nbsp;
Chinggis Khan had little use for these

03:21:25.439 --> 03:21:34.359
beasts. The elephant handlers brought their&nbsp;
elephants to Chinggis Khan and demanded elephant

03:21:34.359 --> 03:21:40.960
food. He asked them what the elephants had&nbsp;
lived on before they fell into captivity.

03:21:40.960 --> 03:21:47.439
They replied, the grass of the plains. When&nbsp;
he heard this, he ordered the elephants

03:21:47.439 --> 03:21:55.160
be set free to forage for themselves. They were&nbsp;
accordingly released, and in the end, perished of

03:21:55.160 --> 03:22:06.519
hunger. In return for surrendering, the citizens of&nbsp;
Samarqand were spared a massacre, but in other places

03:22:06.520 --> 03:22:13.120
that surrendered, the Mongols’ restraint&nbsp;
was misinterpreted as weakness. This was

03:22:13.120 --> 03:22:21.599
when things could get ugly. One such&nbsp;
example was the Khwarazmian city of Nishapur.

03:22:21.600 --> 03:22:27.840
Nishapur was the largest metropolitan city&nbsp;
on the Silk Road, a vast and wealthy place

03:22:27.840 --> 03:22:34.560
in what is today northeastern Iran. It&nbsp;
sat in a fertile plain at the foot of

03:22:34.560 --> 03:22:42.160
the Binalud mountain range in a region&nbsp;
known as Khorasan. Juvaini describes its

03:22:42.160 --> 03:22:51.960
beauty. If the Earth may be compared to the&nbsp;
heavens, then the lands are like its stars,

03:22:51.960 --> 03:22:59.840
and Nishapur among these stars is like the&nbsp;
fair Venus of the skies. What are men doing

03:22:59.840 --> 03:23:07.560
in Baghdad and Kufa seeing that Nishapur is&nbsp;
upon the Earth? For if there be a paradise on

03:23:07.560 --> 03:23:16.440
the face of the Earth, it is this, and if it is&nbsp;
not a paradise, then there is no paradise at all.

03:23:19.520 --> 03:23:28.479
The Mongols arrived at Nishapur in 1221 AD, and at&nbsp;
first, the city took the Khan's deal. It opened its

03:23:28.479 --> 03:23:36.599
gates and its treasuries to the Mongols, but then&nbsp;
the Mongol army departed with their riches, and

03:23:36.600 --> 03:23:44.359
left behind only a handful of governors to keep&nbsp;
their hold on the city. The citizens of Nishapur

03:23:44.359 --> 03:23:51.519
took this withdrawal as a sign that the Mongols&nbsp;
didn't intend to hold it. They soon revolted,

03:23:51.520 --> 03:23:59.399
killed the small number of Mongol governors, and&nbsp;
locked their gates. When they got word of this, the

03:23:59.399 --> 03:24:09.040
Khan's armies swung back around and laid sieged&nbsp;
the city. Still, its fate was not entirely sealed;

03:24:09.040 --> 03:24:16.359
that was until a single arrow flew down from the&nbsp;
city walls and struck one of the Mongol attackers,

03:24:17.199 --> 03:24:23.000
killing him. Unfortunately for the&nbsp;
people of Nishapur, he was the husband

03:24:23.000 --> 03:24:29.199
of one of Chinggis Khan's daughters, the&nbsp;
Great Khan's son-in-law, a man named

03:24:29.199 --> 03:24:39.359
Tokachar. Until the third day they fought&nbsp;
fiercely from the tower of Qara-Qush, and

03:24:39.359 --> 03:24:46.439
discharged quarrels and arrows from the&nbsp;
walls and ramparts. By an evil chance

03:24:46.439 --> 03:24:52.759
which was to be the bane of all that&nbsp;
people, an arrow was let fly, whereby Tokachar

03:24:52.760 --> 03:24:59.560
fell lifeless, the townsmen having made&nbsp;
an end of him without recognizing his person.

03:24:59.560 --> 03:25:10.399
The death of a member of the Mongol&nbsp;
royal bloodline was something that Chinggis

03:25:10.399 --> 03:25:18.160
Khan took extremely seriously. When the city finally&nbsp;
fell, he called upon on his widowed daughter, and

03:25:18.160 --> 03:25:25.040
told her that she would be allowed to decide&nbsp;
the fate of Nishapur. In her grief and rage,

03:25:25.040 --> 03:25:31.840
she ordered that the city be utterly destroyed&nbsp;
and every living thing within its walls put to

03:25:31.840 --> 03:25:42.720
death. They then drove all the survivors, men and&nbsp;
women, out onto the plain, and in order to avenge

03:25:42.720 --> 03:25:49.199
Tokachar, it was commanded that the town should be&nbsp;
laid waste in such a manner that the site

03:25:49.199 --> 03:25:56.439
could be plowed upon, and that in the exaction of&nbsp;
vengeance, not even cats and dogs would be left

03:25:56.439 --> 03:26:08.439
alive. The destruction of the city was&nbsp;
total, and the vengeance of the Khan

03:26:08.439 --> 03:26:16.239
remorseless in its totality. They severed&nbsp;
the heads of the slain from their bodies

03:26:17.000 --> 03:26:23.560
and heaped them up in piles, keeping those of&nbsp;
the men separate from those of the women and

03:26:23.560 --> 03:26:30.720
children. Abodes and dwelling places were&nbsp;
leveled with the dust. Rose gardens became

03:26:30.720 --> 03:26:44.439
furnaces. After the fall of the empire's most&nbsp;powerful
fortress of Samarqand, the Khwarazmian Shah truly

03:26:44.439 --> 03:26:55.160
began to panic. As his cities fell one by one, the&nbsp;
Shah Ala ad-Din Muhammad turned tail and fled. He

03:26:55.160 --> 03:27:01.639
rode from fortress to fortress as the Mongol&nbsp;
armies pursued him, and as he did, he slipped

03:27:01.640 --> 03:27:10.000
into a deep depression. Juvaini recounts that he&nbsp;
began to be plagued with nightmares. He began

03:27:10.000 --> 03:27:18.040
drinking heavily, and spent all his time in the&nbsp;
pursuit of pleasures. The terror of the last day

03:27:18.040 --> 03:27:25.160
was apparent in his condition, and fear and dread&nbsp;
were manifest in his speech. For the remainder

03:27:25.160 --> 03:27:32.599
of his life, he constantly applied himself to&nbsp;
the quaffing of cups of purple wine. One night

03:27:32.600 --> 03:27:39.399
in his sleep, the sultan saw luminous persons,&nbsp;
their faces scratched, their hair disordered and

03:27:39.399 --> 03:27:46.120
disheveled, clad in black robes like mourners,
who smote their heads and made lamentation.

03:27:47.560 --> 03:27:52.800
He asked them who they were,&nbsp;
and they replied, “We are Islam.”

03:27:52.800 --> 03:28:03.560
Eventually, with his nightmares&nbsp;
and the Mongol horsemen chasing close

03:28:03.560 --> 03:28:09.279
behind him, the Shah escaped to the most&nbsp;
remote hideout he could manage. He took

03:28:09.279 --> 03:28:16.120
a boat out onto a small island off the&nbsp;
coast of the Caspian Sea, and hid there.

03:28:18.279 --> 03:28:26.000
Whenever he halted for a day, the Mongols would&nbsp;
overtake him. The sultan sent for certain emirs

03:28:26.000 --> 03:28:32.520
and consulted them. They thought it best for him&nbsp;
to seek asylum in one of the islands of the Sea

03:28:32.520 --> 03:28:39.800
of Abaskun. He went to one of these islands, where&nbsp;
he remained for a while, then when the report of

03:28:39.800 --> 03:28:46.040
his presence on the island was spread about, he&nbsp;
took the precaution of removing to another island.

03:28:49.439 --> 03:28:57.879
Finally, the Mongols captured the Shah's capital of&nbsp;
Gurganj, and his family fell into the hands of Chinggis

03:28:57.880 --> 03:29:07.160
Khan. When the dreadful news reached the sultan&nbsp;
and he learned that his small sons had been put

03:29:07.160 --> 03:29:13.120
to the sword, that his veiled womanfolk&nbsp;
had been in the clutches of strangers, and

03:29:13.120 --> 03:29:19.040
that all of his wedded wives had fallen&nbsp;
into the embraces of other men, his head

03:29:19.040 --> 03:29:25.720
grew dizzy. The world grew dark before&nbsp;
his eyes, then was the pain passed remedy

03:29:25.720 --> 03:29:32.680
and threatened his very existence, and he&nbsp;
preferred death to life. He writhed in this

03:29:32.680 --> 03:29:39.319
anguish and agitation, and bemoaned this calamity&nbsp;
and disaster until he delivered up his soul

03:29:39.319 --> 03:29:46.040
to God and was released from the sorrow of his&nbsp;
life and the trickery of the revolving heavens.

03:29:52.040 --> 03:30:00.120
Alone on his tiny Island, the Shah of the Khwarazmian&nbsp;
Empire, Ala ad-Din Muhammad, died, possibly of

03:30:00.120 --> 03:30:10.840
dysentery, in the year 1220. He was buried wrapped&nbsp;
in a torn white shirt for a shroud. His empire,

03:30:10.840 --> 03:30:18.600
now utterly destroyed, passed into the hands&nbsp;
of the Mongols. His eldest son, an accomplished

03:30:18.600 --> 03:30:25.800
warrior named Jalal ad-Din, evaded capture and&nbsp;
led a sizable force south in the direction

03:30:25.800 --> 03:30:32.399
of India, where he intended to continue his&nbsp;
resistance. But he was finally caught by the

03:30:32.399 --> 03:30:40.920
pursuing Mongol force in the autumn of 1221,&nbsp;
and his army was utterly destroyed. Legend has

03:30:40.920 --> 03:30:48.520
it that Jalal ad-Din only escaped death by leaping&nbsp;
his horse into the Indus River and swimming for

03:30:48.520 --> 03:30:58.319
safety across the rushing torrent of its waters.&nbsp;
The geographer Yaqut al-Hamawi, a citizen of the

03:30:58.319 --> 03:31:05.399
city of Merv, who fled the advance of the Mongols,&nbsp;
wrote about the destruction they left in their wake.

03:31:05.399 --> 03:31:15.160
Those infidels and heathens roamed through&nbsp;
those abodes, so that palaces were erased off the

03:31:15.160 --> 03:31:21.680
Earth as lines of writing are effaced from paper,&nbsp;
and cities became a dwelling for the owl and the

03:31:21.680 --> 03:31:30.080
raven. In those places, the screech owls answer&nbsp;
each other. They are filled with sadness. The

03:31:30.080 --> 03:31:36.880
Devil himself would bewail the great catastrophe.&nbsp;
It was an event enough to turn gray the hair of

03:31:36.880 --> 03:31:48.279
children. The Arab writer Ibn Al-Athir also wrote&nbsp;
with palpable sorrow about the horror of those

03:31:48.279 --> 03:31:58.479
days. With one stroke, a world which billowed with&nbsp;
fertility was laid desolate, and the regions

03:31:58.479 --> 03:32:07.160
thereof became a desert, and the greater part of&nbsp;
the living, dead, and their skin and bones crumbling

03:32:07.160 --> 03:32:15.840
dust, and the mighty were humbled. For some years,
I continued a verse from mentioning this event,

03:32:16.640 --> 03:32:24.640
deeming it so horrible that I shrank from&nbsp;
recording it. Oh, would that my mother had not

03:32:24.640 --> 03:32:34.359
borne me or that I had died and become a forgotten&nbsp;
thing before this befell. Nay, it is unlikely that

03:32:34.359 --> 03:32:45.839
mankind will see the like of this calamity&nbsp;
until the world comes to an end and perishes.

03:32:50.160 --> 03:32:57.080
The conquest of the Khwarazmian Empire had&nbsp;
taken four years. It had wiped some of

03:32:57.080 --> 03:33:03.559
the world's largest cities off the&nbsp;
map and cost countless lives, and by

03:33:03.560 --> 03:33:15.760
the end of it, Chinggis Khan's empire was&nbsp;
the largest that the world had ever seen.

03:33:41.520 --> 03:33:50.040
By this time, Chinggis Khan was in his sixties, and he&nbsp;
was beginning to think with increasing trepidation

03:33:50.040 --> 03:33:59.399
about his own mortality. During his campaign&nbsp;
in Persia, he invited a Chinese Daoist monk named

03:33:59.399 --> 03:34:06.759
Master Chang-chun to visit him in the hopes that&nbsp;
this wise man might have some answer about how a

03:34:06.760 --> 03:34:15.920
man could live forever. This holy man's journey&nbsp;
is recorded in a text called The Account of the

03:34:15.920 --> 03:34:24.120
Perfect Master Chang-chun's Journey to the West.&nbsp;
In it, he describes his journey over the Mongolian

03:34:24.120 --> 03:34:34.840
steppe. On the fifth day of the third month, we&nbsp;
began traveling in a northeasterly direction.

03:34:34.840 --> 03:34:42.399
All around us we saw human habitation, nothing but&nbsp;
black carts and white tents, and herders following

03:34:42.399 --> 03:34:49.040
the grass and water to pasture their animals.&nbsp;
When we passed out of the marshy plains, there

03:34:49.040 --> 03:34:56.120
was not even the smallest tree or shrub. Only&nbsp;
yellow dust clouds and white grasses were in

03:34:56.120 --> 03:35:05.840
sight. On his journey, he saw everywhere the&nbsp;
signs of the great war that was unfolding,

03:35:05.840 --> 03:35:12.600
and passed by a number of battlefields left&nbsp;
by the passage of the Mongol armies into the

03:35:12.600 --> 03:35:20.319
west. The stony gorge on the south&nbsp;
was unbearably alarming. On both

03:35:20.319 --> 03:35:27.040
sides, precipices held up the towering sky,&nbsp;
and the chilly surge of a mountain stream

03:35:27.040 --> 03:35:32.479
flowed and rolled over the ground. People&nbsp;
covered their noses because of corpses

03:35:32.479 --> 03:35:38.519
strewn about the narrow path, but it was the&nbsp;
long-eared donkeys drowned in the stream

03:35:38.520 --> 03:35:45.640
that sickened my heart. War has raged&nbsp;
for ten years and over huge distances.

03:35:48.800 --> 03:35:57.120
When he finally arrived in Samarqand after months of&nbsp;
travel, he found the city half empty, many of its

03:35:57.120 --> 03:36:07.000
inhabitants fled, and its walls and defenses torn&nbsp;
down. In the second month of winter, on the 18th

03:36:07.000 --> 03:36:14.880
day, we crossed a large river and reached north of&nbsp;
the city of Samarqand. Before the sultan was defeated,

03:36:14.880 --> 03:36:22.319
there were more than 100,000 households in the&nbsp;
city. Since the fall of the city, only one in four

03:36:22.319 --> 03:36:29.040
remains. Finally, he reached the court of the Great

03:36:29.040 --> 03:36:41.680
Khan. When he arrived, Chinggis Khan had one&nbsp;
question on his mind. Refreshments and drinks were

03:36:41.680 --> 03:36:49.080
served, and then the emperor asked, “Now that you&nbsp;
have come all this way, what secret elixir for long

03:36:49.080 --> 03:36:59.080
life can you provide me?” But the Daoist master would&nbsp;
disappoint him. The master replied, “There is the way

03:36:59.080 --> 03:37:06.199
of good health, but I can give you no elixir for&nbsp;
long life.” His Majesty appreciated the master's

03:37:06.199 --> 03:37:15.519
candor, and ordered two tents to be erected to&nbsp;
the east of his residence in which we would stay.

03:37:17.279 --> 03:37:25.359
It's clear from this that Chinggis Khan was&nbsp;
beginning to fear that he did not have long left.

03:37:25.359 --> 03:37:32.120
A hunting accident also seems to have frightened&nbsp;
him, and brought the question of his mortality to

03:37:32.120 --> 03:37:39.680
the forefront of his mind. On the eighth day,&nbsp;
the emperor went hunting in the foothills of

03:37:39.680 --> 03:37:47.920
the eastern mountains, and shot at a large boar. His&nbsp;
horse tripped, and he lost control. The boar stood

03:37:47.920 --> 03:37:55.720
nearby, not daring to advance, until his entourage&nbsp;
rushed in with another horse. The hunt was called

03:37:55.720 --> 03:38:03.160
off, and the emperor returned. When the master heard&nbsp;
about the incident, he went to remonstrate with the

03:38:03.160 --> 03:38:11.519
emperor, saying, “Your falling from your horse is a&nbsp;
warning from Heaven.” The emperor responded, saying, “I

03:38:11.520 --> 03:38:20.160
have already come to this deep realization.” For&nbsp;
two months thereafter, he did not go out to hunt.

03:38:20.160 --> 03:38:27.552
The man who had brought so much death to other&nbsp;
lands now felt its icy hand on his own shoulder.

03:38:27.560 --> 03:38:53.439
Chinggis Khan’s concern wasn't just for&nbsp;
his own life. Now, in his sixties, he began to realize

03:38:53.439 --> 03:39:02.160
too late that he had not sufficiently prepared&nbsp;
for the inevitable question of his succession.

03:39:02.160 --> 03:39:08.880
He would pass on to his heirs the largest land&nbsp;
empire that history would ever know, but when

03:39:08.880 --> 03:39:16.960
he looked at his four sons by his Chief Empress&nbsp;
Borte, he found them totally unprepared to take

03:39:16.960 --> 03:39:27.239
on such a burden. It's likely that his plan was&nbsp;
a simple one; his empire would be divided into

03:39:27.239 --> 03:39:34.399
a kaleidoscope of different provinces, and over&nbsp;
these, three of his sons would rule. But he would

03:39:34.399 --> 03:39:42.879
ensure that each held possessions in the other's&nbsp;
lands so that none would be tempted to go to war.

03:39:42.880 --> 03:39:49.920
Above these three brothers would sit the fourth&nbsp;
son, who would rule the entire empire in his place

03:39:49.920 --> 03:39:57.640
as the Great Khan. The system was well conceived,&nbsp;
but it would depend on the cooperation of every

03:39:57.640 --> 03:40:05.720
one of his sons, and for a number of reasons,&nbsp;
that is the one thing that Chinggis Khan did not

03:40:05.720 --> 03:40:15.479
have. He had brought his four&nbsp;
sons, Jochi, Chaghatai, Ogedei, and Tolui 

03:40:15.479 --> 03:40:22.839
with him on the Khwarazmian campaign, and they&nbsp;
had each led armies and fought bravely, but

03:40:22.840 --> 03:40:30.399
throughout the war, trouble had been brewing.
Just as he and his half-brother Begter had

03:40:30.399 --> 03:40:45.399
once quarreled over fish and rabbits, now his&nbsp;
sons fought over cities and kingdoms.

03:40:45.399 --> 03:40:49.160
First, let's take a look at&nbsp;
the character of each of his sons.

03:40:49.160 --> 03:41:02.199
The eldest of Chinggis Khan's sons was Jochi,&nbsp;
but his life had been lived under a cloud of

03:41:02.199 --> 03:41:10.239
suspicion. He was the son whose name meant ‘guest’,&nbsp;
as though he was simply a visitor who was being

03:41:10.239 --> 03:41:18.439
shown courtesy by the rest of the family. He&nbsp;
had been born shortly after Chinggis Khan’s wife

03:41:18.439 --> 03:41:25.359
Borte was kidnapped by the Merkit forest people,&nbsp;
and no one could know for sure whether Chinggis

03:41:25.359 --> 03:41:34.839
Khan was truly his father. Still, the Khan had&nbsp;
all his life treated Jochi as one of his sons,

03:41:34.840 --> 03:41:43.239
and Jochi also had the strongest desire to prove&nbsp;
himself. He was a courageous leader who always

03:41:43.239 --> 03:41:50.080
charged right into the heart of the fight.&nbsp;
Whatever the truth of his fatherhood, he had

03:41:50.080 --> 03:41:57.800
spent his life living up to the reputation&nbsp;
of his father. But while Chinggis Khan seems

03:41:57.800 --> 03:42:03.680
to have set the issue of his parenthood&nbsp;
aside, his other sons couldn't forget it so

03:42:03.680 --> 03:42:16.359
readily. Next in line was Chinggis Khan's second&nbsp;
son, Chaghatai. Chaghatai was hot-headed and

03:42:16.359 --> 03:42:24.439
proud, and all his life had resented his older&nbsp;
brother, Jochi. When Chinggis Khan looked at Jochi

03:42:24.439 --> 03:42:31.199
and Chaghatai, it's hard to imagine that he didn't&nbsp;
see the similarity between himself and his older

03:42:31.199 --> 03:42:39.000
brother, Begter, and remember, perhaps now with a&nbsp;
little sadness, how that story had ended, with

03:42:39.000 --> 03:42:48.520
Begter lying dead in the long grass of the steppe. All&nbsp;
his life, Chaghatai had felt sure that Jochi was not

03:42:48.520 --> 03:42:56.439
his father's son, and he treated his older brother&nbsp;
with contempt. Silently, he feared that the throne

03:42:56.439 --> 03:43:03.599
of the Great Khan would be given to his older&nbsp;
brother, in his eyes a usurper and the son of the

03:43:03.600 --> 03:43:11.680
Merkit who raped his mother. In hope of mending the&nbsp;
relationship between these two brothers, Chinggis

03:43:11.680 --> 03:43:20.640
Khan had given them a joint mission in the last&nbsp;war,
to capture the Khwarazm-Shah's capital of Gurganj,

03:43:20.640 --> 03:43:28.199
but the plan had been a disaster. The defenders of the&nbsp;
city put up a fearsome resistance that lasted six

03:43:28.199 --> 03:43:35.479
months, and the brothers were forced to burn it&nbsp;
down in order to push them back. Since the city

03:43:35.479 --> 03:43:42.080
would belong to Jochi once it was captured, Chaghatai
cared little about how much damage was done to

03:43:42.080 --> 03:43:51.279
it, whereas Jochi wished to protect its buildings,&nbsp;
even at the cost of Mongol lives. Chinggis Khan had

03:43:51.279 --> 03:43:59.519
hoped to capture the jewel of this empire intact,&nbsp;
but now Gurganj was a ruin, and the city would never

03:43:59.520 --> 03:44:07.560
regain its former splendor. This episode seems to&nbsp;
have been just another point of bitter contention

03:44:07.560 --> 03:44:15.040
between the two brothers, and a warning about&nbsp;
the burning resentments smoldering between them.

03:44:16.800 --> 03:44:24.239
The third brother was named Ogedei. He was&nbsp;
charismatic and larger than life, a barrel-

03:44:24.239 --> 03:44:32.239
chested man with an unusually large beard for a&nbsp;
Mongol. He had a jovial personality and a love of

03:44:32.239 --> 03:44:41.800
feasting and drinking. He was a capable general, but&nbsp;
he did have one overriding weakness; that was his

03:44:41.800 --> 03:44:52.239
raging alcoholism. Like many Mongols, Ogedei was&nbsp;
a big drinker, but even by Mongol standards, his

03:44:52.239 --> 03:45:01.000
habit went too far. At one point, his older brother&nbsp;
Chaghatai had appointed an official to monitor Ogedei's

03:45:01.000 --> 03:45:11.239
drinking, but it was no good. Ogedei evaded his&nbsp;
watcher and drank himself silly regardless. One

03:45:11.239 --> 03:45:16.840
common story about him describes how he promised&nbsp;
his brothers that he would half the number

03:45:16.840 --> 03:45:25.520
of cups he drank every night, but he simply ordered&nbsp;
a new cup to be made that was twice the size, and

03:45:25.520 --> 03:45:35.960
so, his drinking went on. Still, Ogedei was diplomatic&nbsp;
and generous, and as a result, was well liked by

03:45:35.960 --> 03:45:50.199
all. The final brother was Tolui. He was the youngest&nbsp;
of the four, a calculating and formidable warrior,

03:45:50.199 --> 03:45:59.159
and he had a famed streak of cruelty. During the&nbsp;
conquest of the Khwarazmian Empire, he had been sent to

03:45:59.159 --> 03:46:05.920
pacify the region of Khorasan, and passed through&nbsp;
the region dealing out death on a scale that was

03:46:05.920 --> 03:46:14.439
unusual even for Mongols. He had been leading the&nbsp;
army responsible for the massacre at Nishapur, and

03:46:14.439 --> 03:46:22.159
he repeated the same genocidal violence&nbsp;
at the great cities of Merv and Herat. At these

03:46:22.159 --> 03:46:29.000
settlements, he promised the inhabitants that he&nbsp;
would spare them if they surrendered, but unlike

03:46:29.000 --> 03:46:35.840
his father, he went back on his word. When they&nbsp;
opened the gates, he ordered that every living

03:46:35.840 --> 03:46:44.960
person be put to the sword. Interestingly, Mongol&nbsp;
tradition often held that the youngest son

03:46:44.960 --> 03:46:52.080
should inherit his father's property as a kind&nbsp;
of social welfare. It was assumed that by the

03:46:52.080 --> 03:46:57.720
time their father died, the older brothers&nbsp;
would have already amassed their own wealth,

03:46:57.720 --> 03:47:05.080
whereas the youngest had the most need of an&nbsp;
inheritance. This rule had never been applied

03:47:05.080 --> 03:47:11.040
to titles which were supposed to be appointed to&nbsp;
the most worthy candidate, but it must have been

03:47:11.040 --> 03:47:17.040
playing on everyone's minds as the question&nbsp;
of the Khan’s succession became ever more

03:47:17.040 --> 03:47:30.359
pressing. It was these four sons that Chinggis&nbsp;
Khan summoned to a fateful kuriltai, a meeting

03:47:30.359 --> 03:47:38.880
of the clans in 1223 at a region called&nbsp;
Qulan-Bashi in modern Kazakhstan; Jochi, the

03:47:38.880 --> 03:47:44.520
man of uncertain fatherhood, Chaghatai,&nbsp;
the hot-headed and embittered would-be

03:47:44.520 --> 03:47:51.680
older brother, Ogedei, the stocky wine-&nbsp;
soaked drinker, and Tolui, the cold-hearted

03:47:51.680 --> 03:47:59.080
warrior, and in the smoke-filled atmosphere&nbsp;
of his great tent, he told them that there

03:47:59.080 --> 03:48:10.600
they would decide who would rule the empire&nbsp;
after he was gone. The Secret History

03:48:10.600 --> 03:48:17.479
records that one of his wives, Yesui, urged&nbsp;
him to choose his successor in the following

03:48:17.479 --> 03:48:31.519
words. Living beings who are born to this world are&nbsp;
not eternal. When your body, like a great old tree,

03:48:31.520 --> 03:48:39.000
will fall down, to whom will you give your people,&nbsp;
which is like tangled hemp? When your body, like the

03:48:39.000 --> 03:48:45.359
stone base of a pillar, will collapse, to whom will&nbsp;
you bequeath your people, which is like a flock of

03:48:45.359 --> 03:48:53.359
birds? Of your four sons, the heroes whom you have&nbsp;
begotten, which one will you designate as your

03:48:53.359 --> 03:49:07.719
successor? But the kuriltai got off to a bad&nbsp;
start. First, Chinggis Khan asked his oldest

03:49:07.720 --> 03:49:14.720
son Jochi to speak, and this sign of apparent&nbsp;favor
enraged his hot-headed younger brother, Chaghatai.

03:49:16.880 --> 03:49:27.800
He said, “The eldest of my sons is Jochi. What do you,&nbsp;
Jochi, say? Speak up.” But before Jochi could utter a

03:49:27.800 --> 03:49:35.159
sound, Chaghatai said, “Do you mean that you will&nbsp;
appoint Jochi as your successor? How can we let

03:49:35.159 --> 03:49:44.639
ourselves be ruled by this bastard son of a Merkit?”&nbsp;
The effect of this pronouncement was explosive.

03:49:46.560 --> 03:49:54.040
At these words, Jochi rose, and grabbing Chaghatai&nbsp;
by the collar, said, “I have never been told by

03:49:54.040 --> 03:50:01.040
my father, the Khan, that I was different from&nbsp;
my brothers. How can you discriminate against

03:50:01.040 --> 03:50:09.840
me? In what skill are you better than I? Only in&nbsp;
your pigheadedness could you possibly exceed

03:50:09.840 --> 03:50:20.199
me.” Chinggis Khan watched his sons fighting in&nbsp;
silence. Seeing the flames of the hearth fire

03:50:20.199 --> 03:50:25.840
dance in their eyes, perhaps he remembered&nbsp;
the words of his mother Oelun on the day

03:50:25.840 --> 03:50:33.920
that he and Qasar had killed their brother, Begter.
Suddenly his great voice boomed out, trembling with

03:50:33.920 --> 03:50:45.640
anger. Before you were born, the starry sky was&nbsp;
turning upon itself. The many people of the felt

03:50:45.640 --> 03:50:55.359
tents were in turmoil. They fought against each&nbsp;
other. At such time, your mother was abducted. It

03:50:55.359 --> 03:51:02.679
was not her wish. It happened at a time when one&nbsp;
man slew another. She was not in love with someone

03:51:02.680 --> 03:51:09.720
else. You speak so as to harden the butter of your&nbsp;
mother's affection, so as to sour the milk of that

03:51:09.720 --> 03:51:17.319
lady's heart. Were you, too, not born from the same&nbsp;
belly? Were you, too, not issued from a single

03:51:17.319 --> 03:51:27.159
womb? These were almost the same words that&nbsp;
his mother Oelun had once used on him, the

03:51:27.159 --> 03:51:31.920
same words that the legendary Alan the&nbsp;
Beautiful had said to her quarreling

03:51:31.920 --> 03:51:38.399
sons. The brothers were chastened, and perhaps&nbsp;
realizing that they had harmed both of their

03:51:38.399 --> 03:51:44.519
own chances, Chaghatai suggested another&nbsp;
candidate that everyone could agree on.

03:51:46.640 --> 03:51:53.760
I shall not dispute Jochi's strength, nor shall&nbsp;
I reply to his claims of skill, but it is Ogedei

03:51:53.760 --> 03:52:02.520
among us who is steady and reliable. Let us&nbsp;
therefore agree on Ogedei. So he spoke, and at

03:52:02.520 --> 03:52:12.239
these words, Chinggis Khan said, “What do you say,&nbsp;
Jochi? Speak up.” Whereupon, Jochi said, “Chaghatai has

03:52:12.239 --> 03:52:21.880
just said it; Chaghatai and I shall, in cooperation&nbsp;
with each other, serve the Khan. Let us agree on Ogedei.”

03:52:21.880 --> 03:52:27.960
From this moment on, the drunken

03:52:27.960 --> 03:52:35.800
but charismatic Ogedei would be&nbsp;
the heir to the Mongol

03:52:35.800 --> 03:52:44.440
Empire. After that explosive meeting,&nbsp;
the brothers rode off in all directions,

03:52:45.359 --> 03:52:54.399
never to be reunited. The oldest son Jochi was&nbsp;
most wounded by Chinggis Khan's decision, and

03:52:54.399 --> 03:53:01.399
would never see his father again. Wearied&nbsp;
by this conflict in his family, the Great

03:53:01.399 --> 03:53:10.040
Khan set out back to Mongolia, arriving there&nbsp;
in spring of 1225. Perhaps those who saw him

03:53:10.040 --> 03:53:23.120
there felt a change come over him. The life&nbsp;
of the Great Khan was coming to an end.

03:53:23.120 --> 03:53:38.080
In the year 1225, Chinggis Khan set out on&nbsp;
what would be his final military campaign. It

03:53:38.080 --> 03:53:44.960
would be against the Tanguts of Western Xia, the&nbsp;
Tibetan Buddhists he had already conquered

03:53:44.960 --> 03:53:52.120
on his way to Northern China. In the years&nbsp;
since, they had become unreliable allies,

03:53:52.120 --> 03:53:58.519
and were beginning to rebel against his&nbsp;
rule. With the Khwarazmian Empire conquered, he

03:53:58.520 --> 03:54:03.880
now wanted to punish the Tanguts for&nbsp;
their impudence. He marched into their

03:54:03.880 --> 03:54:10.399
lands and laid waste to them, but on this&nbsp;
campaign, while traveling through the hot

03:54:10.399 --> 03:54:17.639
deserts of the western regions, Chinggis Khan&nbsp;
fell from his horse, as The Secret History records.

03:54:17.640 --> 03:54:35.880
Chinggis Khan, riding his steed named Red Earth&nbsp;
Gray, on the way hunted the many wild asses

03:54:35.880 --> 03:54:44.720
of Arbuqa. When the wild asses passed close by&nbsp;
them, his horse took fright. Chinggis Khan fell,

03:54:44.720 --> 03:54:50.640
and his body being in great pain,
he halted at Cho’orqat. He spent that

03:54:50.640 --> 03:54:58.319
night there, and the following morning, his&nbsp;
wife, Yisui Qatun, said, “Princes and commanders,

03:54:58.319 --> 03:55:03.479
consult each other on what to do. The Khan&nbsp;
has spent the night, his body hot with fever.”

03:55:03.479 --> 03:55:16.759
The summer heat made the Khan's condition worse,&nbsp;
and so, his men took him up into the nearby

03:55:16.760 --> 03:55:25.800
mountains of Liupan, densely forested with Chinese&nbsp;
pine and dragon spruce, just beginning to turn to

03:55:25.800 --> 03:55:35.199
their autumn colors. Not long after, the&nbsp;
Great Khan's illness worsened, and he died at the

03:55:35.199 --> 03:55:44.239
end of August in the year 1227. The Secret History&nbsp;
of the Mongols records his passing in brief

03:55:44.239 --> 03:56:02.040
terms. Chinggis Khan came back, and&nbsp;
in the Year of the Pig, ascended to Heaven.

03:56:02.040 --> 03:56:18.080
There is much debate over what exactly&nbsp;
killed Chinggis Khan. There are several outlandish

03:56:18.080 --> 03:56:24.800
myths that circulate around the circumstances&nbsp;
of his death. Some more colorful versions fill

03:56:24.800 --> 03:56:32.600
his passing with dramatic irony, imagining a Tangut&nbsp;
princess killing and castrating him when he tries

03:56:32.600 --> 03:56:40.279
to force her into bed, but most chronicles simply&nbsp;
mention an illness that fell on him suddenly, among

03:56:40.279 --> 03:56:47.399
them, the Persian historian Ata-Malik Juvaini.&nbsp;
When Chinggis Khan returned from the lands of

03:56:47.399 --> 03:56:53.519
the West to his old incumbent in the East, he&nbsp;
was overcome by an incurable disease arising

03:56:53.520 --> 03:57:01.560
from the unpleasantness of the climate. Some modern&nbsp;
scholars have even suggested that he was an early

03:57:01.560 --> 03:57:08.640
casualty of the Bubonic plague, which would soon&nbsp;
spread westwards across Eurasia and cause death

03:57:08.640 --> 03:57:15.960
and destruction on an unprecedented scale. The&nbsp;
Chinese language source, The History of Yuan or

03:57:15.960 --> 03:57:22.640
Yuan Shi, records that on the 18th of August,&nbsp;
the Khan felt unwell with a fever, and eight days

03:57:22.640 --> 03:57:29.600
later, he died. Such a rapid pace of decline&nbsp;
could point to the Black Death being the

03:57:29.600 --> 03:57:37.319
cause. Whatever the cause of his death,&nbsp;
the Khan's body was soon prepared for

03:57:37.319 --> 03:57:44.239
burial. Mongols of this time held a great taboo

03:57:44.239 --> 03:57:48.880
around speaking about death, and so, we&nbsp;
actually know little about the deaths

03:57:48.880 --> 03:57:55.399
of many of the characters in this story.&nbsp;
Some, like Chinggis Khan's wife Borte,

03:57:55.399 --> 03:58:02.040
simply disappear from records altogether, and&nbsp;
we have no information about when or how she

03:58:02.040 --> 03:58:10.399
died. As for the Khan, some believe that he was&nbsp;
probably buried close to where his army was

03:58:10.399 --> 03:58:18.239
situated, somewhere in Ningxia among the Liupan&nbsp;
mountains, but other sources record a more

03:58:18.239 --> 03:58:25.880
dramatic version of events. The Venetian explorer&nbsp;
Marco Polo, who traveled to Mongolia nearly half

03:58:25.880 --> 03:58:34.800
a century later, wrote the following account&nbsp;
that was told to him. All the Grand Khans and all

03:58:34.800 --> 03:58:41.560
the descendants of Chinggis, their first lord, are&nbsp;
carried to a mountain to be interred. Wherever

03:58:41.560 --> 03:58:48.120
so the sovereign may die, he is carried to his&nbsp;
burial in that mountain with his predecessors. No

03:58:48.120 --> 03:58:55.399
matter if the place of his death were a 100 days’&nbsp;
journey distant, there must he be carried to his

03:58:55.399 --> 03:59:06.879
burial. Mongol religious beliefs held that the&nbsp;
bodies of the dead should never be disturbed.

03:59:06.880 --> 03:59:12.840
For this reason, Marco Polo also recounts that&nbsp;
the Mongols were determined that no one should

03:59:12.840 --> 03:59:20.439
ever find the grave of the Great Khan, that his&nbsp;
body would forever lie undisturbed, and that

03:59:20.439 --> 03:59:28.159
they went to extraordinary lengths to make&nbsp;
sure its location remained a secret. When

03:59:28.159 --> 03:59:33.359
they are carrying the body of any emperor to be&nbsp;
buried with the others, the convoy that goes with

03:59:33.359 --> 03:59:40.799
the body puts to the sword all whom they fall in&nbsp;
with on the road. They do the same, too, with horses,

03:59:40.800 --> 03:59:47.199
for when the emperor dies, they kill all his best&nbsp;
horses in order that he may have the use of them

03:59:47.199 --> 03:59:54.840
in the other world, as they believe, and I tell&nbsp;
you as a certain truth that when one Khan died,

03:59:54.840 --> 04:00:02.199
more than 20,000 persons who chanced to meet the&nbsp;
body on its way were slain in the manner I have told.

04:00:02.199 --> 04:00:12.760
While these accounts may be an exaggeration,&nbsp;
what is sure is that the Mongol soldiers fenced

04:00:12.760 --> 04:00:18.960
off a large area of land around the sacred&nbsp;
mountain Burkan Khaldun, marking it with a

04:00:18.960 --> 04:00:26.840
fence of arrows stuck in the ground. Other than&nbsp;
the closest royal family of the Khan, no one was

04:00:26.840 --> 04:00:32.800
allowed to enter this forbidden zone on&nbsp;
pain of death, with guards permanently

04:00:32.800 --> 04:00:40.359
stationed on its perimeter. The later Mongol&nbsp;
historian Saghang Sechen describes the body

04:00:40.359 --> 04:00:47.199
of Chinggis Khan being removed to his native&nbsp;
Mongolia on a two-wheeled wagon escorted

04:00:47.199 --> 04:00:55.479
by his great army. On the way, one of the&nbsp;
Khan's old friends began to sing a mournful

04:00:55.479 --> 04:01:06.679
song. Kiluken Bahadur of the Sunid tribe lifted&nbsp;
up his voice and sang, “Once you did swoop like a

04:01:06.680 --> 04:01:15.640
falcon, but now a rumbling wagon trundles you off.&nbsp;
Oh, my king, have you in truth then forsaken your

04:01:15.640 --> 04:01:22.760
wife and your children, and the rule of your&nbsp;
people? Oh, my king, circling in pride like an

04:01:22.760 --> 04:01:31.239
eagle once you did lead us, oh, my king, but now you&nbsp;
have stumbled and fallen like a wild horse. Oh, my

04:01:31.239 --> 04:01:40.239
king. Today it's thought that the most&nbsp;
likely place for the Khan's burial is

04:01:40.239 --> 04:01:47.760
in this area, somewhere around the mountain of&nbsp;
Burkan Khaldun, the holy peak that he had always

04:01:47.760 --> 04:01:54.439
climbed whenever he needed to hear the voice&nbsp;
of his God and to be close to the great sky

04:01:54.439 --> 04:02:13.839
above. Now, between Chinggis Khan and the&nbsp;
Great Blue Sky, there was only silence.

04:02:39.040 --> 04:02:46.159
After the death of Chinggis Khan, the Mongol&nbsp;
Empire went into a state of some shock, and

04:02:46.159 --> 04:02:53.680
its wars of conquest were largely put on hold,&nbsp;
but the immense respect he had won during his

04:02:53.680 --> 04:03:00.560
life carried over into his death, and the plan&nbsp;
he had put in place for his succession was

04:03:00.560 --> 04:03:07.359
carried out. For the next two years, the&nbsp;
empire was held in a kind of regency by

04:03:07.359 --> 04:03:14.080
his youngest son Tolui, and at the end of that&nbsp;
period, once the time of mourning had passed,

04:03:14.080 --> 04:03:22.479
Ogedei took his position as Great Khan on the&nbsp;
13th of September 1229, as The Secret History

04:03:22.479 --> 04:03:37.279
records. In accordance with the decree of&nbsp;
Chinggis Khan, they installed Ogedei as Khan.

04:03:37.279 --> 04:03:43.800
The night guards, the quiver bearers, and the&nbsp;
8,000 day guards who had been protecting the

04:03:43.800 --> 04:03:50.000
precious life of their father Chinggis Khan, the&nbsp;
personal slaves and the 10,000 guards who had

04:03:50.000 --> 04:03:54.920
been in close attendance on the person&nbsp;
of his father, the Khan, were all handed over.

04:03:54.920 --> 04:04:13.720
In fitting with his character, one of Ogedei's&nbsp;
first acts as Khan was to hold a grand celebration.

04:04:15.399 --> 04:04:22.120
At this festival, feasts were held, songs&nbsp;
were sung, and games played, wrestling and

04:04:22.120 --> 04:04:28.399
hunting, archery and riding, and of course,&nbsp;
enormous quantities of alcohol would have

04:04:28.399 --> 04:04:36.559
been consumed. The airag and black kumis, the&nbsp;
Chinese rice wines and fine Persian grape

04:04:36.560 --> 04:04:43.640
wines, would have flowed from silver goblets,&nbsp;
and the revelry would have lasted for days.

04:04:44.479 --> 04:04:51.279
Ogedei loved to be liked, and he had always&nbsp;
had a generous streak. To celebrate his coming

04:04:51.279 --> 04:04:57.599
to power, he opened his father's treasuries&nbsp;
and distributed gifts and wealth to all the

04:04:57.600 --> 04:05:04.840
influential families of the Mongol steppe. This&nbsp;
generosity gained him many friends, but the

04:05:04.840 --> 04:05:13.640
Persian scholar Ata-Malik Juvaini recounts his&nbsp;
profligate behavior with a note of disapproval.

04:05:14.319 --> 04:05:20.880
He was ever spreading the carpet of merrymaking&nbsp;
and treading the path of excess, in constant

04:05:20.880 --> 04:05:28.439
application to wine and the company of angelic&nbsp;
women. Being by nature extravagantly bountiful,

04:05:28.439 --> 04:05:33.000
he gave away everything that came in&nbsp;
from the farthest and nearest parts of

04:05:33.000 --> 04:05:40.319
the empire without its being registered by&nbsp;
accountant or inspector. No mortal returned

04:05:40.319 --> 04:05:47.479
from his presence without his lot or share, and&nbsp;
no petitioner heard from his tongue the word ‘no’.

04:05:47.479 --> 04:06:00.359
Ogedei was for the most part a successful ruler,&nbsp;
but he also had a quite different vision for the

04:06:00.359 --> 04:06:07.040
Mongol Empire to that of his father. Chinggis&nbsp;
Khan had always maintained his dislike and

04:06:07.040 --> 04:06:14.479
distrust of settled peoples and city-dwellers. He&nbsp;
had envisioned his empire as the people of the

04:06:14.479 --> 04:06:22.519
felt walls, a pure confederation of nomadic peoples&nbsp;
that would stand up for the pastoralist lifestyle

04:06:22.520 --> 04:06:30.520
against the corruptions of the settled world.&nbsp;
But Ogedei had seen the great cities of China and

04:06:30.520 --> 04:06:38.040
Persia. He had looked with envious eyes upon the&nbsp;
great walls of Beijing and Samarqand, and had brought

04:06:38.040 --> 04:06:47.560
advisers from Northern China to help him rule. One&nbsp;
of these, a Khitan man named Yelu Chucai, is said to

04:06:47.560 --> 04:06:58.399
have given Ogedei the following piece of advice.&nbsp;
An empire won on horseback cannot be ruled on

04:06:58.399 --> 04:07:07.799
horseback. For this reason, Ogedei now dreamed of&nbsp;
departing from his father's policy and building

04:07:07.800 --> 04:07:15.080
a proper capital for the empire he had inherited.&nbsp;
This capital would be complete with all the things

04:07:15.080 --> 04:07:23.199
a great city needed; buildings, streets, temples,&nbsp;
workshops, and palaces. He ordered that this new

04:07:23.199 --> 04:07:29.359
city be built out in the middle of the steppe, at&nbsp;
the same spot where his father had set up his

04:07:29.359 --> 04:07:37.759
main camp, a site where the canyon-like Orkhon River&nbsp;
Valley spills out into the pastures below, right in

04:07:37.760 --> 04:07:46.399
the heart of Mongolia. Construction of this city&nbsp;
happened quickly, with architects and craftsmen

04:07:46.399 --> 04:07:53.960
being brought primarily from the conquered regions&nbsp;
of China, but Ogedei also brought some Persian builders

04:07:53.960 --> 04:08:01.720
to Mongolia to work on his palaces. Ata-Malik&nbsp;
Juvaini gives an account of the new Mongol city.

04:08:01.720 --> 04:08:09.600
There had previously been&nbsp;
no town or village in that place,

04:08:09.600 --> 04:08:14.880
except for the remains of a wall. The&nbsp;
Khan called caused a town to be built

04:08:14.880 --> 04:08:22.279
on it, which they called Ordu-Balig,&nbsp;
though it is better known as Kara-Korum.

04:08:22.279 --> 04:08:35.920
Karakorum in Mongolian means black castle&nbsp;
or black stones. The city rose out of the bare

04:08:35.920 --> 04:08:43.720
steppe grasslands, with earthwork walls and four&nbsp;
gates, and buildings lined with wooden pillars

04:08:43.720 --> 04:08:51.680
built in the Chinese style with swooping pagoda&nbsp;
roofs. At the four corners of the city, he had

04:08:51.680 --> 04:09:00.399
four stone tortoises carved, facing out in each&nbsp;
direction. The tortoise was a symbol of stability

04:09:00.399 --> 04:09:09.479
and protection, and with their incredibly long&nbsp;
lives had become representations of eternity. These

04:09:09.479 --> 04:09:20.159
stone guardians watched over the city and formed&nbsp;
a statement in stone, that Karakorum was built to last.

04:09:20.159 --> 04:09:26.720
With the help of his foreign craftsmen, Ogedei&nbsp;
built Karakorum into what he hoped would be a

04:09:26.720 --> 04:09:35.119
fitting capital for the world's largest empire, and&nbsp;
a fitting venue for the world's most impressive

04:09:35.119 --> 04:09:45.080
parties. Above the town, a garden was built for&nbsp;
the Khan with four gates, and in the midst

04:09:45.080 --> 04:09:52.159
of that garden, artisans reared up a castle,&nbsp;
and inside it a throne having three flights

04:09:52.159 --> 04:10:00.040
of steps for the Khan alone. The utensils were of&nbsp;
gold and silver and studded with jewels. Twice

04:10:00.040 --> 04:10:06.720
in the year would the Khan alight in this&nbsp;
pleasant abode. Whenever the sun entered the

04:10:06.720 --> 04:10:14.760
sign of Aries and the world was glad, he would&nbsp;
feast for a month in this residence, and as

04:10:14.760 --> 04:10:21.600
the bounty of the rain reaches both herbs and&nbsp;
trees, so both great and small took part in the

04:10:21.600 --> 04:10:31.439
feasting. Ogedei encouraged the empire's&nbsp;
elites to build houses near his palace, but

04:10:31.439 --> 04:10:38.960
for the most part, Karakorum remained something of&nbsp;
a halfway point between a Mongol camp and a true

04:10:38.960 --> 04:10:46.399
city. Much of the Mongol nobility continued&nbsp;
to live in their ger tents, often pitching

04:10:46.399 --> 04:10:53.719
them outside the walls, and treated the city as&nbsp;
something of an eccentric novelty. At its heart

04:10:53.720 --> 04:11:01.119
was the Central Secretariat, the main civilian&nbsp;
governing body of the empire. This contained a

04:11:01.119 --> 04:11:06.920
large body of scribes who assessed tax&nbsp;
registries and tribute, and translated

04:11:06.920 --> 04:11:13.439
orders to be sent to the various provinces&nbsp;
of the empire. Other than this administrative

04:11:13.439 --> 04:11:20.759
hub and the palaces of the Khan, the city contained&nbsp;
mostly warehouses for the vast treasures looted

04:11:20.760 --> 04:11:28.880
from all over Asia, and workshops where captured&nbsp;
craftsmen toiled, as well as various houses of

04:11:28.880 --> 04:11:35.880
worship for all the different religions&nbsp;
of the empire. The Flemish monk, William of

04:11:35.880 --> 04:11:42.600
Rubruck, who passed through in the middle of the&nbsp;
13th century, was less than impressed with this

04:11:42.600 --> 04:11:49.920
imperial capital, and compared it unfavorably&nbsp;
to the small town of St. Denis just north of

04:11:49.920 --> 04:12:00.319
Paris. Regarding the city of Karakorum, you should&nbsp;
know that discounting the Khan's palace, it is not

04:12:00.319 --> 04:12:07.000
even as fine as the town of St. Denis, and&nbsp;
the monastery of St. Denis is worth ten of

04:12:07.000 --> 04:12:14.479
the palace. It contains two quarters; one for&nbsp;
the Saracens, where there are bazaars and where

04:12:14.479 --> 04:12:23.479
many traders gather. The other is the quarter of&nbsp;
the Chinese, who are all craftsmen. Set apart from

04:12:23.479 --> 04:12:30.759
these quarters lie large palaces belonging&nbsp;
to the court secretaries. There are twelve idol

04:12:30.760 --> 04:12:37.800
temples belonging to different peoples, two mosques&nbsp;
where the religion of Muhammad is proclaimed, and

04:12:37.800 --> 04:12:44.920
one Christian church at the far end of the town.&nbsp;
The town is enclosed by a mud wall, and has four

04:12:44.920 --> 04:12:57.000
gates. But despite its somewhat humble appearance,&nbsp;
Karakorum was an expensive city to maintain.

04:12:57.000 --> 04:13:03.640
Sitting out in the middle of the steppe, its land&nbsp;
was not fertile, and its people could grow few

04:13:03.640 --> 04:13:11.119
crops. For this reason, it was never self-sufficient,&nbsp;
and its population had to be sustained by food

04:13:11.119 --> 04:13:20.199
brought over long distances from crop-growing&nbsp;
regions in Northern China. Ogedei had hoped that

04:13:20.199 --> 04:13:27.000
Karakorum would become a trading hub in its own&nbsp;
right, and that its economy would become self-

04:13:27.000 --> 04:13:35.159
sustaining. To encourage this, he had trees&nbsp;
planted along the roads that were used by

04:13:35.159 --> 04:13:41.519
trade caravans to help shelter them from the&nbsp;
sun and rain, and to show where the roads were

04:13:41.520 --> 04:13:49.880
when the steppe was covered in winter snows. Ogedei&nbsp;
also expanded one of the Mongols’ most impressive

04:13:49.880 --> 04:13:59.199
achievements; their extensive postal system. This&nbsp;
system, which became known as the Jam in Mongolian

04:13:59.199 --> 04:14:05.960
and Yam in Turkic, connected every corner of the&nbsp;
empire with a system of postal stations where

04:14:05.960 --> 04:14:13.399
fresh horses and supplies were always kept.&nbsp;
The Venetian explorer Marco Polo described

04:14:13.399 --> 04:14:17.439
the remarkable functioning of&nbsp;
this enormous piece of public

04:14:17.439 --> 04:14:27.519
infrastructure. From each city proceed many roads&nbsp;
and highways leading to a variety of provinces, one

04:14:27.520 --> 04:14:34.000
to one province, another to another, and each road&nbsp;
receives the name of the province to which it

04:14:34.000 --> 04:14:42.239
leads. The messengers of the emperor find at every&nbsp;
25 miles of the journey a station which they call

04:14:42.239 --> 04:14:49.760
Yam, in which they find all the rooms furnished&nbsp;
with fine beds and all other necessary articles

04:14:49.760 --> 04:14:56.359
in rich silk. If even a king were to arrive&nbsp;
at one of these, he would find himself well

04:14:56.359 --> 04:15:06.159
lodged. At each of these stations, a full complement&nbsp;
of fresh horses would be kept. When a messenger

04:15:06.159 --> 04:15:11.559
approached one of these stations, he would&nbsp;
bang a drum so that the people working there

04:15:11.560 --> 04:15:17.040
would know to get his horse ready, and he could&nbsp;
continue his journey with the minimum amount of

04:15:17.040 --> 04:15:27.399
delay. At some of these stations, moreover, there&nbsp;
shall be posted some 400 horses standing ready for

04:15:27.399 --> 04:15:34.960
the use of the messengers. At others, there shall&nbsp;
be 200. On all these posts taken together, there are

04:15:34.960 --> 04:15:42.920
more than 300,000 horses kept up, especially for&nbsp;
the use of the messengers. The thing is on a scale

04:15:43.439 --> 04:15:53.199
so wonderful and costly that it is hard to bring&nbsp;
oneself to describe it. The Mongols issued

04:15:53.199 --> 04:16:01.199
passports to travelers in the form of tablets&nbsp;
called paiza, made of wood, bronze, silver, or gold,

04:16:01.199 --> 04:16:07.880
depending on the rank of the person carrying&nbsp;
it. These conferred status on the traveler, and

04:16:07.880 --> 04:16:15.560
allowed them to access the services of the Jam&nbsp;
postal stations. But despite these measures to

04:16:15.560 --> 04:16:21.920
bring the vast empire closer together, the&nbsp;
capital of Karakorum was some way off the

04:16:21.920 --> 04:16:28.760
main arteries of the Silk Road, and traders saw&nbsp;
little reason to make the long journey out into

04:16:28.760 --> 04:16:37.520
the steppe, unless it could be made worth their while.&nbsp;
To encourage them to keep coming to his new city,

04:16:37.520 --> 04:16:43.640
Ogedei decreed that they would be paid above the&nbsp;
usual price for their goods, sometimes even

04:16:43.640 --> 04:16:50.680
twice as much as they were worth elsewhere. For&nbsp;
a time, this strategy worked, and the merchants

04:16:50.680 --> 04:16:58.080
kept coming, but this system was obviously&nbsp;
unsustainable, and soon the money began to run

04:16:58.080 --> 04:17:09.080
dry. By the year 1235, six years into Ogedei's rule,&nbsp;
much of the vast wealth that had been amassed

04:17:09.080 --> 04:17:17.239
by Chinggis Khan had already been frittered away by&nbsp;
his son. The dream of turning the nomadic empire

04:17:17.239 --> 04:17:24.119
of conquest into a settled empire of trade&nbsp;
and commerce was looking ever more unlikely,

04:17:24.119 --> 04:17:30.199
and facing a potential bankruptcy in his&nbsp;
future, Ogedei knew that the Mongol Empire

04:17:30.199 --> 04:17:43.840
would have to find new sources of gold. The&nbsp;
Mongols would once more go to war.

04:17:48.680 --> 04:17:57.040
It's during Ogedei's reign that the Mongol Empire's&nbsp;
ambitions grew from the conquest of its neighbors

04:17:57.040 --> 04:18:04.319
and subjugation of other steppe peoples to a much&nbsp;
more expansive vision, a belief that the whole

04:18:04.319 --> 04:18:10.679
world had been destined to live under Mongol&nbsp;
rule, and that there was nowhere on Earth that

04:18:10.680 --> 04:18:18.840
would escape their conquests. To decide where&nbsp;
the Mongol armies should next descend, Ogedei

04:18:18.840 --> 04:18:25.399
summoned another kuriltai, a gathering of&nbsp;
the clans, bringing together the entire family

04:18:25.399 --> 04:18:32.399
of Chinggis Khan, their wives and vassals and key&nbsp;
commanders, and here a number of different options

04:18:32.399 --> 04:18:39.759
were raised. Some argued that the Mongols should&nbsp;
march south to the lands of India; others that it

04:18:39.760 --> 04:18:46.159
was the turn of Southern China and the Song&nbsp;Dynasty,
who had watched with such glee as the northern

04:18:46.159 --> 04:18:52.880
Jin were destroyed. Others wanted to march into&nbsp;
the Muslim lands and seize the great cities

04:18:52.880 --> 04:19:01.080
of Baghdad, Aleppo, and Damascus, but there was one&nbsp;
final option that was raised by the general named

04:19:01.080 --> 04:19:09.439
Subedei. He had been one of Chinggis Khan's closest&nbsp;
generals, and was now the last surviving member of

04:19:09.439 --> 04:19:17.399
that old guard, something that gave him immense&nbsp;
respect. He suggested that the horde ride west,

04:19:17.399 --> 04:19:25.799
and toward a previously unexplored land that sat&nbsp;
on the periphery of the world, a great peninsula

04:19:25.800 --> 04:19:42.640
jutting out of the Asian landmass, about which the&nbsp;
Mongols knew little. These were the lands of Europe.

04:19:54.520 --> 04:20:03.000
Europe, around the year 1200, was something of&nbsp;
a backwater. It was home to about 70 million

04:20:03.000 --> 04:20:08.040
people, but although it produced textiles&nbsp;
and fine metals, compared to other areas

04:20:08.040 --> 04:20:14.840
of the world, much of medieval Europe had&nbsp;
low levels of urbanism. Other than the huge

04:20:14.840 --> 04:20:21.840
Byzantine capital of Constantinople, Europe had&nbsp;
only a handful of cities that had even 50,000

04:20:21.840 --> 04:20:29.640
inhabitants, and even fewer outside of Italy.&nbsp;
Its position, somewhat removed from Silk

04:20:29.640 --> 04:20:35.680
Road trading routes, meant that it was not a great&nbsp;
beneficiary of the vast wealth that flowed along

04:20:35.680 --> 04:20:42.640
them, and as a result, Europeans were also among&nbsp;
the last to hear news coming out of the east.

04:20:46.080 --> 04:20:52.319
For this reason, Europeans also had a somewhat&nbsp;
confused idea of what the world beyond their

04:20:52.319 --> 04:20:58.719
borders looked like. It was widely believed&nbsp;
in Europe at the time that a great Christian

04:20:58.720 --> 04:21:06.359
king ruled far in the east, a man that they&nbsp;
called Prester John. It was supposed that this

04:21:06.359 --> 04:21:12.679
Christian emperor would one day ride west to&nbsp;
help the Christians retake Jerusalem from the

04:21:12.680 --> 04:21:20.680
Saracens. When Mongol armies first arrived in&nbsp;
Europe, there was at first some excitement.

04:21:20.680 --> 04:21:29.840
This was perhaps the coming of the great Prester&nbsp;
John, but the reality would be quite different. The

04:21:29.840 --> 04:21:36.600
late 13th-century Chronicle of Novgorod, one of&nbsp;
the oldest Russian histories, describes the

04:21:36.600 --> 04:21:42.920
first arrival of these nomadic horsemen&nbsp;
about 14 years earlier, in the year 1223.

04:21:42.920 --> 04:21:55.319
The same year, for our sins, unknown tribes came.&nbsp;
No one exactly knows who they are, nor whence they

04:21:55.319 --> 04:22:03.359
came, nor what their language is, nor of what race&nbsp;
they are, nor what their faith is, but they call

04:22:03.359 --> 04:22:11.599
them the Tartars. We have heard that they have&nbsp;
captured many countries, slaughtered a quantity

04:22:11.600 --> 04:22:21.239
of the godless peoples, and scattered
others. These perplexing foreigners were in fact

04:22:21.239 --> 04:22:28.960
a pair of Mongol armies led by the generals&nbsp;
of Chinggis Khan, Subedei and Jebe. They had been

04:22:28.960 --> 04:22:35.880
sent to destroy any remains of the Kipchak&nbsp;
people, a large confederation of steppe nomads

04:22:35.880 --> 04:22:42.119
who occupied the area of the Volga River, and&nbsp;who
had fought on the side of the Khwarazmian Empire

04:22:42.119 --> 04:22:49.000
just a couple of years earlier. These were some of&nbsp;
the last holdouts among the peoples of the steppe

04:22:49.000 --> 04:22:56.800
who had not yet bent the knee to the Mongols.&nbsp;
Now a large force of Kipchak Turks fled west

04:22:56.800 --> 04:23:12.440
to Russia and begged the help of the major power&nbsp;
in that region, the settled kingdom of Kievan Rus.

04:23:13.640 --> 04:23:20.279
Centered around the city of Kiev in modern&nbsp;
Ukraine, Kievan Rus was less of a kingdom

04:23:20.279 --> 04:23:26.040
and more a fractious collection of princely&nbsp;
city states that formed a belt across the

04:23:26.040 --> 04:23:31.319
European peninsula, from the Arctic White&nbsp;
Sea in the north to the shores of the Black

04:23:31.319 --> 04:23:39.000
Sea in the south, and like the Khwarazmians, its&nbsp;
people had often employed Kipchak nomads as

04:23:39.000 --> 04:23:45.680
mercenary cavalry in its armies. When&nbsp;
the Kipchaks fled into Russia, they warned

04:23:45.680 --> 04:23:52.720
the Russians in no uncertain terms about&nbsp;
what was coming, as the Novgorod Chronicle

04:23:52.720 --> 04:24:04.600
records. To all the Russians they brought many&nbsp;
gifts; horses and camels, buffalos and girls, and

04:24:04.600 --> 04:24:12.360
they came saying this: “Our land they have taken&nbsp;
away today, and yours will be taken tomorrow.”

04:24:16.479 --> 04:24:22.639
Frightened into action by this warning, the&nbsp;
princes of Kievan Rus put together a grand

04:24:22.640 --> 04:24:29.119
coalition and massed a force of 880,000 men&nbsp;
under the command of Grand Prince Mstislav III

04:24:29.119 --> 04:24:39.040
of Kiev. Together they marched out&nbsp;
to meet these barbarians. On the way,

04:24:39.040 --> 04:24:45.399
they encountered some Mongol envoys, who told&nbsp;
the Grand Prince that they meant him no harm,

04:24:45.399 --> 04:24:50.080
that they were only there to destroy&nbsp;
the last remnants of the Kipchaks, who

04:24:50.080 --> 04:24:56.559
they contemptuously referred to as their&nbsp;
slaves and horse herders. But the Kievan

04:24:56.560 --> 04:25:03.920
ruler would make exactly the same mistake as&nbsp;
the Shah of Khwarazm, as the Chronicle of Novgorod

04:25:03.920 --> 04:25:15.319
recalls. The Tartars send envoys to the&nbsp;
Russians saying, “Behold; we hear that you

04:25:15.319 --> 04:25:21.639
are coming against us, but we have not&nbsp;
occupied your land, nor your towns, nor

04:25:21.640 --> 04:25:30.040
your villages, nor is it against you we have&nbsp;
come. But we have come sent by God against our

04:25:30.040 --> 04:25:42.239
rebellious horse herders.” But the Russians did&nbsp;
not listen to this, but killed all the envoys.

04:25:43.560 --> 04:25:52.080
Still confident of victory, the Russians advanced&nbsp;
to crush the Mongol invaders. At the sight of the

04:25:52.080 --> 04:25:58.920
European army, with its mass of peasant infantry,&nbsp;
supported by colorful columns of heavily-armed

04:25:58.920 --> 04:26:04.520
knights, their pennants flying and helmets&nbsp;
gleaming, the Mongols appeared to retreat

04:26:04.520 --> 04:26:13.640
in panic. The Russians were encouraged, and so,&nbsp;
they gave chase. They pursued the Mongols for a

04:26:13.640 --> 04:26:20.680
whole day, and then another, and then another, but&nbsp;
whenever they thought they were getting close,

04:26:20.680 --> 04:26:27.760
their quarry just managed to pull away. They&nbsp;
became perturbed by the almost supernatural

04:26:27.760 --> 04:26:34.359
speed and endurance of these foreigners, how they&nbsp;
never seemed to stop or slow down, never seemed

04:26:34.359 --> 04:26:44.239
to need supplies, never slept or lit campfires.&nbsp;
Gradually, the Europeans ran out out of steam.

04:26:44.239 --> 04:26:51.399
Their horses grew tired, and their footsoldiers,&nbsp;
too. It was at this point that the Mongol trap

04:26:51.399 --> 04:27:00.639
swung shut. On the 1st of April 1223, without&nbsp;
warning, a second Mongol army swept out of the

04:27:00.640 --> 04:27:07.640
forests and began a massacre on the banks&nbsp;
of the Kalka River, as the Novgorod Chronicle

04:27:07.640 --> 04:27:18.239
recalls. There was a terrible and savage&nbsp;
slaughter, and Mstislav, Duke of Kiev, seeing this

04:27:18.239 --> 04:27:26.000
evil, set up a stockade of posts about him,&nbsp;
and fought with them for three days, and of

04:27:26.000 --> 04:27:33.520
the rest of the troops, only every 10th&nbsp;
returned to his home. A countless number

04:27:33.520 --> 04:27:42.120
of people perished, and there was lamentation and&nbsp;
weeping and grief throughout towns and villages.

04:27:45.560 --> 04:27:51.399
As the infantry was slaughtered,&nbsp;
the princes of Kiev tried to flee the

04:27:51.399 --> 04:27:58.159
battlefield, but they were easily hunted down&nbsp;
by the Mongols. A great part of the kingdom's

04:27:58.159 --> 04:28:05.559
aristocracy was wiped out in that single day&nbsp;
of battle. It's recorded that several Kievan

04:28:05.560 --> 04:28:11.640
nobles were captured, and as a punishment&nbsp;
for killing the Mongol ambassadors, they

04:28:11.640 --> 04:28:18.080
were stuffed under the floorboards of one of&nbsp;
the Mongol tents. All night, the Mongol warriors

04:28:18.080 --> 04:28:25.119
feasted and celebrated their victory, their weight&nbsp;
steadily crushing to death the nobles beneath the

04:28:25.119 --> 04:28:37.000
floor. Then, with their mission complete,&nbsp;
the Mongols vanished. They had appeared,

04:28:37.000 --> 04:28:42.040
wiped out an entire army with ease,&nbsp;
and then disappeared without a trace.

04:28:43.760 --> 04:28:53.040
The Novgorod Chronicle records the confusion that&nbsp;
the event sowed. The Tartars turned back from the

04:28:53.040 --> 04:29:02.519
river Dnieper, and we know not where they came from,&nbsp;
nor where they hid themselves again. Only God knows

04:29:02.520 --> 04:29:13.920
where he fetched them against us for our
sins. To the medieval European mind, the meaning

04:29:13.920 --> 04:29:23.080
of this event was clear; it was a punishment from&nbsp;
God. But little did they know that worse was on its

04:29:23.080 --> 04:29:42.239
way. It was the winter of 1237, on the frozen&nbsp;
expanse of the Russian steppe, when the first

04:29:42.239 --> 04:29:49.119
Mongol horsemen once more appeared&nbsp;
on the edge of Europe, but this time

04:29:49.119 --> 04:29:57.399
they came to stay. In his Chronica&nbsp;
Majora, or Great Chronicle, the English

04:29:57.399 --> 04:30:02.719
writer Matthew Paris wrote about&nbsp;
these newcomers in terms of utter

04:30:02.720 --> 04:30:12.279
condemnation. An immense horde of that&nbsp;
detestable race of Satan, the Tartars, rushed

04:30:12.279 --> 04:30:19.759
forth like demons loosed from hell. They are&nbsp;
inhuman and of the nature of beasts,

04:30:19.760 --> 04:30:25.840
rather to be called monsters than man,&nbsp;
thirsting after and drinking blood, and

04:30:25.840 --> 04:30:32.920
tearing and devouring the flesh of dogs&nbsp;
and human beings. They are invincible in

04:30:32.920 --> 04:30:41.920
battle. They have no human laws, know no&nbsp;
mercy, and are crueler than lions or bears.

04:30:43.359 --> 04:30:48.679
The Mongols had waited until the winter set&nbsp;
in for their invasion, so that the great rivers

04:30:48.680 --> 04:30:56.399
Volga and Dnieper would freeze over, turning&nbsp;
them into a highway for their horses. Moving

04:30:56.399 --> 04:31:03.439
fast over the frozen ground, they once more easily&nbsp;
encircled the Russian armies and utterly destroyed

04:31:03.439 --> 04:31:12.239
them. It wasn't just the speed of&nbsp;
the invasion that took the Europeans

04:31:12.239 --> 04:31:19.359
by surprise. For people in Europe, the technologies&nbsp;
that the Mongols brought with them were so

04:31:19.359 --> 04:31:26.799
advanced as to be indistinguishable from magic.&nbsp;
In the city of Ryazan, the citizens were so

04:31:26.800 --> 04:31:33.399
terrified by the Mongols’ incendiary weaponry,&nbsp;
the Chinese fire lances, and pots of flaming

04:31:33.399 --> 04:31:39.279
naphtha that they hurled from their catapults, that&nbsp;
in the confusion they believed that the Mongols

04:31:39.279 --> 04:31:47.639
had brought with them trained dragons from the&nbsp;
east. By 1240, virtually all the major cities of

04:31:47.640 --> 04:31:56.199
Russia had fallen to the Mongols. In December,&nbsp;
they rounded on what was then the cultural,

04:31:56.199 --> 04:32:06.839
religious, and economic heart of the region, the&nbsp;
great city on the Dnieper, the city of

04:32:06.839 --> 04:32:17.920
Kiev. Kiev held out for nine days, during which the&nbsp;
Mongol catapults bombarded it with stones and

04:32:17.920 --> 04:32:25.880
flaming projectiles. In terror, its population&nbsp;
flooded towards the great stone Church of the

04:32:25.880 --> 04:32:32.080
Tithes that stood on the banks of the&nbsp;
Dnieper River. They were desperate to get

04:32:32.080 --> 04:32:37.920
close to the shrine of the Virgin Mary, which&nbsp;
they hoped would protect them, and climbed up

04:32:37.920 --> 04:32:43.960
onto the church's roof. But the weight of the&nbsp;
crowd on the roof timbers caused them to

04:32:43.960 --> 04:32:51.239
collapse, and many of those sheltering within&nbsp;
the church were crushed. The Mongol army soon

04:32:51.239 --> 04:32:59.840
flooded into the city and put its people to&nbsp;
the sword. Of Kiev's 50,000 inhabitants, it's

04:32:59.840 --> 04:33:08.439
reported that only 2,000 or so
survived. After the invasion, many Russian

04:33:08.439 --> 04:33:15.359
cities fell into ruin, and stone building&nbsp;
stopped for many decades. Economic links

04:33:15.359 --> 04:33:22.920
between cities and nearby villages were broken,&nbsp;
and famine spread, as the Novgorod Chronicle

04:33:22.920 --> 04:33:33.680
recounts. For what is there to say, or what to&nbsp;
speak of the punishment that came to us from God?

04:33:33.680 --> 04:33:41.719
How some of the common people killed the living&nbsp;
and ate them. Others ate horseflesh, dogs, and cats.

04:33:44.039 --> 04:33:55.519
Some fed on moss, snails, pine bark, lime bark, lime and&nbsp;
elm tree leaves, and whatever each could think of.

04:33:55.520 --> 04:34:02.279
Again, other wicked men began to burn the good&nbsp;
people's houses, where they suspected that there

04:34:02.279 --> 04:34:11.718
was grain. Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, the&nbsp;
Pope's envoy to the Mongol Great Khan, traveled

04:34:11.719 --> 04:34:18.920
through Kiev a few years later in February&nbsp;
1246, and wrote the following description of the

04:34:18.920 --> 04:34:25.719
destruction. When we were journeying through&nbsp;
the land, we came across countless skulls and

04:34:25.719 --> 04:34:30.959
bones of dead men lying about on the&nbsp;
ground. Kiev had been a very large and

04:34:30.959 --> 04:34:36.959
thickly populated town, but now it has been&nbsp;
reduced almost to nothing, for there are at

04:34:36.959 --> 04:34:43.000
the present time scarce 200 houses there,&nbsp;
and the inhabitants are kept in complete

04:34:43.000 --> 04:34:55.920
slavery. In some places, it took more than&nbsp;
100 years for Russian cities to rebuild,

04:34:55.920 --> 04:35:04.760
but after devastating Russia, Ogedei’s forces were&nbsp;
just getting started. One Mongol army perhaps

04:35:04.760 --> 04:35:11.760
50,000 strong headed west through the duchies&nbsp;
of Poland, riding in the direction of Germany

04:35:11.760 --> 04:35:19.439
and the Holy Roman Empire, and from there,&nbsp;
all of Western Europe was in their path.

04:35:19.439 --> 04:35:27.320
In all the cities of Europe, rumors ran rampant,&nbsp;
and all anyone had to work with was a name; the

04:35:27.320 --> 04:35:33.840
Tartars. Some believed that the name must mean&nbsp;
that the Mongols had actually come from Hell

04:35:33.840 --> 04:35:39.160
itself, since it reminded them of the name for&nbsp;
the deepest region of the underworld in Greek

04:35:39.160 --> 04:35:45.519
mythology, Tartarus. Others thought that the&nbsp;
name reminded them of the Biblical King of

04:35:45.520 --> 04:35:51.879
Tarshish, mentioned in the Bible. Others still&nbsp;
thought that the Mongols may have been one

04:35:51.879 --> 04:35:59.639
of the lost tribes of Israel, now returned to wreak&nbsp;
havoc on Christendom, perhaps enraged by the theft

04:35:59.639 --> 04:36:08.439
of relics from the Holy Land during the Crusades.&nbsp;
The English monk Matthew of Paris was especially

04:36:08.439 --> 04:36:14.400
responsible for spreading this idea, and tried&nbsp;
to work his way around the inconvenient fact

04:36:14.400 --> 04:36:21.039
that the Mongols didn't appear to speak Hebrew&nbsp;
or seem to be Jewish, as he wrote in his Great

04:36:21.039 --> 04:36:29.279
Chronicle. In the time of the government of&nbsp;
Moses, their rebellious hearts were perverted to

04:36:29.279 --> 04:36:36.879
an evil way of thinking, so that they followed&nbsp;
after strange gods and unknown customs. Their

04:36:36.879 --> 04:36:44.199
heart and language was confused, and their life&nbsp;
changed to that of the cruel and irrational wild

04:36:44.199 --> 04:36:52.760
beast. Unable to beat the Mongols on the&nbsp;
battlefield, people instead began to lash

04:36:52.760 --> 04:36:59.920
out against the defenseless Jewish communities&nbsp;
in countless European cities, and a wave of deadly

04:36:59.920 --> 04:37:09.199
pogroms began. In 1239, a fiery comet passed&nbsp;
by the Earth, seeming to some to be a sign

04:37:09.199 --> 04:37:18.320
of God's judgment, and in 1241, the panic only&nbsp;
increased as an eclipse blotted out the sun.

04:37:18.320 --> 04:37:25.840
People began to believe that the end of days&nbsp;
might finally have arrived. But the northern

04:37:25.840 --> 04:37:32.639
Mongol force headed towards Germany was in&nbsp;
fact just a distraction, a typical Mongol

04:37:32.639 --> 04:37:39.400
tactic to attack in multiple places at once,&nbsp;
and in fact, their true goal was a land that

04:37:39.400 --> 04:37:45.320
was much more amenable to their lifestyle;&nbsp;
that is the rolling grasslands and river

04:37:45.320 --> 04:37:52.718
plains of Hungary, which sat on the edge of the&nbsp;
great steppe behind the wall of the Carpathian

04:37:52.719 --> 04:38:01.920
mountains. Hungary, too, had given shelter to Kipchak&nbsp;
Turks fleeing from the Mongols, who had begged for

04:38:01.920 --> 04:38:11.440
shelter from the Hungarian King Bela IV. The&nbsp;
Mongols sent King Bela the following message.

04:38:13.760 --> 04:38:21.520
I have learned that you keep the Kipchaks, my&nbsp;
slaves, under your protection. I charge you that

04:38:21.520 --> 04:38:28.719
you do not make me your enemy on their account,&nbsp;
for it is easier for them to escape than for you.

04:38:28.719 --> 04:38:35.080
Since they, having no house and continually on the&nbsp;
move with their tents may possibly escape, but you,

04:38:35.080 --> 04:38:41.480
living in houses and possessing fortresses&nbsp;
and cities, how can you flee from my grasp?

04:38:41.480 --> 04:38:55.119
For a time, the Hungarian troops managed&nbsp;
to hold off the Mongols on a narrow bridge

04:38:55.119 --> 04:39:01.760
on a crossing of the Sajo River, but&nbsp;
their resistance did not last long.

04:39:01.760 --> 04:39:11.360
One priest and writer, Thomas of Spalato, wrote an&nbsp;
eye-witness account of the aftermath of the battle.

04:39:12.480 --> 04:39:18.240
The dead fell to the right and to the left&nbsp;
like leaves in winter. The slain bodies of

04:39:18.240 --> 04:39:25.799
these miserable men were strewn across the whole&nbsp;
route. Blood poured forth like torrents of rain. The

04:39:25.799 --> 04:39:32.439
miserable country, stained by the blood of its&nbsp;
sons, was dyed red throughout its length and

04:39:32.439 --> 04:39:41.679
breadth. From there, the Mongols poured into the&nbsp;
great Hungarian plain. They wiped out the royal

04:39:41.680 --> 04:39:48.359
army and sacked towns and villages, rounding up&nbsp;
huge numbers of skilled people who they took

04:39:48.359 --> 04:39:54.879
away with them, drafting others to take part&nbsp;
in their human wave assaults of fortresses,

04:39:54.879 --> 04:40:04.520
just as they had in China and Persia, and killing&nbsp;
countless others. The Hungarian King Bela fled

04:40:04.520 --> 04:40:11.480
south to the coastal regions of his kingdom&nbsp;
in what is now Croatia, and like the Khwarazm-

04:40:11.480 --> 04:40:20.839
Shah, he took a boat out into the Adriatic and took&nbsp;
refuge on an island there. Archaeology paints a

04:40:20.840 --> 04:40:29.400
clear picture of the desperation of this time. The&nbsp;
remains of many medieval Hungarian churches can be

04:40:29.400 --> 04:40:37.039
found with concentric rings of earthwork defenses,&nbsp;
hurriedly constructed, and the Earth around them

04:40:37.039 --> 04:40:45.799
is littered with arrowheads and the bones of the&nbsp;
unfortunate defenders. A great number of

04:40:45.799 --> 04:40:52.799
buried coin hoards have also been uncovered from&nbsp;
around this time, as the kingdom's wealthy rushed

04:40:52.799 --> 04:41:00.600
to hide their riches from the advancing Mongol&nbsp;
tide. When the Mongols finally withdrew from

04:41:00.600 --> 04:41:10.320
Hungary in 1242, a year after they had arrived,&nbsp;
they left behind a devastated land. One Italian

04:41:10.320 --> 04:41:17.160
bishop living in Hungary named Roger of Torre
Maggiore, wrote the following description of the

04:41:17.160 --> 04:41:26.080
desolation. We climbed a tall tree and&nbsp;
surveyed the land destroyed by the Tartars.

04:41:26.080 --> 04:41:32.320
What pain. We began to walk across the waste&nbsp;
and abandoned land that they had destroyed

04:41:32.320 --> 04:41:38.519
while retreating. Church towers were our&nbsp;
way signs, and the road they marked for us

04:41:38.520 --> 04:41:48.100
was rough. The roads and paths had vanished.&nbsp;
Grass and thorn bushes had taken over.

04:41:48.100 --> 04:41:56.879
The Mongols were now on the borders of&nbsp;
both the Holy Roman Empire and the Byzantine

04:41:56.879 --> 04:42:03.279
Empire, Europe's two major powers. It&nbsp;
looked as though all of Europe would

04:42:03.279 --> 04:42:11.400
now fall just like Northern China and the&nbsp;
Khwarazmian Empire before it. If it had, it's likely

04:42:11.400 --> 04:42:17.718
that the entire history of the world would&nbsp;
have gone down another path. If the Mongols

04:42:17.719 --> 04:42:24.119
had devastated Florence, Venice, and Milan the&nbsp;
way they had devastated Beijing and Samarqand,

04:42:24.119 --> 04:42:29.799
the Renaissance would likely never&nbsp;
have taken place, and the modern world as

04:42:29.799 --> 04:42:39.240
we know it would have struggled to be born. But&nbsp;
history again had other plans. One event would

04:42:39.240 --> 04:42:46.840
transpire that would save Europe from this&nbsp;
fate; that was the death of the Great Khan Ogedei.

04:42:46.840 --> 04:43:08.639
Ogedei had always been a great drinker, but&nbsp;
in recent years his alcoholism had truly got out

04:43:08.639 --> 04:43:17.760
of control, partly due to tragedy in his personal&nbsp;
life. His beloved brother Tolui had died a few years

04:43:17.760 --> 04:43:25.359
earlier, with some even whispering that Oegedei had&nbsp;
had him poisoned, and his favorite son and heir,

04:43:25.359 --> 04:43:33.160
Kochu, had also died fighting in China, a mission&nbsp;
that Ogedei himself had sent him on. From that

04:43:33.160 --> 04:43:42.680
point, with grief and guilt seemingly warring inside&nbsp;
him, Ogedei seems to have sunk into a depression. He

04:43:42.680 --> 04:43:50.760
withdrew from government, increasingly losing his&nbsp;
appetite for ruling, and all the while, he drank and

04:43:50.760 --> 04:44:02.439
drank. On the 11th of December 1241, the Great&nbsp;
Khan Ogedei, the son of Chinggis Khan, died as he

04:44:02.439 --> 04:44:11.039
had lived — in a drunken stupor — after&nbsp;
thirteen years of rule, and at the age of 55.

04:44:12.080 --> 04:44:17.160
The Secret History contains a note&nbsp;
supposedly written by Ogedei himself,

04:44:17.160 --> 04:44:27.480
but almost certainly penned by one of his&nbsp;
successors, in which he notes his failures.

04:44:27.480 --> 04:44:38.878
I have sat on the great throne of my&nbsp;
Khan father. I made the nation live with their

04:44:38.879 --> 04:44:47.480
soles on the soil and their grip on the ground,&nbsp;
yet although I carried forward on my back the

04:44:47.480 --> 04:44:57.400
teaming kingdom, it was an error of mine to be&nbsp;
vanquished by grape wine. This was one of my

04:44:57.400 --> 04:45:11.279
errors. With Jochi and Tolui by now all&nbsp;
dead, and Chaghatai dead soon after,

04:45:11.279 --> 04:45:18.560
the last surviving son of Chinggis Khan had&nbsp;
passed away. But as a man who had lived every

04:45:18.561 --> 04:45:24.561
day in the moment and thought little of the&nbsp;
future, crucially, since the death of his oldest

04:45:24.561 --> 04:45:32.240
son, Ogedei had named no successor. There was now&nbsp;
no certainty at all over who would rule the

04:45:32.240 --> 04:45:41.279
empire. After his death, all of Ogedei's successors&nbsp;
raised their claims to the throne of the Great

04:45:41.279 --> 04:45:48.959
Khan, and even Chinggis Khan's surviving brother&nbsp;
Temuge, now in his seventies, suggested that he should

04:45:48.959 --> 04:45:58.000
rule. Suddenly, all plans of advancing further&nbsp;
west into Europe were forgotten. This power

04:45:58.000 --> 04:46:05.680
struggle would last for ten years, and for five of&nbsp;
these, the empire was ruled by a woman, the widow

04:46:05.680 --> 04:46:15.639
of Ogedei, named Toregene Khan. She performed
all the duties of a Mongol Khan; minting coins,

04:46:15.639 --> 04:46:25.279
holding kuriltais, and ensured the succession of&nbsp;
her son, Guyuk. He ruled for a further three years, and

04:46:25.279 --> 04:46:32.240
during this time declared his intention to&nbsp;
launch a full-scale invasion of Europe, even

04:46:32.240 --> 04:46:40.959
sending a letter demanding submission from the&nbsp;
pope. But his health would deteriorate, and he

04:46:40.959 --> 04:46:50.879
died while traveling on the 20th of April 1248.&nbsp;
Europe, once again, was spared, and during this time

04:46:50.879 --> 04:47:10.840
of upheaval in the Mongol Empire, the rest of the&nbsp;
world could breathe something of a side of relief.

04:47:14.799 --> 04:47:18.320
The struggle over who would&nbsp;
become Khan would eventually

04:47:18.320 --> 04:47:21.840
come to an end with the rise of a man named

04:47:21.840 --> 04:47:33.879
Mongke. The previous Great Khan Ogedei had seven&nbsp;
sons, but Mongke was not one of them. He was

04:47:33.879 --> 04:47:40.840
the oldest son of Tolui, the one brother who had&nbsp;
never been considered for the position of Khan.

04:47:41.799 --> 04:47:46.719
We can tell that this was an awkward fact&nbsp;
for Mongke, since one of his first official

04:47:46.719 --> 04:47:53.439
acts was to crown his father Tolui as Great&nbsp;
Khan posthumously, thus strengthening his

04:47:53.439 --> 04:47:59.878
own legitimacy, and when Mongke came to&nbsp;
the throne in 1251, he is said to have

04:47:59.879 --> 04:48:06.439
given a statement that acted as a rebuke&nbsp;
of the ways of his profligate predecessor,

04:48:06.439 --> 04:48:15.878
Ogedei. I follow the laws of my ancestors.&nbsp;
I do not imitate other countries’ ways.

04:48:15.879 --> 04:48:28.279
This question of what kind of&nbsp;
society the Mongol Empire would be

04:48:28.279 --> 04:48:35.879
is one that would resurface again and&nbsp;
again over the coming century. Like his

04:48:35.879 --> 04:48:40.920
father before him, Mongke was an accomplished&nbsp;
warrior and had fought as one of the most

04:48:40.920 --> 04:48:48.959
prominent generals in the invasion of Russia. He&nbsp;
also had Tolui’s somewhat bloodthirsty and ruthless

04:48:48.959 --> 04:48:56.760
streak. To quell any resistance when he came to&nbsp;
power, Mongke purged all members of the nobility

04:48:56.760 --> 04:49:04.080
who had supported other claimants to the throne&nbsp;
of the Great Khan, many of whom were his cousins.

04:49:04.080 --> 04:49:10.920
More than 300 members of the Mongol aristocracy&nbsp;
were slaughtered. While the Mongols were hardly

04:49:10.920 --> 04:49:17.359
shy about spilling blood, this amount of killing&nbsp;
in the upper echelons of Mongol society was

04:49:17.359 --> 04:49:27.519
unprecedented. After that, he turned his attention&nbsp;
to further conquests. He gave command of his troops

04:49:27.520 --> 04:49:34.160
in Persia to one of his brothers named Hulagu,&nbsp;
and his troops in Northern China to another

04:49:34.160 --> 04:49:42.840
brother named Kublai, ordering him to prepare&nbsp;
for an invasion of Southern Song China.

04:49:42.840 --> 04:49:49.359
Meanwhile, the Khan Mongke remained back in&nbsp;
the imperial heartland, in his capital of

04:49:49.359 --> 04:50:02.759
Karakorum. It was during the reign of Mongke&nbsp;
Khan that the King of France, Louis IX,

04:50:02.760 --> 04:50:11.000
sent an ambassador to Mongolia, a Flemish&nbsp;
friar named William of Rubruck. He would write

04:50:11.000 --> 04:50:18.439
one of the most fascinating accounts of life in&nbsp;
the Mongol court of Karakorum at this time. After

04:50:18.439 --> 04:50:25.400
many months of travel across the steppe of Central&nbsp;
Asia, William of Rubruck arrived at the Mongol capital

04:50:25.400 --> 04:50:34.480
late in the year 1253. He was taken to see the Khan,&nbsp;
and gives a rare description of the appearance of

04:50:34.480 --> 04:50:43.320
Mongke. The Khan was sitting on a couch, dressed&nbsp;
in a fur which was spotted and very glossy,

04:50:43.320 --> 04:50:54.519
like a seal skin. He is snub-nosed, a man of medium&nbsp;
build, and aged about forty-five. William was frustrated

04:50:54.520 --> 04:51:00.320
because his interpreter was drinking continually&nbsp;
throughout his meeting with the Khan, and by the

04:51:00.320 --> 04:51:08.160
end was thoroughly drunk. By this point, he could&nbsp;
hardly understand what the Mongol ruler was saying.

04:51:08.160 --> 04:51:15.199
Nevertheless, the Khan gave them permission to stay&nbsp;
in the city, and William of Rubruck began exploring

04:51:15.199 --> 04:51:22.679
the Mongol capital. In this melting pot in the&nbsp;
heart of the empire, he encountered people from

04:51:22.680 --> 04:51:32.000
all over Eurasia, including one monk from China&nbsp;
who seems to have had some fun at his expense.

04:51:32.000 --> 04:51:39.240
On one occasion, a priest from China was sitting&nbsp;
with me, dressed in cloth of the finest red, and I

04:51:39.240 --> 04:51:47.320
asked him where he came by such a color. He told me&nbsp;
how in the east of China there are soaring crags

04:51:47.320 --> 04:51:54.359
inhabited by creatures built like human beings&nbsp;
in every respect, except that their knees do not

04:51:54.359 --> 04:52:01.519
bend, and they move along in a kind of hopping,&nbsp;
and that they are one cubit tall and covered in

04:52:01.520 --> 04:52:09.480
hair. They live in inaccessible caves, and when men&nbsp;
go hunting them, they take the most intoxicating

04:52:09.480 --> 04:52:16.400
ale they can brew and make cup-shaped hollows&nbsp;
in the rocks, which they fill with the ale. So,

04:52:16.400 --> 04:52:23.000
the hunters lie hidden, and these creatures emerge&nbsp;
from their caves and sample the drink, crying ‘chin

04:52:23.000 --> 04:52:30.559
chin’, and it is from this cry that their name&nbsp;
is derived, for they are known as chinchin. Then

04:52:30.559 --> 04:52:37.439
they gather round in very great numbers, become&nbsp;
drunk, and fall asleep on the spot. At this point,

04:52:37.439 --> 04:52:44.400
the hunters come forward and tie their hands and&nbsp;
feet while they are asleep, and next, they open up

04:52:44.400 --> 04:52:51.199
a vein in their necks and extract from each one&nbsp;
three or four drops of blood before letting them

04:52:51.199 --> 04:53:04.558
go free. The blood, the priest told me, is of the&nbsp;
greatest value for making purple dye. But

04:53:04.559 --> 04:53:10.320
despite his slightly gullible nature, William&nbsp;
explored the city diligently, and there he

04:53:10.320 --> 04:53:16.080
was astonished to find a number of other&nbsp;
Europeans living and working in this foreign

04:53:16.080 --> 04:53:25.439
land, thousands of kilometers from home. We were&nbsp;
discovered by a woman from Metz in France named

04:53:25.439 --> 04:53:32.359
Pascha, who had been captured in Hungary, and she&nbsp;
made us as substantial a meal as she could. She

04:53:32.359 --> 04:53:39.119
told us about the unheard of destitution she&nbsp;
had suffered, but now she was well enough off.

04:53:39.119 --> 04:53:45.920
She had a young Russian husband by whom&nbsp;
she had three very fine little boys. She told us

04:53:45.920 --> 04:53:53.000
that there was also a master goldsmith at Karakorum
called William, originally from Paris, whose surname

04:53:53.000 --> 04:54:01.359
is Bucher. This William Bucher had been working&nbsp;
in Hungary when the Mongols swept in from the

04:54:01.359 --> 04:54:09.279
steppe, and like many others before him, he had been&nbsp;
rounded up for his skill in metalworking. When he

04:54:09.279 --> 04:54:15.959
arrived in Karakorum, the Khan Mongke had soon&nbsp;
recognized his potential, and set him to work

04:54:15.959 --> 04:54:24.359
building a remarkable mechanical contraption out&nbsp;
of silver. At the entrance to this great palace,

04:54:24.359 --> 04:54:32.199
Master William of Paris has constructed for him a&nbsp;
large tree made of silver, with four silver lions

04:54:32.199 --> 04:54:40.320
at its roots, each one containing a conduit pipe&nbsp;
and spewing forth white mare's milk. The branches,

04:54:40.879 --> 04:54:48.000
leaves, and fruit of the tree are of silver. There&nbsp;
are four conduits leading into the tree, and over

04:54:48.000 --> 04:54:55.080
each one of them lies a gilded serpent with&nbsp;
its tail twined around the trunk. One of the

04:54:55.080 --> 04:55:03.760
pipes discharges wine, a second fermented mare's&nbsp;
milk, a third a kind of mead, and a fourth a rich

04:55:03.760 --> 04:55:10.321
ale. Each beverage has its own silver vessel&nbsp;
at the foot of the tree, ready to receive it.

04:55:12.480 --> 04:55:15.439
The fountain even had a method of announcing to

04:55:15.439 --> 04:55:20.679
guests that the drinking had begun,&nbsp;
the perfect centerpiece for a Mongol feast.

04:55:20.680 --> 04:55:31.559
Between the four pipes at the top, he made an&nbsp;
angel holding a trumpet, so when drink is required,

04:55:31.559 --> 04:55:39.840
a man concealed in its cavity then blows strongly&nbsp;
on the pipe that leads to the angel. The angel

04:55:39.840 --> 04:55:46.840
puts the trumpet to its mouth, and the trumpet&nbsp;
gives out a very loud blast. When the stewards

04:55:46.840 --> 04:55:53.160
in the chamber hear this, each pours his drink&nbsp;
into the appropriate pipe, and the pipes spurt

04:55:53.160 --> 04:56:02.279
it out. By this time, Christianity had&nbsp;
made great inroads at the Mongol court, and many

04:56:02.279 --> 04:56:08.599
of the Khan's wives were Christians, but there&nbsp;
were also Muslim, Buddhist, and even Jewish holy

04:56:08.600 --> 04:56:15.959
men living in Karakorum, all enjoying the freedom&nbsp;
of religion that made the Mongol realm virtually

04:56:15.959 --> 04:56:23.840
unique around the world. The Khan Mongke was curious&nbsp;
about religion, but seems to have courted each

04:56:23.840 --> 04:56:30.320
faith without ever converting to one of them. In&nbsp;
order to perhaps settle the matter once and for

04:56:30.320 --> 04:56:37.638
all, the Great Khan organized a series of debates,&nbsp;
and invited the friar, William of Rubruck, to take

04:56:37.639 --> 04:56:46.279
part. The following day, he sent to me his&nbsp;
secretaries, who said, “Our master is sending us

04:56:46.279 --> 04:56:55.199
to you with this message; here you are, Christians,&nbsp;
Saracens, and Buddhists, and each one of you claims

04:56:55.199 --> 04:57:03.638
that his religion is superior and that his&nbsp;
writings or books contain more truth. So, he

04:57:03.639 --> 04:57:10.639
would like you all to assemble together and hold&nbsp;
a conference, and each one to put his claims in

04:57:10.639 --> 04:57:19.680
writing to enable the Khan to learn the truth.”&nbsp;
William accepted, but he soon found out that

04:57:19.680 --> 04:57:26.359
the Mongols arranged their intellectual debates&nbsp;
much like their wrestling matches. This would

04:57:26.359 --> 04:57:33.400
be a rowdy, boisterous affair, and like Mongol&nbsp;
wrestlers, the debaters were expected to drink

04:57:33.400 --> 04:57:40.519
a large cup of alcoholic kumis between&nbsp;
each round. Quickly, the holy men became

04:57:40.520 --> 04:57:49.600
drunk. To their surprise and despite their bitter&nbsp;
differences back home, the Muslims and Christians

04:57:49.600 --> 04:57:55.520
found themselves largely in agreement on the&nbsp;
broad points, that there was one God, that he was

04:57:55.520 --> 04:58:03.279
all powerful, and that heaven awaited them after&nbsp;
death. Together, they argued against the Buddhists,

04:58:03.279 --> 04:58:09.959
who believed in many gods with limited powers,&nbsp;
and in reincarnation after death. They argued

04:58:09.959 --> 04:58:16.480
over the nature of good and evil, whether&nbsp;
everything in creation is good, and why God allows

04:58:16.480 --> 04:58:22.240
bad things to happen. According to William’s&nbsp;
own account, he effortlessly outsmarted his

04:58:22.240 --> 04:58:29.558
opponents. But to his disappointment, no one&nbsp;
agreed to convert to Christianity then and

04:58:29.559 --> 04:58:40.039
there. Everybody listened without challenging a&nbsp;
single word, but for all that, no one said, “I believe,

04:58:40.680 --> 04:58:46.279
and wish to become a Christian.” When&nbsp;
it was over, the Christians and Saracens

04:58:46.279 --> 04:58:54.080
alike sang in loud voices, while the Buddhists&nbsp;
remained silent, and after that, everyone drank

04:58:54.080 --> 04:59:03.920
heavily. But if William had hoped to convince&nbsp;
the Great Khan, he would be frustrated. For his

04:59:03.920 --> 04:59:15.840
part, Mongke Khan remained unconvinced. “We&nbsp;
Mongols,” he said, “believe that there is only one

04:59:15.840 --> 04:59:26.680
God, through whom we have life and through whom&nbsp;
we die, and towards him we direct our hearts. But

04:59:26.680 --> 04:59:36.799
just as God has given the hand several fingers, so&nbsp;
he has given mankind several paths. To you, God has

04:59:36.799 --> 04:59:46.039
given the scriptures, whereas to us he has given&nbsp;
shamans, and we do as they tell us, and live in peace.”

04:59:46.039 --> 04:59:59.359
The debates came to an inconclusive&nbsp;
end, and the question over which was the

04:59:59.359 --> 05:00:08.839
true religion would go unsettled for another day.&nbsp;
William would leave the Khan's court soon after,

05:00:08.840 --> 05:00:15.680
but during his time in Karakorum, he had noticed&nbsp;
some extraordinary measures of personal security

05:00:15.680 --> 05:00:22.799
surrounding Mongke and his household. William&nbsp;
himself was even grilled by the Khan's security

05:00:22.799 --> 05:00:31.760
services. They searched our legs, chests,&nbsp;
and arms to see whether we had knives

05:00:31.760 --> 05:00:39.000
on us. They made the interpreter take off his&nbsp;
belt. We were summoned by the grand secretary

05:00:39.000 --> 05:00:46.080
and judge, and they inquired most minutely&nbsp;
whence we came from, why we had come, what

05:00:46.080 --> 05:00:51.119
was our business, and this inquiry was&nbsp;
made because it had been reported to

05:00:51.119 --> 05:00:57.959
Mongke Khan that 40 assassins had entered&nbsp;
the city under various disguises to kill him.

05:00:57.959 --> 05:01:08.959
Mongke Khan had good reason to be worried. That's&nbsp;
because he had become a target for a controversial

05:01:08.959 --> 05:01:16.480
Islamic sect known as the Hashashin, a&nbsp;
group who have given us the English word

05:01:16.480 --> 05:01:43.039
assassin. The Hashashin occupied perhaps&nbsp;as
many as a hundred remote mountain fortresses

05:01:43.039 --> 05:01:49.160
across an area stretching from the Mediterranean&nbsp;
coast to Afghanistan, but they coordinated their

05:01:49.160 --> 05:01:55.879
operations from their headquarters, the lofty&nbsp;
Alamut Castle in the Alborz mountain range of

05:01:55.879 --> 05:02:04.039
northern Iran. Alamut means eagle's nest, and it&nbsp;
was perched high up on the mountain crags. The

05:02:04.039 --> 05:02:11.480
Hashashin had no armies to speak of, no infantry&nbsp;
and no cavalry, but they exercised a formidable

05:02:11.480 --> 05:02:20.558
strategic power. That is, they assassinated any&nbsp;
noble, general, or king who stood in their way. One

05:02:20.559 --> 05:02:27.920
writer named Benjamin of Tudela wrote an account&nbsp;
of these mysterious killers and their enigmatic

05:02:27.920 --> 05:02:38.760
ruler. They call him Sheikh-al-Hashishin. He&nbsp;
is their elder, and upon his command, all

05:02:38.760 --> 05:02:44.799
of the men of the mountain come out or&nbsp;
go in. They are believers of the word of

05:02:44.799 --> 05:02:50.359
their elder, and everyone everywhere&nbsp;
fears them, because they even kill

05:02:50.359 --> 05:02:58.400
kings. Although it's difficult to unpick the&nbsp;
legends from the truth when it comes to this

05:02:58.400 --> 05:03:04.359
secretive sect, according to Arab, Persian,&nbsp;
and Chinese sources, the name Hashashin comes

05:03:04.359 --> 05:03:10.400
from the group's predilection for the drug&nbsp;
hashish, a concentrated resin of the cannabis

05:03:10.400 --> 05:03:17.400
plant. According to legends, young men would be&nbsp;
initiated into the group by smoking hashish, and

05:03:17.400 --> 05:03:23.599
under its intoxicating effects, they were shown&nbsp;
the beautiful gardens that the Hashashin kept

05:03:23.600 --> 05:03:33.400
in their castles. Marco Polo recounted one version&nbsp;
of these tales. Upon awakening from this

05:03:33.400 --> 05:03:39.718
state of lethargy, their senses were struck with all&nbsp;
the delightful objects that have been described,

05:03:40.279 --> 05:03:46.240
and each perceived himself surrounded&nbsp;
by lovely damsels. He believed himself

05:03:46.240 --> 05:03:51.920
assuredly in paradise, and felt an&nbsp;
unwillingness to relinquish its

05:03:51.920 --> 05:03:57.959
delights. When four or five days had thus&nbsp;
been passed, they were carried out of the

05:03:57.959 --> 05:04:07.639
garden. The young initiates were&nbsp;
told that they had visited the gardens of

05:04:07.639 --> 05:04:12.400
paradise, and would be allowed to return&nbsp;
if they were willing to give their life

05:04:12.400 --> 05:04:18.679
for the cause. So long as the supply of&nbsp;
hashish was kept flowing, the group had

05:04:18.680 --> 05:04:25.559
an endless reserve of brainwashed young men&nbsp;
willing to do their bidding, as Marco Polo

05:04:25.559 --> 05:04:35.719
describes. Animated to enthusiasm by words of&nbsp;
this nature, all went forward to die in his

05:04:35.719 --> 05:04:42.039
service. The consequence of this system was&nbsp;
that when any of the neighboring princes or

05:04:42.039 --> 05:04:49.799
others gave insult to this chief, they were put&nbsp;
to death by these, his discipled assassins, none

05:04:49.799 --> 05:04:56.320
of whom felt terror at the risk of losing their&nbsp;own
lives, provided they could execute their master’s will.

05:04:56.320 --> 05:05:06.599
We don't know if these rumors were true or&nbsp;
just stories made up by the group's enemies. The

05:05:06.600 --> 05:05:13.920
word ‘hashishi’ can often mean simply ‘rebel’ or ‘outlaws’,&nbsp;
and their name may have actually been the Arabic

05:05:13.920 --> 05:05:21.879
word ‘asasiyyun’, meaning something like ‘the principled&nbsp;
ones’. Regardless of the truth, what is certain is

05:05:21.879 --> 05:05:26.959
that the assassins were a thorn in the side&nbsp;
of the mighty Middle Eastern powers like the

05:05:26.959 --> 05:05:34.840
Fatimid, Abbasid, and Seljuk empires. Over the course&nbsp;
of nearly two centuries, they killed hundreds of

05:05:34.840 --> 05:05:42.400
notable people, including three caliphs and one&nbsp;
Crusader king of Jerusalem, and now they had

05:05:42.400 --> 05:05:50.400
set their sights on the Khan of the Mongols. They had&nbsp;
clearly enjoyed the respite that the ten years of

05:05:50.400 --> 05:05:55.519
Mongol infighting had brought the world, and&nbsp;
hoped that by killing Mongke, they might bring

05:05:55.520 --> 05:06:05.199
about another, and perhaps even that the entire&nbsp;
Mongol entity would simply unravel. In the 1240s,

05:06:05.199 --> 05:06:12.920
one Mongol general was even assassinated by this&nbsp;
group, and for Mongke, this was the final straw. In

05:06:12.920 --> 05:06:19.920
1253, he ordered his younger brother Hulagu to&nbsp;
march into the west and crush the assassins for

05:06:19.920 --> 05:06:37.760
good. Hulagu advanced into Afghanistan, and from&nbsp;
there seized their fortresses one by one. Finally,

05:06:37.760 --> 05:06:45.879
he rounded on the eagle's nest castle of Alamut,&nbsp;
high in the snowy mountains of northern Iran.

05:06:45.879 --> 05:06:52.879
Ata-Malik Juvaini describes the sight that the&nbsp;
defenders of Alamut saw approaching through the

05:06:52.879 --> 05:07:03.000
jagged peaks. And from the direction of Ustundar
there came armies all fire and fury, along steep

05:07:03.000 --> 05:07:10.559
roads as crooked as the covenant of the wicked.&nbsp;
And from Alamut, which lay to the left, came

05:07:10.559 --> 05:07:18.559
the princes Balaghai and Tutar, with a great body&nbsp;
of men, all clamoring for vengeance with a host

05:07:18.559 --> 05:07:24.359
like a mountain of iron. The mountains and&nbsp;
valleys billowed with the great masses of men.

05:07:24.359 --> 05:07:31.359
The approach to Alamut was steep and virtually

05:07:31.359 --> 05:07:39.798
impregnable, but by now, the Mongol armies&nbsp;
were experts at siege warfare. With their morning

05:07:39.799 --> 05:07:48.080
draft, the Mongol army struck the harp of war and&nbsp;
prepared to do battle with mangonels and stones.

05:07:48.080 --> 05:07:54.039
They cut down and trimmed for these mangonels&nbsp;
the trees which these people had watered for

05:07:54.039 --> 05:08:01.840
many years past, not realizing what purpose they&nbsp;
would serve or what fruit they would ultimately

05:08:01.840 --> 05:08:09.639
bear. The castle of Alamut soon&nbsp;
surrendered, and the assassins

05:08:09.639 --> 05:08:16.680
were crushed as an independent force. With&nbsp;
this inconvenience safely out of the way,

05:08:16.680 --> 05:08:22.920
the Mongols now rounded on the Muslim&nbsp;
Middle East and its great capital of Baghdad.

05:08:22.920 --> 05:08:42.000
Baghdad at this time was a grand city. It&nbsp;
was the center of the Abbasid Caliphate throughout

05:08:42.000 --> 05:08:47.639
the Islamic Golden Age of the 9th and 10th&nbsp;
centuries, growing to be the largest city

05:08:47.639 --> 05:08:53.359
worldwide by the beginning of the 10th century,&nbsp;
and though at this point it had suffered some

05:08:53.359 --> 05:09:00.920
centuries of decline, it was still the beating&nbsp;
heart of the Muslim world. It was a city of cabarets

05:09:00.920 --> 05:09:09.439
and taverns, places where backgammon and chess were&nbsp;
played. On street corners, acrobats performed, and

05:09:09.439 --> 05:09:17.718
storytellers spun tales for their audiences like&nbsp;
those later found in the Arabian Nights. The city

05:09:17.719 --> 05:09:25.439
also had formidable defenses, with a high and&nbsp;
thick wall. Each of its four gates had double

05:09:25.439 --> 05:09:35.279
doors that were made of iron, so heavy that it took&nbsp;
several men to open and close them. The caliphate

05:09:35.279 --> 05:09:41.119
was ruled by the caliph, who was the supreme&nbsp;
religious figure cross the Muslim world,

05:09:41.119 --> 05:09:50.519
somewhere between an emperor and a pope. Until that&nbsp;
point, relations with the caliph in Baghdad, a man

05:09:50.520 --> 05:09:57.439
named Al-Mustasim, had been relatively friendly,&nbsp;
but the Mongols had asked him for soldiers to

05:09:57.439 --> 05:10:04.959
help them fight the assassins, and perhaps fearing&nbsp;
that their daggers might be turned against him, he

05:10:04.959 --> 05:10:13.439
ignored the Mongol request. This disrespect
was enough for the Khan Mongke to order his younger

05:10:13.439 --> 05:10:24.280
brother Hulagu to march down into the lowlands&nbsp;
of Mesopotamia and destroy the caliphate entirely.

05:10:24.280 --> 05:10:32.879
The Mongols gathered a huge&nbsp;
force, including a thousand Chinese

05:10:32.879 --> 05:10:39.240
siege engineers, and swept into the&nbsp;
plains of Mesopotamia in the year 1257.

05:10:40.039 --> 05:10:49.680
Hulagu sent a letter to the caliph Al-Mustasim,&nbsp;
urging him to surrender in ferocious terms.

05:10:49.680 --> 05:10:57.359
I will bring you crashing down from the summit of&nbsp;
the sky. Like a lion, I will throw you down to the

05:10:57.359 --> 05:11:08.039
lowest depths. I will not leave a single person&nbsp;
alive in your country. I will turn your city, lands,

05:11:08.039 --> 05:11:19.320
and empire into flames. If you have the heart to&nbsp;
save your head and your ancient family, listen

05:11:19.320 --> 05:11:28.439
carefully to my advice. If you refuse to accept&nbsp;
it, I will show you the meaning of the will of

05:11:28.439 --> 05:11:39.199
God. But the caliph Al-Mustasim did not listen.

05:11:42.959 --> 05:11:51.719
The Mongols arrived at the capital of Baghdad in&nbsp;
January of 1258. The 9th-century writer Al-Jahiz

05:11:51.719 --> 05:11:56.879
wrote the following description of the sight&nbsp;
that the Mongol soldiers would have seen as

05:11:56.879 --> 05:12:04.719
they approached across the broad floodplain&nbsp;
of the rushing river Tigris. I have seen such

05:12:04.719 --> 05:12:11.000
cities in the district of Syria, in Byzantine&nbsp;
territory, and in other provinces, but I have

05:12:11.000 --> 05:12:19.520
never seen a city of greater height or possessing&nbsp;
more spacious gates, or more perfect defenses than

05:12:19.520 --> 05:12:28.199
Baghdad. The Mongols settled in for a siege,&nbsp;
and built a rampart completely surrounding

05:12:28.199 --> 05:12:34.840
the city. They constructed their vast mangonels&nbsp;
and other siege engines, and began to bombard

05:12:34.840 --> 05:12:42.400
the city with their terrifying gunpowder weapons&nbsp;
and incendiary pots of naphtha, brought all the way

05:12:42.400 --> 05:12:49.759
from China. But once these ran out, the Mongols&nbsp;
realized that they had a problem. The valley of

05:12:49.760 --> 05:12:58.160
the Tigris and Euphrates is essentially a vast&nbsp;
salt flat, and contains virtually no stone. So,

05:12:58.160 --> 05:13:07.240
they had no projectiles for their catapults. Faced&nbsp;
with this problem, they would have to be creative.

05:13:07.240 --> 05:13:13.000
The Mongols began to cut down the heavy date&nbsp;
palms that grew everywhere along the riverbank,

05:13:13.000 --> 05:13:20.199
and loaded pieces of their heavy trunks into&nbsp;
their catapults. The citizens of Baghdad would

05:13:20.199 --> 05:13:26.920
soon face the sight of their own date trees&nbsp;
being hurled over enormous distances into the

05:13:26.920 --> 05:13:39.119
city. Mongol siege engines broke through Baghdad's&nbsp;
defenses within just a few days, and the assault

05:13:39.119 --> 05:13:48.599
on the walls began in late January. By February&nbsp;
the 4th, Hulagu's elite forces had seized control

05:13:48.600 --> 05:13:55.959
of the eastern wall. In a growing state of&nbsp;
desperation, the caliph Al-Mustasim made

05:13:55.959 --> 05:14:04.719
frantic attempts to negotiate, but Hulagu refused,&nbsp;
even executing the caliph’s soldiers who tried to

05:14:04.719 --> 05:14:12.119
surrender. The caliph ultimately capitulated&nbsp;
on February the 10th, and the Mongols captured

05:14:12.119 --> 05:14:20.639
him and began to sack the city. The Hawadit Al-Gamia,
written by an anonymous eyewitness, records the

05:14:20.639 --> 05:14:29.840
scenes of carnage. The inhabitants&nbsp;
of Baghdad were put under the sword on Monday,

05:14:29.840 --> 05:14:37.199
and were subjected to forty days of continuous&nbsp;
killing, pillaging, and enslavement. A great part

05:14:37.199 --> 05:14:43.519
of the city, including the caliph’s mosque and its&nbsp;
surrounding, were burnt, and the city was laid in

05:14:43.520 --> 05:14:51.600
ruins. The dead lay as mounds in the streets and&nbsp;
the markets. Rain fell on them. Horses trampled

05:14:51.600 --> 05:14:58.480
down upon them. Their faces were disfigured,&nbsp;
and they became an example to anyone who saw

05:14:58.480 --> 05:15:09.279
them. Some among the city's populations&nbsp;
were spared. The Xia Muslims in the city,

05:15:09.279 --> 05:15:15.759
as well as Baghdad's Jewish population, avoided&nbsp;
the worst of the massacre. The city's Christian

05:15:15.760 --> 05:15:22.959
community was also spared, since the Mongol&nbsp;
general Hulagu's wife was a Christian, and asked

05:15:22.959 --> 05:15:30.080
her husband to show them mercy. Many of the&nbsp;
glorious libraries of Baghdad were destroyed,

05:15:30.080 --> 05:15:36.680
and the books within them likely burned up&nbsp;
in the fires that engulfed the city. Some later

05:15:36.680 --> 05:15:45.119
sources like Qutb ad-Din an-Nahrawali, writing around
300 years later, embellished the story with the poetic

05:15:45.119 --> 05:15:50.879
flourish that the river Tigris had turned&nbsp;
black with the ink of the books thrown into it.

05:15:50.879 --> 05:16:00.680
After the slaughter was done, Hulagu held a&nbsp;
victory feast, where he had the caliph brought

05:16:00.680 --> 05:16:07.760
to him in chains. The chronicler Nasir ad-Din
at-Tusi, who may have been present as

05:16:07.760 --> 05:16:16.480
an eyewitness, recorded the words of the Mongol&nbsp;
general. Hulagu set a golden tray before the caliph

05:16:16.480 --> 05:16:26.279
and said, “Eat.” “It is not edible,” said the caliph. “Then&nbsp;
why did you keep it?” asked the Khan, “and not give

05:16:26.279 --> 05:16:32.599
it to your soldiers? And why did you not make&nbsp;
these iron doors into arrowheads and come to

05:16:32.600 --> 05:16:38.840
the bank of the river so that I might not have&nbsp;
been able to cross it?” “Such,” replied the caliph,

05:16:39.359 --> 05:16:45.718
“was God's will.” “What will befall&nbsp;
you,” said the Khan, “is also God's will.”

05:16:45.719 --> 05:16:53.279
The caliph was rolled up in&nbsp;
a carpet and trampled to death by

05:16:53.279 --> 05:16:58.320
horses, in accordance with the Mongol&nbsp;
requirements that royal blood not be

05:16:58.320 --> 05:17:05.240
spilled. The sack of Baghdad tore the&nbsp;
heart out of the Muslim world, and

05:17:05.240 --> 05:17:13.080
ended the 500-year rule of the Abbasid Caliphate,&nbsp;
but the Mongol armies were just getting

05:17:13.080 --> 05:17:25.879
started. Hulagu arrived at the Syrian city of&nbsp;
Aleppo in December 1259, and after a siege of

05:17:25.879 --> 05:17:34.760
seven days, stormed it and massacred its population.&nbsp;
The sultan of Syria, An-Nasir Yusuf, was still at

05:17:34.760 --> 05:17:43.080
large, and when the news of the sack of Aleppo&nbsp;
reached him, he and his army fled south. The

05:17:43.080 --> 05:17:51.480
Mongols followed hot on his heels, and captured&nbsp;
Damascus sixteen days after they had taken Aleppo.

05:17:51.480 --> 05:17:57.759
The Mongols followed the sultan down the shores of&nbsp;
the Mediterranean, and forged through Palestine up

05:17:57.760 --> 05:18:05.760
to the border of Egypt. They finally tracked down&nbsp;
the Syrian sultan An-Nasir Yusuf at the port town of

05:18:05.760 --> 05:18:15.639
Gaza, and later had him killed. Now, on the border of&nbsp;
Egypt, Hulagu sent ambassadors to the sultan there,

05:18:15.639 --> 05:18:24.920
a man named Qutuz, demanding that he swear loyalty to&nbsp;
the Mongol Empire. The Egyptian sultan responded by

05:18:24.920 --> 05:18:33.320
having the men beheaded and displaying their&nbsp;
heads on Cairo's Bab Zuweila gate. It was an act

05:18:33.320 --> 05:18:40.359
virtually guaranteed to lead to a Mongol invasion,&nbsp;
and soon, perhaps the land of the pyramids might

05:18:40.359 --> 05:18:49.080
have also been added to the vast stretch of the&nbsp;
Mongol Empire. But that was not to be the case.

05:18:49.080 --> 05:18:56.680
That's because news soon came down the Silk Road&nbsp;
of another seismic shock that would send tremors

05:18:56.680 --> 05:19:08.719
throughout the Mongol world; that was the death&nbsp;
on the 11th of August 1259, of the Great Khan Mongke.

05:19:20.400 --> 05:19:28.519
For years now, the Khan Mongke had been concerned&nbsp;
with how poorly the war in China was going.

05:19:28.520 --> 05:19:35.000
News of his brother Hulagu's glorious victories&nbsp;
in Persia and Mesopotamia trickled back to him

05:19:35.000 --> 05:19:43.400
in Mongolia; the destruction of the assassins,&nbsp;
the seizing of Alamut, the sack of Baghdad. But

05:19:43.400 --> 05:19:52.638
meanwhile, the news from China was one of slow,&nbsp;
grinding progress. The Khan’s other brother, Kublai,

05:19:52.639 --> 05:19:58.600
who had been left in charge of the final&nbsp;
conquest of Song China, could give him only

05:19:58.600 --> 05:20:08.760
excuses. The Song Chinese had by now spent&nbsp;
decades hardening their border on the

05:20:08.760 --> 05:20:15.920
Yangtse River against the Mongol invasion that&nbsp;
they knew would come, and their fortifications

05:20:15.920 --> 05:20:24.199
were formidable. Kublai was not a seasoned&nbsp;
warrior like his other brothers. He had a

05:20:24.199 --> 05:20:30.840
much better head for administration and finance.&nbsp;
In fact, he had spent much of his life feasting

05:20:30.840 --> 05:20:38.359
in a luxurious estate in Northern China, a kind&nbsp;
of quasi capital that would be called Shangdu,

05:20:38.359 --> 05:20:46.080
and has been rendered into English as Xanadu.&nbsp;
Eventually, the Khan Mongke announced that he would

05:20:46.080 --> 05:20:54.600
leave Mongolia and travel to China to take&nbsp;
charge of the war himself. In the steppe capital

05:20:54.600 --> 05:21:04.039
of Karakorum, he left his youngest brother in&nbsp;
charge, a man named Ariq Boke. Mongke took charge

05:21:04.039 --> 05:21:11.879
of an army and marched south. His final documented&nbsp;
presence was during the siege of Diaoyu Castle,

05:21:11.879 --> 05:21:19.799
near present-day Chongqing in southwestern China.&nbsp;
Later Chinese sources claim that he was killed

05:21:19.799 --> 05:21:26.359
during an assault on the fortress, either by a&nbsp;
crossbow bolt or a flying stone from a cannon

05:21:26.359 --> 05:21:34.240
or catapult, but more reliable sources such as&nbsp;
Rashid-ad-din record that he simply died of a

05:21:34.240 --> 05:21:44.199
disease. Due to the climate there, an&nbsp;
epidemic of dysentery broke out. Cholera

05:21:44.199 --> 05:21:49.840
spread among the Mongol soldiers, and&nbsp;
many of them died. The monarch of the

05:21:49.840 --> 05:21:56.799
world drank wine to ward off the cholera, and&nbsp;
he continued so to do. Suddenly, he developed

05:21:56.799 --> 05:22:03.000
an indisposition, and his illness came to a&nbsp;
crisis. He soon passed away at the foot of

05:22:03.000 --> 05:22:14.420
the unlucky fortress. He was 52 years old,&nbsp;
and this was the seventh year of his reign.

05:22:14.420 --> 05:22:24.240
However he died, the death of Mongke&nbsp;
in 1259 would mark a watershed in the

05:22:24.240 --> 05:22:31.439
history of the Mongols. This was the&nbsp;
maximum extent of their territory, and

05:22:31.439 --> 05:22:38.558
the last time that the entire Mongol&nbsp;
Empire would ever fight as one force.

05:22:38.559 --> 05:22:44.400
After the deaths of previous Khans, members of&nbsp;
the royal family had mostly rushed back to

05:22:44.400 --> 05:22:52.279
Mongolia to help elect a new overlord in a&nbsp;
grand kuriltai, but this time, none of them

05:22:52.279 --> 05:23:01.000
moved. They decided to stay where they were and&nbsp;
claim their own territory. Now the vast swathe of

05:23:01.000 --> 05:23:08.439
Asia that the Mongols had conquered fractured&nbsp;
into what were essentially four distinct empires.

05:23:13.879 --> 05:23:19.480
Firstly in Persia and the Middle East,&nbsp;
Mongke's brother Hulagu declared himself

05:23:19.480 --> 05:23:25.279
the ruler or Ilkhan of the territory he&nbsp;
had spent years conquering, which now

05:23:25.279 --> 05:23:31.638
stretched from Afghanistan to Turkey.&nbsp;
It would become known as the Ilkhanate.

05:23:31.639 --> 05:23:44.639
Second was in the northwest, in the&nbsp;
steppe bordering Europe in Ukraine and Russia, and

05:23:44.639 --> 05:23:52.320
stretching across the Volga region to the Ural&nbsp;
and Caucasus mountains. These lands were held by

05:23:52.320 --> 05:24:00.840
Khans descended from Chinggis Khan's oldest son Jochi,&nbsp;
the guest, who had fought all his life to prove

05:24:00.840 --> 05:24:08.439
himself to his father. They would call themselves&nbsp;
the Ulus of Jochi, but later historians would give

05:24:08.439 --> 05:24:16.558
them the name the Golden Horde. Their rulers would&nbsp;
be among the first of the Mongols to convert to

05:24:16.559 --> 05:24:29.000
Islam. Third was in the center of the empire, in the&nbsp;
conquered Silk Road regions that had once been the

05:24:29.000 --> 05:24:38.719
Khwarazmian Empire and the vast steppe of Kazakhstan and&nbsp;
Siberia. Here, the descendants of Chaghatai ruled

05:24:38.719 --> 05:24:43.559
what became known as the Chaghatai&nbsp;
Kharnate, presiding over the cities

05:24:43.559 --> 05:24:48.439
of Samarqand and Bukhara, which had by&nbsp;
now recovered somewhat from the

05:24:48.439 --> 05:24:57.519
destruction of Chinggis Khan, and once more&nbsp;
brought healthy income to their rulers.

05:24:57.520 --> 05:25:08.080
But it was in the east that the heir&nbsp;
to the throne of the Great Khan rose. He was

05:25:08.080 --> 05:25:16.752
the second son of Tolui and the late Mongke Khan's&nbsp;
brother, the somewhat unlikely new emperor, Kublai.

05:25:16.752 --> 05:25:39.639
Kublai was born on September&nbsp;
the 23rd 1215, the same year that Chinggis Khan

05:25:39.639 --> 05:25:49.639
had sacked Beijing, and for his entire life, the&nbsp;
Mongol Empire had been at war in China. As an

05:25:49.639 --> 05:25:57.199
adult, he had been awarded a Chinese estate with&nbsp;
10,000 households, and since then had divided his

05:25:57.199 --> 05:26:04.638
time between China and the Mongolian steppe.&nbsp;
Kublai had a liking for the trappings of

05:26:04.639 --> 05:26:13.680
settled society, the silks and the finery. He was&nbsp;
advised by Chinese advisers, and even a Buddhist

05:26:13.680 --> 05:26:20.400
monk who converted him to Tibetan Buddhism and&nbsp;
taught him to speak Chinese in a rudimentary

05:26:20.400 --> 05:26:29.759
way. Already, the people back in Mongolia may have&nbsp;
begun to whisper that Kublai was more Chinese than

05:26:29.760 --> 05:26:38.439
Mongolian. When his brother Mongke came to the&nbsp;
throne as Great Khan, Kublai was made viceroy

05:26:38.439 --> 05:26:46.679
over part of Northern China, and set about building&nbsp;
an opulent palace at Shangdu, and he was made one

05:26:46.680 --> 05:26:54.039
of the commanders of the final assault on the&nbsp;
last bastion of Chinese culture, the southern Song

05:26:54.039 --> 05:27:06.799
Dynasty. But much to the frustration of his&nbsp;
older brother Mongke Khan, the conquest of

05:27:06.799 --> 05:27:13.359
the Song was a long and difficult campaign.&nbsp;
In the Song, the Mongols faced without doubt

05:27:13.359 --> 05:27:19.240
the most technologically advanced army&nbsp;
on Earth. The Song pelted Mongol armies

05:27:19.240 --> 05:27:25.199
with repeating crossbows, launched huge&nbsp;
gunpowder bombs from their catapults, and

05:27:25.199 --> 05:27:30.320
even filled their explosives with pieces&nbsp;
of broken pottery to create perhaps the

05:27:30.320 --> 05:27:38.320
first shrapnel bombs in history. Rashid&nbsp;
ad-Din paints a picture of this grinding

05:27:38.320 --> 05:27:46.279
campaign. The roads were difficult and&nbsp;
the places and castles hard to capture.

05:27:46.279 --> 05:27:51.080
They had repeatedly given battle, and&nbsp;
entry and exit had been made difficult

05:27:51.080 --> 05:27:58.000
for them. Moreover, on account of the unhealthy&nbsp;
climate, many of that army had fallen sick and

05:27:58.000 --> 05:28:09.680
died. Still, the momentum of Mongol advance was by&nbsp;
this point unstoppable. Despite heavy losses,

05:28:09.680 --> 05:28:17.400
they pushed steadily into the heartlands of&nbsp;
the Song. That was until Kublai heard news that

05:28:17.400 --> 05:28:25.519
his brother Mongke had died, and the throne of&nbsp;
the Great Khan was up for grabs. Kublai had

05:28:25.520 --> 05:28:33.160
long dreamed of taking that throne for himself,&nbsp;
and as Mongke's brother, he was a prime candidate.

05:28:33.160 --> 05:28:40.320
But he was at a distinct disadvantage. Having&nbsp;
spent so many years in China, he had become

05:28:40.320 --> 05:28:47.480
distant from the life of the imperial court.&nbsp;
Meanwhile, his main rival was the man that

05:28:47.480 --> 05:28:56.080
Mongke had left in charge back in Karakorum, their&nbsp;
youngest brother, the fourth son of Tolui, Ariq Boke.

05:28:56.080 --> 05:29:07.320
While his brothers Hulagu and Kublai were&nbsp;
away fighting in distant corners of the empire,

05:29:07.320 --> 05:29:16.199
Ariq Boke had been back in the capital living the&nbsp;
life of a true steppe Mongol; hunting and riding, and

05:29:16.199 --> 05:29:24.199
supervising the administration of Mongke Khan's&nbsp;
empire, and he had been making friends. He was

05:29:24.199 --> 05:29:29.920
a skilled politician, and over his years&nbsp;
in Karakorum had come to gain the support

05:29:29.920 --> 05:29:37.559
of the majority of Mongol nobility, including&nbsp;
most of Mongke Khan's own family. It's possible

05:29:37.559 --> 05:29:43.119
that people may have hoped that under&nbsp;
his rule, the empire would remain an empire of

05:29:43.119 --> 05:29:49.959
the steppe for all the people of the felt walls,&nbsp;
and would not, like Kublai, be seduced by the

05:29:49.959 --> 05:29:59.480
ways of the settled societies it had conquered.&nbsp;
When the Great Khan Mongke died, Ariq Boke knew

05:29:59.480 --> 05:30:07.959
that his time was short. The chronicler Rashid&nbsp;
ad-Din recalls how he plotted to seize the throne.

05:30:09.160 --> 05:30:14.680
No sooner had Ariq Boke heard the news&nbsp;
of his brother's death than his eyes fell

05:30:14.680 --> 05:30:24.160
upon the imperial throne, and his courtiers and&nbsp;
retainers also urged him to seize it. But it's

05:30:24.160 --> 05:30:31.039
worth remembering that Rashid ad-Din was writing&nbsp;
on behalf of the Mongol court in Persia, who

05:30:31.039 --> 05:30:38.119
were Kublai's allies, and in fact, all evidence&nbsp;
points to the fact that Ariq Boke was Mongke's

05:30:38.119 --> 05:30:44.519
preferred successor, and that it was Kublai and&nbsp;
not him who was attempting to seize the throne

05:30:44.520 --> 05:30:54.080
in a coup. To Ariq Boke's anger, he soon got news&nbsp;
that Kublai, still in China, had held a kuriltai of

05:30:54.080 --> 05:31:02.320
his own in 1260 in his summer palace at Shangdu, and&nbsp;
announced his counter-claim to the throne of the

05:31:02.320 --> 05:31:12.718
Great Khan. This action was by all Mongol standards&nbsp;
illegal. It was not held in Mongolia, as was proper.

05:31:12.719 --> 05:31:18.799
None of the royal family was in attendance, and to&nbsp;
make matters worse, it was done with some of the

05:31:18.799 --> 05:31:29.080
trappings of Chinese ceremony. In virtually every&nbsp;
way, it was an affront. Blindsided, Ariq Boke rushed

05:31:29.080 --> 05:31:37.840
to announce a kuriltai in Mongolia, and at that&nbsp;
gathering, he declared himself the new Great Khan.

05:31:40.799 --> 05:31:50.199
In response, Kublai gathered his armies and marched&nbsp;
north. The Mongol Empire was now at war with

05:31:50.199 --> 05:32:10.320
itself. In the west, Hulagu's Ilkhanate backed&nbsp;
his brother Kublai's claim, and went to war with the

05:32:10.320 --> 05:32:18.320
Golden Horde and the Chaghatai Kharnate, who backed&nbsp;
Ariq Boke, and meanwhile, Kublai gathered all

05:32:18.320 --> 05:32:25.039
his forces and marched into Mongolia. With&nbsp;
him, he brought all the might of northern

05:32:25.039 --> 05:32:33.519
China. Unfortunately for Ariq Boke, his&nbsp;
skill as a politician did not translate

05:32:33.520 --> 05:32:40.799
into strategic thinking. Although he sat at the&nbsp;
political heart of the empire, his military

05:32:40.799 --> 05:32:48.000
position was vulnerable. Karakorum had no&nbsp;
natural defenses other than the Mongolian

05:32:48.000 --> 05:32:52.840
steppe around it, and no one who built it&nbsp;
ever imagined it having to withstand a

05:32:52.840 --> 05:32:59.799
siege. The city had little agriculture of its&nbsp;own,
and for the last thirty years had needed to be

05:32:59.799 --> 05:33:07.760
supplied with food and other necessities along&nbsp;
sprawling supply routes, as Rashid ad-Din recounts.

05:33:10.240 --> 05:33:16.558
It was customary for food and drink to be&nbsp;
brought to Karakorum from China by cart.

05:33:16.559 --> 05:33:25.279
Kublai cut off the supply, and this resulted in&nbsp;
shortages and severe inflation. Ariq Boke was

05:33:25.279 --> 05:33:41.279
helpless. Ariq Boke recognized the precarity&nbsp;
of his position, and at his brother's advance

05:33:41.279 --> 05:33:51.240
in 1261, he fled the capital for the northern&nbsp;
steppe. Kublai swept into Karakorum and looted

05:33:51.240 --> 05:33:58.080
the city that his uncle Ogedei had built,&nbsp;
as though it were any other conquest. He

05:33:58.080 --> 05:34:05.799
stripped it of much of its wealth and sent&nbsp;
this back to his palace at Shangdu in China.

05:34:05.799 --> 05:34:12.400
It's likely that the silver tree of Karakorum,&nbsp;
built by the French silversmith William Boucher,

05:34:12.400 --> 05:34:20.400
was also seized and possibly melted down&nbsp;
for transport. Treasure carts rolled back

05:34:20.400 --> 05:34:28.920
over the Gobi Desert, laden with precious things,&nbsp;
now heading in the opposite direction. Only fifty

05:34:28.920 --> 05:34:37.639
years after Chinggis Khan's conquest of the&nbsp;
Jin Dynasty, China's wealth was coming home.

05:34:41.799 --> 05:34:48.879
Ariq Boke spent the next few years being chased&nbsp;
from place to place, trying to gather support on

05:34:48.879 --> 05:34:54.920
the steppe, but his weakness in the face of his&nbsp;
brother's advance had destroyed any respect

05:34:54.920 --> 05:35:02.000
that anyone held for him. At times, it seemed&nbsp;
like even the weather had turned against him,

05:35:02.000 --> 05:35:12.920
as Rashid ad-Din records. One day, Ariq Boke was&nbsp;
busy reveling and carousing, when suddenly a fierce

05:35:12.920 --> 05:35:18.559
wind came and tore out the stakes and broke&nbsp;
the poles of his court tent, resulting in the

05:35:18.559 --> 05:35:24.520
injury of several people. The court ministers&nbsp;
and commanders took this as an omen of his

05:35:24.520 --> 05:35:32.240
demise, and totally abandoned him. Ariq Boke was&nbsp;
left there with only a few soldiers, and he was

05:35:32.240 --> 05:35:46.519
dumbfounded. The outcome was soon clear. In 1264,&nbsp;
four years into the civil war, Ariq Boke traveled to

05:35:46.520 --> 05:35:54.199
Kublai's palace at Shangdu to formally surrender&nbsp;
in tears to his brother. Kublai is recorded to

05:35:54.199 --> 05:36:03.160
have also wept as he received his surrender. Ariq&nbsp;
Boke was imprisoned, and died a year later while

05:36:03.160 --> 05:36:12.279
still in captivity, possibly from poison. Kublai&nbsp;
now ascended the throne, and was confirmed as

05:36:12.279 --> 05:36:21.759
Great Khan in another grand kuriltai, but there&nbsp;
were some notable absences at this event. None

05:36:21.760 --> 05:36:29.439
of the Khans of the other sides of the empire&nbsp;
attended. Now the Mongol Empire was officially

05:36:29.439 --> 05:36:37.878
divided, and turned its strength not against its&nbsp;
enemies, but against itself. The late 13th-century

05:36:37.879 --> 05:36:47.400
Syrian historian, Ibn Wasil, recounts the&nbsp;
solemn words of one Mongol general. Mongols

05:36:47.400 --> 05:36:55.199
are now killed by Mongol swords. If we were&nbsp;
united, then we would have conquered all of the

05:36:55.199 --> 05:37:05.400
world. If Chinggis Khan had been alive,&nbsp;
doubtless he would have reminded his

05:37:05.400 --> 05:37:11.679
grandsons of the story his mother Oelun&nbsp;
had told him, of Alan the fair and her

05:37:11.680 --> 05:37:18.320
sons, and the arrows that united could&nbsp;
not be broken. But divided, each would

05:37:18.320 --> 05:37:37.439
snap one by one. In the coming decades and&nbsp;
centuries, this is exactly what would happen.

05:37:44.920 --> 05:37:53.400
Despite ruling over a now much-reduced empire,&nbsp;
Kublai Khan still commanded a vast territory. At

05:37:53.400 --> 05:38:00.759
as much as 14 million square km, it was 50%&nbsp;
larger than modern China, encompassing the

05:38:00.760 --> 05:38:07.840
fertile central plains and a large stretch&nbsp;
of the steppe of Mongolia and Eastern Russia,

05:38:07.840 --> 05:38:13.520
and he was determined to build a power base&nbsp;
there that would last, and that would perhaps

05:38:13.520 --> 05:38:21.959
allow him to reconquer the other quadrants of his&nbsp;
grandfather's domain. But to do that, he would have

05:38:21.959 --> 05:38:30.480
to adopt the trappings of power that his Chinese&nbsp;
subjects understood, according to their traditions.

05:38:30.480 --> 05:38:39.080
To this end, in 1271, Kublai Khan formerly claimed the&nbsp;
Mandate of Heaven and crowned himself emperor of

05:38:39.080 --> 05:38:49.080
China. The following year of 1272 would be the&nbsp;
first year of a new dynasty, which he would call

05:38:49.080 --> 05:38:58.359
the Great Yuan, a word which means either beginning&nbsp;
or center. In accordance with Chinese tradition, his

05:38:58.359 --> 05:39:04.798
courtiers begged him to take the title of&nbsp;
emperor, and he modestly refused twice, only

05:39:04.799 --> 05:39:13.760
accepting the third time they asked. A Chinese&nbsp;
emperor needed an imperial capital, and Kublai

05:39:13.760 --> 05:39:21.439
decided to move his from the site of Shangdu, and&nbsp;
build a new one near the ruined city of Beijing

05:39:21.439 --> 05:39:29.599
that his grandfather had destroyed. There,&nbsp;
he would build the new city of Dadu, meaning great

05:39:29.600 --> 05:39:37.600
capital, but his Mongolian and Turkic subjects&nbsp;
would often refer to it as Khanbaliq, which in

05:39:37.600 --> 05:39:49.119
Mongolian means ‘the city of the Khan’. Rashid ad-Din&nbsp;
recalls his decision. He designated as his winter

05:39:49.119 --> 05:39:56.400
residence the city of Khanbaliq, which had been an&nbsp;
imperial capital. It had been chosen as a site

05:39:56.400 --> 05:40:03.080
in ancient times by astrologers and philosophers,&nbsp;
and it was considered to be very auspicious and

05:40:03.080 --> 05:40:12.119
lucky. Since Genghis Khan had destroyed it, Kublai&nbsp;
Khan wanted to rebuild it, so for his own fame and

05:40:12.119 --> 05:40:18.959
reputation, he built another city next to it.&nbsp;
Inside the city he built a truly magnificent

05:40:18.959 --> 05:40:29.680
palace for his ordu. Its pillars and paving are all&nbsp;
of marble. It was to this capital of Khanbaliq that

05:40:29.680 --> 05:40:37.241
a weary traveler arrived from the other side of&nbsp;
the world, probably sometime around the year 1271.

05:40:38.479 --> 05:40:45.279
He had left his home at the age of sixteen or&nbsp;
seventeen, and set out on a journey of exploration

05:40:45.279 --> 05:40:50.240
with his brother that had taken him&nbsp;
across Central Asia and through many

05:40:50.240 --> 05:41:07.240
of the lands that now belonged to the&nbsp;
Mongol Khanates. His name was Marco Polo.

05:41:09.000 --> 05:41:16.039
It was likely the unification of much&nbsp;
of Asia under the Mongols that allowed Polo to

05:41:16.039 --> 05:41:23.439
conduct his journey, since the strict enforcement&nbsp;
of the Mongol yassa law code had kept banditry and

05:41:23.439 --> 05:41:31.439
robbery to a minimum. This was the period that&nbsp;
has been called the Pax Mongolica, or the Mongol

05:41:31.439 --> 05:41:37.359
Peace, when it was said with some exaggeration&nbsp;
that even a maiden carrying a nugget of

05:41:37.359 --> 05:41:45.160
gold on her head could wander safely across the&nbsp;
realm without being robbed. When Polo arrived in

05:41:45.160 --> 05:41:51.080
Khanbaliq, he was given an audience with the&nbsp;
Great Khan, which he describes in his later work.

05:41:51.080 --> 05:41:58.080
I shall tell you of the great&nbsp;
and wonderful magnificence of the

05:41:58.080 --> 05:42:07.359
Great Khan now reigning, by name Kublai Khan. He&nbsp;
is the most powerful man as regards forces

05:42:07.359 --> 05:42:13.558
and lands and treasure, that exists in the&nbsp;
world or ever have existed from the time

05:42:13.559 --> 05:42:20.760
of our First Father Adam until this day.&nbsp;
He is of a good stature, neither tall nor

05:42:20.760 --> 05:42:27.639
short, but of a middle height. He has a becoming&nbsp;
amount of flesh, and is very shapely in all his

05:42:27.639 --> 05:42:37.119
limbs. His complexion is white and red, the&nbsp;
eyes black and fine, the nose well-formed.

05:42:38.760 --> 05:42:47.760
He also describes the opulence of the Khan's&nbsp;
palace. The Hall of the Palace is so large that

05:42:47.760 --> 05:42:56.400
it could easily dine 6,000 people, and it is quite&nbsp;
a marvel to see how many rooms there are besides.

05:42:56.400 --> 05:43:03.119
The outside of the roof also is all colored&nbsp;
with vermilion and yellow and green and blue

05:43:03.119 --> 05:43:10.519
and other hues, which are fixed with a varnish so&nbsp;
fine and exquisite that they shine like crystal,

05:43:10.520 --> 05:43:21.080
and lend a resplendent luster to the palace, as&nbsp;
seen for a great way round. Marco Polo

05:43:21.080 --> 05:43:27.680
was also astonished to see the Chinese invention&nbsp;
of paper money being circulated by the Imperial

05:43:27.680 --> 05:43:37.279
mint, a concept that he struggled to understand. He&nbsp;
makes them take of the bark of the mulberry tree,

05:43:37.279 --> 05:43:43.320
and this they make into something resembling&nbsp;
sheets of paper. When these sheets have been

05:43:43.320 --> 05:43:48.558
prepared, they are cut up into pieces of&nbsp;
different sizes. The smallest of these

05:43:48.559 --> 05:43:57.199
is worth a half silver coin; the next, a little&nbsp;
larger, a whole silver coin; one, a little larger

05:43:57.199 --> 05:44:04.119
still, is worth half a silver groat of Venice. All&nbsp;
these pieces of paper are issued with as much

05:44:04.119 --> 05:44:11.760
solemnity and authority as if they were of pure&nbsp;
gold or silver, and on every piece a variety

05:44:11.760 --> 05:44:19.760
of officials whose duty it is, have to write their&nbsp;
names and put their seals. Anyone forging it would

05:44:19.760 --> 05:44:25.799
be punished with death, and the Khan causes&nbsp;
every year to be made such a vast quantity

05:44:25.799 --> 05:44:31.799
of this money, which costs him nothing, that it&nbsp;
must equal in amount all the treasures in the

05:44:31.799 --> 05:44:42.719
world. According to Marco Polo, Kublai Khan was&nbsp;
so impressed with his adventurous spirit

05:44:42.719 --> 05:44:49.199
and command of four different languages, that&nbsp;
he appointed him an ambassador. Over the next

05:44:49.199 --> 05:44:55.558
seventeen years, Polo claims to have conducted a&nbsp;
large number of ambassadorial journeys for

05:44:55.559 --> 05:45:01.400
Kublai, visiting the far south of China,&nbsp;
Burma, and other lands around southeast

05:45:01.400 --> 05:45:06.920
Asia, before finally being allowed&nbsp;
to return home through Mesopotamia.

05:45:09.760 --> 05:45:16.400
Back home, the Venetian Marco Polo was taken&nbsp;
as a prisoner of war by the rival Genoise,

05:45:16.400 --> 05:45:23.519
and imprisoned for a year in Genoa. During his&nbsp;
imprisonment, Polo shared a cell with a writer

05:45:23.520 --> 05:45:31.600
named Rustichello da Pisa. Throughout their time
imprisoned together, Polo recounted his extensive travels

05:45:31.600 --> 05:45:38.719
through Asia to Rustichello, who transcribed them into&nbsp;
a work that they called The Description of the

05:45:38.719 --> 05:45:47.199
World, but it would become known as The Travels of&nbsp;
Marco Polo, one of the most famous and influential

05:45:47.199 --> 05:45:56.439
travel books in history. Polo's work, published&nbsp;
in a dialect of Italian, caused a sensation back

05:45:56.439 --> 05:46:02.878
home, and after being translated into Latin, it&nbsp;
was published around all of Europe continuously

05:46:02.879 --> 05:46:12.160
for the next centuries. But one detail from Marco&nbsp;
Polo's journey does stand out. When he finally got

05:46:12.160 --> 05:46:20.840
permission to leave China and return home in 1292,&nbsp;
nearly twenty years after leaving home, he returned not

05:46:20.840 --> 05:46:28.879
over land, but by boat. That's because the Pax&nbsp;
Mongolica, the Mongol Peace that had brought

05:46:28.879 --> 05:46:36.840
stability to Asia and allowed his journey in the&nbsp;
first place, was already beginning to fracture.

05:46:48.000 --> 05:46:55.320
Despite the glowing impression that the empire&nbsp;
left on Marco Polo, China under Kublai Khan's Yuan

05:46:55.320 --> 05:47:02.359
Dynasty was a troubled place. For one thing, it was&nbsp;
still at war with the remnants of the southern

05:47:02.359 --> 05:47:11.959
Song, who held out in several strongholds for many&nbsp;
years. But by the 19th of March 1279, the Mongols

05:47:11.959 --> 05:47:20.080
had cornered the last child emperor of the Song
in a coastal fortress called Yamen, at the mouth

05:47:20.080 --> 05:47:27.840
of the Pearl River. The boy was only six or seven&nbsp;
years of age, but he was the final hope for the

05:47:27.840 --> 05:47:36.039
continuation of the Song line. When Mongol forces&nbsp;
finally closed in and it became clear that all

05:47:36.039 --> 05:47:42.719
was lost, one of the young emperor's attendants&nbsp;
took the boy in his arms and gave the following

05:47:42.719 --> 05:47:51.080
cry. The affairs of the nation lie&nbsp;
in ruin, and our country is destroyed.

05:47:51.080 --> 05:47:55.799
There is no hope now. His Majesty has&nbsp;
no alternative but to die for the country.

05:47:55.799 --> 05:48:06.799
With the boy in his arms, he leapt from the&nbsp;
cliffs into the ocean. It’s said that hundreds of the

05:48:06.799 --> 05:48:13.680
royal family and attendants followed the young&nbsp;
emperor to his watery grave rather than face the

05:48:13.680 --> 05:48:26.080
Mongols. The sorrow of the collapse of&nbsp;
the Song Dynasty would haunt the Chinese

05:48:26.080 --> 05:48:34.400
people for generations. The poet Hsieh Ao&nbsp;
captured the sense of melancholy when

05:48:34.400 --> 05:48:41.759
he visited the ruins of the former Imperial&nbsp;
Palace at Hangchow, and memorialized it in a

05:48:49.080 --> 05:49:01.439
poem. Like an ancient ruin, the grass&nbsp;
grows high. Gone are the guards and

05:49:01.439 --> 05:49:06.959
the gatekeepers. Fallen towers&nbsp;
and crumbling palaces desolate

05:49:06.959 --> 05:49:15.559
my soul. Under the eaves of the long-ago&nbsp;
hall fly in and out the swallows, but within,

05:49:15.559 --> 05:49:30.080
silence. The destruction of the Song was&nbsp;
something that many of the Chinese citizens

05:49:30.080 --> 05:49:36.639
of the Yuan Dynasty would never forget, and&nbsp;
for some, it was a wound that they would never

05:49:36.639 --> 05:49:51.199
forgive. With the south of China finally&nbsp;
crushed, Kublai Khan was the first foreign invader

05:49:51.199 --> 05:49:58.519
to ever conquer the whole of the central plains&nbsp;
of China. This was also the first time that the

05:49:58.520 --> 05:50:06.760
land had been united since the Tang Dynasty 400&nbsp;
years earlier. But Kublai had won an empire

05:50:06.760 --> 05:50:14.160
now devastated by decades of war. The north&nbsp;
of China had been suffering from famine ever

05:50:14.160 --> 05:50:20.558
since it was first occupied by the Mongols. Its&nbsp;
agriculture had always been weaker than the south,

05:50:20.559 --> 05:50:25.840
where the humid weather meant that rice could&nbsp;
be grown, but in the north the major crops were

05:50:25.840 --> 05:50:33.680
wheat, sorghum, and millet. Since the destruction&nbsp;
of Chinggis Khan's initial invasion, the northern

05:50:33.680 --> 05:50:41.879
economy had recovered somewhat, but famine was&nbsp;
an ever-present threat. To remedy this, Kublai Khan

05:50:41.879 --> 05:50:47.840
ordered the lengthening of the so-called Grand&nbsp;
Canal so that it now connected his new capital

05:50:47.840 --> 05:50:55.760
of Khanbaliq with the old Song capital of Hangzhou,&nbsp;
a symbol of national reunification that also allowed

05:50:55.760 --> 05:51:04.959
the transport of rice from the south to the famine-&nbsp;
struck north. This measure improved matters, and

05:51:04.959 --> 05:51:12.119
for a time, a level of stability came to the&nbsp;
once divided land. But already, the Mongols were

05:51:12.119 --> 05:51:19.080
finding that conquering a vast and complex kingdom&nbsp;
like China was much easier than actually ruling it.

05:51:24.100 --> 05:51:36.520
The new hybrid empire of Mongolian China&nbsp;
was also going through a crisis of identity.

05:51:37.199 --> 05:51:45.160
Kublai's government was a tiny Mongol minority ruling&nbsp;
over a vast population of tens of millions of Han

05:51:45.160 --> 05:51:52.680
Chinese, and they were steadily losing their&nbsp;
military advantage. Most of his soldiers were

05:51:52.680 --> 05:52:00.760
now no longer Mongolian horsemen, but Chinese&nbsp;
footsoldiers. The old capital of Karakorum, far

05:52:00.760 --> 05:52:06.959
out in the steppe, had become an irrelevance,&nbsp;
its palaces stripped of their treasures,

05:52:06.959 --> 05:52:13.799
and what wealth it once had taken back&nbsp;
to China. People back in Mongolia must

05:52:13.799 --> 05:52:17.559
have begun to wonder who it&nbsp;
was that had actually been

05:52:17.559 --> 05:52:27.279
conquered. To ensure that the empire maintained its&nbsp;
Mongol identity, Kublai was keen to keep all the

05:52:27.279 --> 05:52:35.959
higher echelons of power reserved for Mongols. To&nbsp;
this end, southern Chinese people of the former Song

05:52:35.959 --> 05:52:43.359
were relegated to fourth-class citizens in their&nbsp;
own country, with the northern Chinese above them,

05:52:43.359 --> 05:52:51.839
the central Asians and Tanguts above them both, and&nbsp;
of course Mongols as the empire's elite class. Han

05:52:51.840 --> 05:52:58.279
Chinese were forbidden from holding many of the&nbsp;
most powerful positions or holding key roles in

05:52:58.279 --> 05:53:05.080
the civil service. That meant that many of the&nbsp;
people who were most familiar with the land and

05:53:05.080 --> 05:53:12.439
the workings of its administration were kept away&nbsp;
from any positions where they might do some good.

05:53:12.439 --> 05:53:20.119
Increasingly, Kublai feared that he might lose a grip&nbsp;
on this slippery empire, and so, he decided to do

05:53:20.119 --> 05:53:37.359
what Mongols had always done when they wanted to&nbsp;
unite people around them; they went to war.

05:53:37.359 --> 05:53:43.599
First, he was determined to conquer the kingdom&nbsp;
of Dai Viet in the south, the northern kingdom of

05:53:43.600 --> 05:53:52.039
what is Vietnam today, but these plans would be&nbsp;
frustrated. Although he swept south in three major

05:53:52.039 --> 05:53:59.039
invasions and managed to capture the Vietnamese&nbsp;
capital of Thang Long, near modern Hanoi, the Mongol

05:53:59.039 --> 05:54:06.719
forces found the humid tropical weather and&nbsp;
thick jungle landscape impossible to contend with.

05:54:06.719 --> 05:54:13.160
The Vietnamese soldiers melted away into the&nbsp;
matted vegetation, and raided Mongol armies with

05:54:13.160 --> 05:54:23.359
hit-and-run tactics that slowly whittled away their&nbsp;
strength, as the history of Yuan describes. Although

05:54:23.359 --> 05:54:30.839
the Viet were defeated many times, they gathered&nbsp;
more and more troops. Without sufficient supplies,

05:54:30.840 --> 05:54:36.439
both our generals and troops suffered hardships&nbsp;
and many of them were killed. In that land,

05:54:36.439 --> 05:54:42.638
the troops and horses of the Mongols could&nbsp;
not manifest their talent, too. Eventually, they

05:54:42.639 --> 05:54:48.760
had to abandon the capital, crossing the river&nbsp;
toward the north side to discuss the plan of

05:54:48.760 --> 05:54:59.479
retreat. While they were never actually defeated&nbsp;
in battle, the Mongols eventually withdrew after

05:54:59.479 --> 05:55:06.321
taking heavy losses, leaving the kingdom of&nbsp;
Dai Viet still independent, if somewhat devastated.

05:55:08.199 --> 05:55:13.558
These tactics of guerrilla warfare were so&nbsp;
successful for the medieval Vietnamese that

05:55:13.559 --> 05:55:19.320
the generals who had masterminded them became&nbsp;
national heroes, and the books on strategy that

05:55:19.320 --> 05:55:26.879
they wrote would be read for centuries to come.&nbsp;
As a result, the same tactics would be used again

05:55:26.879 --> 05:55:34.000
in the 20th century, when they would inspire the&nbsp;
North Vietnamese army and the irregular forces

05:55:34.000 --> 05:55:40.240
of the Vietcong when they once again faced a&nbsp;
more powerful invader in the form of the United

05:55:40.240 --> 05:55:51.359
States. For his part, Kublai Khan was&nbsp;
angered by these failed invasions,

05:55:51.359 --> 05:55:55.718
and even had one of his own sons&nbsp;
named Toqan banished for his part

05:55:55.719 --> 05:56:02.719
in the disaster. With this embarrassment no&nbsp;
doubt stinging, Kublai planned an invasion of

05:56:02.719 --> 05:56:08.680
one of the last holdouts against Mongol&nbsp;
rule in the east, the island nation of

05:56:08.680 --> 05:56:22.559
Japan. The first Mongol attempt to capture&nbsp;
Japan had ended in failure, although they

05:56:22.559 --> 05:56:29.920
had briefly occupied the islands of Tsushima&nbsp;
and Iki. Although they had inherited a large

05:56:29.920 --> 05:56:36.959
navy from the Jin and Song, and the Koreans who&nbsp;
they had recently subjugated, the Mongols were

05:56:36.959 --> 05:56:45.359
not used to naval warfare, and struggled to seize&nbsp;
a credible hold on any land in Japan. This time, in

05:56:45.359 --> 05:56:53.478
the second invasion of 1280, Kublai sent a larger&nbsp;
force of perhaps 30,000 soldiers, and ordered the

05:56:53.479 --> 05:57:00.840
construction of a grand fleet that was probably&nbsp;
at that time the largest in the world. He was

05:57:00.840 --> 05:57:06.559
determined to seize a bridgehead from which&nbsp;
a larger force could spread out over the whole

05:57:06.559 --> 05:57:13.320
of Japan. The armada of as many as&nbsp;
4,000 ships sailed from the port of

05:57:13.320 --> 05:57:19.718
Masan in Korea, and from China, leaving&nbsp;
from Ningbo at the mouth of the Yangtse

05:57:19.719 --> 05:57:30.799
River. They chose the landing site of&nbsp;
Hakata Bay, near the modern city of Fukuoka,

05:57:30.799 --> 05:57:40.039
which sits on the large Japanese island of Kyushu,&nbsp;
just 200 km off the coast of Korea. But Japanese

05:57:40.039 --> 05:57:45.879
resistance would be fierce. They had learned&nbsp;
the lessons of the first invasion, and spent

05:57:45.879 --> 05:57:54.320
the intervening years preparing, even building&nbsp;
a strong defensive wall surrounding Hakata Bay.

05:57:54.320 --> 05:57:58.840
When the Mongols landed, they brought&nbsp;
all the technological might of China with

05:57:58.840 --> 05:58:06.279
them. The Japanese source, the Hachiman Gudokun,&nbsp;
describes the challenge of dealing with these

05:58:06.279 --> 05:58:13.039
terrifying weapons, and notes with scorn the&nbsp;
Mongols’ lack of adherence to the traditional

05:58:13.039 --> 05:58:21.920
conventions of warfare. They sent iron bombshells&nbsp;
flying against us, which made our side dizzy and

05:58:21.920 --> 05:58:28.279
confused. Our soldiers were frightened out&nbsp;
of their wits by the thundering explosions.

05:58:28.279 --> 05:58:35.279
Their eyes were blinded, their ears deafened, so that&nbsp;
they could hardly distinguish east from west.

05:58:35.279 --> 05:58:40.879
According to our manner of fighting, we must first&nbsp;
call out by name someone from the enemy ranks, and

05:58:40.879 --> 05:58:47.160
then attack in single combat. But they took no&nbsp;
notice at all of such conventions. They rushed

05:58:47.160 --> 05:58:52.199
forward all together in a mass, grappling with&nbsp;
any individuals they could catch, and killing them.

05:58:52.199 --> 05:59:01.199
Many of the invading soldiers&nbsp;
were Chinese, not Mongol, and they had

05:59:01.199 --> 05:59:06.439
little stake in this conflict.&nbsp;
Many deserted or surrendered

05:59:06.439 --> 05:59:13.519
when the fighting got tough. The Mongols fought&nbsp;
for two months at Hakata Bay in a kind of bitter

05:59:13.520 --> 05:59:20.479
stalemate. They were unable to make any headway&nbsp;
against the Japanese defenses, while the Japanese,

05:59:20.479 --> 05:59:32.159
too, struggled to dislodge them entirely.&nbsp;
Then on the 15th of August, fate intervened.

05:59:32.159 --> 05:59:41.840
A powerful typhoon swept in from&nbsp;
the west, a common occurrence in late summer

05:59:41.840 --> 05:59:48.959
in Southeast Asia. The storm struck the Mongol&nbsp;
fleet anchored off the coast, causing severe

05:59:48.959 --> 05:59:58.760
destruction. The Venetian Marco Polo describes&nbsp;
the outcome. Now it happened one day that such

05:59:58.760 --> 06:00:05.359
a gale was blowing from the north that the troops&nbsp;
declared that if they did not get away, all their

06:00:05.359 --> 06:00:12.400
ships would be wrecked. So they all embarked and&nbsp;
left the island, and put out to sea. And let me

06:00:12.400 --> 06:00:19.160
tell you that when they had sailed about four miles,&nbsp;
the gale began to freshen, and there was such a

06:00:19.160 --> 06:00:27.639
crowd of ships that many of them were smashed by&nbsp;
colliding with one another. Thousands of soldiers

06:00:27.639 --> 06:00:35.080
were left clinging to debris or swept ashore by&nbsp;
the force of the storm. Japanese warriors walked

06:00:35.080 --> 06:00:41.600
up and down the beaches, killing all Mongols&nbsp;
they could find, only sparing the Chinese, who

06:00:41.600 --> 06:00:49.920
they believed had been forced into participating&nbsp;
in the invasion. To the Japanese, this typhoon was

06:00:49.920 --> 06:00:57.400
no accident. It was the kamikaze, or divine wind,&nbsp;
that had been sent by the gods to smash the

06:00:57.400 --> 06:01:07.279
Mongol invaders and protect the lands of Japan.&nbsp;
To Kublai Khan, this further crushing loss was

06:01:07.279 --> 06:01:17.759
a disaster from which his morale would never&nbsp;
fully recover. In Burma, too, the Mongols

06:01:17.760 --> 06:01:23.959
succeeded in toppling the empire of Bagan, but&nbsp;
the humid, tropical environment in the south of

06:01:23.959 --> 06:01:31.520
the country soon defeated them, along with its&nbsp;
host of tropical diseases. The Mongols had now

06:01:31.520 --> 06:01:38.240
found the geographic bounds of their expansion.&nbsp;
There was no more treasure left to plunder,

06:01:38.240 --> 06:01:46.199
no more lands left to seize. All that was left to&nbsp;
do was turn against one another and collapse from

06:01:46.199 --> 06:02:07.199
within. The Great Khan Kublai died on the 18th of&nbsp;
February 1294, and his death would begin the

06:02:07.199 --> 06:02:16.599
slow decline of Mongol power in Asia. In China,&nbsp;
nine further Khans followed the reign of Kublai,

06:02:16.600 --> 06:02:23.799
but their reigns were largely short, unstable,&nbsp;
and characterized by widespread incompetence,

06:02:23.799 --> 06:02:33.279
corruption, and famine. Kublai's successor, his&nbsp;
grandson Temur Oljeitu, died without an heir, and

06:02:33.279 --> 06:02:39.840
a period of struggle followed that led to&nbsp;
to growing resentment among China's people.

06:02:39.840 --> 06:02:46.160
Meanwhile, the Mongols who remained back in&nbsp;
the Mongolian steppe increasingly viewed these

06:02:46.160 --> 06:02:53.160
emperors as foreigners who had forgotten their&nbsp;
old way of life, and began to ignore the rule of

06:02:53.160 --> 06:03:00.959
the Great Khan in China. The last emperor of&nbsp;
the Yuan Dynasty ascended the throne in the

06:03:00.959 --> 06:03:11.000
year 1333. His name was Toghon Temur, and it's in&nbsp;
his hands that the Yuan Dynasty would truly

06:03:20.479 --> 06:03:36.080
disintegrate. Toghon Temur came to the&nbsp;
throne at the age of thirteen and ruled for 33

06:03:36.080 --> 06:03:42.680
years, but as a young boy emperor, he mostly&nbsp;
left the business of governing to his corrupt

06:03:42.680 --> 06:03:49.639
officials, and when he came of age, he saw&nbsp;
little reason to change that. During his

06:03:49.639 --> 06:03:57.279
reign, he presided over a China rife with&nbsp;
discord and instability. Banditry became

06:03:57.279 --> 06:04:06.160
rampant, with the weakened Yuan armies unable to&nbsp;
restore order. On top of this increasing discord,

06:04:06.160 --> 06:04:11.680
it was during these decades that the&nbsp;
Black Death arrived in earnest, and moved

06:04:11.680 --> 06:04:17.959
with shocking speed and lethality through the&nbsp;
population of China and the rest of the Mongol

06:04:17.959 --> 06:04:24.240
world. The very trade routes that&nbsp;
had made the Mongols rich over the

06:04:24.240 --> 06:04:29.080
last century now became conduits&nbsp;
through which the disease flowed

06:04:29.080 --> 06:04:35.799
unchecked. During the 14th century, it's&nbsp;
estimated that China would lose between

06:04:35.799 --> 06:04:45.160
a half and two-thirds of its population to this plague.
One later Chinese source describes the effect of this

06:04:45.160 --> 06:04:54.680
disease. In the autumn, there was a great&nbsp;
epidemic. The victim first developed a hard

06:04:54.680 --> 06:05:02.279
lump below the armpits or between the thighs,&nbsp;
or else coughed thin blood, and died before

06:05:02.279 --> 06:05:08.519
they had time to take medicine. There were&nbsp;
whole families wiped out, with none to bury them.

06:05:08.520 --> 06:05:20.240
From the late 1290s onward, the countryside&nbsp;
endured a truly baffling intensity of natural

06:05:20.240 --> 06:05:28.119
disasters, including droughts, floods of the Yellow&nbsp;
River, plagues of locusts, snow storms, torrential

06:05:28.119 --> 06:05:35.799
rains, typhoons, landslides, earthquakes, and&nbsp;
even the reported appearance of dragons

06:05:35.799 --> 06:05:43.080
over the skies of China. These extreme weather&nbsp;
events were partly driven by global weather

06:05:43.080 --> 06:05:49.719
conditions and the medieval climate shift&nbsp;
known as the Little Ice Age, but throughout

06:05:49.719 --> 06:05:56.879
this period of hardship, the Yuan government's&nbsp;
ineffective policies made everything worse, and

06:05:56.879 --> 06:06:05.559
before long, its people became convinced that&nbsp;
the Yuan Mongols had lost the Mandate of Heaven.

06:06:06.240 --> 06:06:13.039
The later Chinese source, The History of Ming&nbsp;
or Mingshi, describes the collapse of central

06:06:13.039 --> 06:06:21.840
order. At this time, the Yuan government was&nbsp;
no longer in control, and bandits rose up

06:06:21.840 --> 06:06:29.119
on all sides. They amassed armies of several&nbsp;
myriads each, and they all appointed generals

06:06:29.119 --> 06:06:35.639
and commanders who slaughtered the officials&nbsp;
and invaded the prefectures and districts.

06:06:35.639 --> 06:06:39.439
Still other bandits collected&nbsp;
their swarms of soldiers, and

06:06:39.439 --> 06:06:45.000
took possession of various places&nbsp;on
the sea coast. The world was in chaos.

06:06:45.000 --> 06:06:54.879
By 1351, popular hatred of&nbsp;
China's Mongol rulers erupted

06:06:54.879 --> 06:06:59.199
in a major peasant uprising that&nbsp;
would become known by the scarlet

06:06:59.199 --> 06:07:05.519
headgear that its fighters wore. It&nbsp;
was called the Red Turban Rebellions.

06:07:08.240 --> 06:07:13.599
The Red Turbans were a large coalition&nbsp;
of different groups, many motivated by

06:07:13.600 --> 06:07:18.719
a religious conviction that the end of&nbsp;
the world was coming, that the prophesied

06:07:18.719 --> 06:07:27.039
final Buddha, named Maitreya, would soon arrive&nbsp;
and bring an end to all suffering. These

06:07:27.039 --> 06:07:32.478
rebels met at night in clandestine&nbsp;
meetings, and recruited followers

06:07:32.479 --> 06:07:39.320
from among the workers conscripted to dig&nbsp;
the Grand Canal. It was soon a nationwide

06:07:39.320 --> 06:07:51.119
uprising. By 1351, the rebels had seized several&nbsp;
cities, and even the old Song capital of Kaifeng

06:07:51.119 --> 06:07:57.879
fell into the hands of one Red Turban group.&nbsp;
In the midst of all this chaos, the famine

06:07:57.879 --> 06:08:03.320
and plague passed through the village of&nbsp;
one young man living in the valley of the

06:08:03.320 --> 06:08:11.679
river Huai, right in the center of China. He was&nbsp;
barely more than a boy, born into the depths of

06:08:11.680 --> 06:08:21.000
the poverty-stricken peasantry. His name was&nbsp;
Zhu Yuanzhang. The History of Ming describes

06:08:21.000 --> 06:08:32.039
this tragedy. Drought, locusts, and pestilence&nbsp;
came. At that time, he was seventeen years of age.

06:08:32.039 --> 06:08:38.879
His father, mother, and eldest brother all died in&nbsp;
succession. The survivors were too poor to be

06:08:38.879 --> 06:08:45.760
able to provide a proper burial for the dead.&nbsp;He
was now alone, with no one on whom he could lean.

06:08:45.760 --> 06:08:55.479
This orphaned boy would join a Buddhist&nbsp;
monastery, but from there was swept up in the

06:08:55.479 --> 06:09:00.639
rising groundswell of rebellion, and&nbsp;
when he was old enough, he joined the

06:09:00.639 --> 06:09:05.479
Red Turban Rebellion. Eventually&nbsp;
he would rise through the ranks

06:09:05.479 --> 06:09:12.400
of this rebel insurgency, and then break away&nbsp;
to form his own army. To the astonishment of

06:09:12.400 --> 06:09:17.638
the Mongols, this peasant general even&nbsp;
captured the large and important city

06:09:17.639 --> 06:09:26.119
of Nanjing. After this victory, he announced&nbsp;
a war of national liberation in the following

06:09:26.119 --> 06:09:35.320
terms. It used to be said that the Yuan or&nbsp;
Mongols, who came from the regions of the north,

06:09:35.920 --> 06:09:43.240
conquered our empire, not so much by their&nbsp;
courage and skill as by the aid of Heaven,

06:09:43.240 --> 06:09:50.160
and now it is sufficiently plain that&nbsp;
heaven itself wishes to deprive them

06:09:50.160 --> 06:10:05.320
of that empire. The time has come to&nbsp;
drive these foreigners out of China.

06:10:09.119 --> 06:10:15.558
Such was the weakened state of the Yuan Dynasty&nbsp;
that much of Zhu Yuanzhang's energy was spent

06:10:15.559 --> 06:10:23.160
fighting not the Mongols, but other Chinese&nbsp;
rivals among the Red Turbans. But after years

06:10:23.160 --> 06:10:33.920
of war, he finally won supremacy over all other&nbsp;
rebel groups. On the 20th of January 1368, Zhu

06:10:33.920 --> 06:10:39.840
Yuanzhang formerly claimed the Mandate&nbsp;
of Heaven, and declared himself the emperor

06:10:39.840 --> 06:10:48.799
of China. He announced the beginning of a new&nbsp;
dynasty that he called the Ming, meaning bright

06:10:48.799 --> 06:10:56.199
or brilliant, and this orphaned peasant would go&nbsp;
down in history with the name of the Hongwu

06:10:56.199 --> 06:11:04.840
emperor. With his rule now secure, he&nbsp;
declared his intentions to march north

06:11:04.840 --> 06:11:10.559
and against the Mongol capital&nbsp;
of Khanbaliq, as the History of Ming recounts.

06:11:10.559 --> 06:11:19.479
On the 9th of November, the emperor&nbsp;
summoned his generals to discuss an expedition

06:11:19.479 --> 06:11:29.520
to the north. He said, “The Yuan reign will soon&nbsp;
be over, and North China is already in ruins.

06:11:29.520 --> 06:11:35.799
Now we shall strike northward and rescue the&nbsp;
living from flood and flame. Let us take our

06:11:35.799 --> 06:11:43.439
veterans of a 100 battles, pit them against their&nbsp;
long-untried soldiers, and strike directly at the

06:11:43.439 --> 06:11:50.519
Yuan capital. So great is our force that&nbsp;
this can be done as easily as splitting bamboo.”

06:11:50.520 --> 06:11:59.439
In August of 1368,&nbsp;
the Ming forces arrived in the

06:11:59.439 --> 06:12:05.320
region of Beijing, and at the sight of&nbsp;
the army, the Khan's capital of Khanbaliq

06:12:05.320 --> 06:12:13.160
surrendered without a fight. Beijing was now in&nbsp;
the hands of the Chinese, little more than 150

06:12:13.160 --> 06:12:22.639
years since Chinggis Khan had sacked it. The later&nbsp;
Mongol chronicle, the Altan Tobchi, attributes the

06:12:22.639 --> 06:12:35.119
following lament to the last Khan of China, Toghon&nbsp;
Temur, using the Chinese name Daidu for the capital.

06:12:36.920 --> 06:12:43.639
My Daidu, straight and wonderfully made of&nbsp;
various jewels, the summer residence

06:12:43.639 --> 06:12:52.479
of ancient Khans. My dear Daidu that I've lost&nbsp;
on the year of the bald red rabbit…nobles

06:12:52.479 --> 06:13:00.359
born foolish cared not for their state.&nbsp;
I was left alone, weeping. I became like

06:13:00.359 --> 06:13:06.959
a calf left behind on its native pastures.&nbsp;
Kublai the Wise Khan spent his summers

06:13:06.959 --> 06:13:15.080
there. They besieged and took precious&nbsp;
Daidu. I have lost the whole of it to China.

06:13:15.080 --> 06:13:26.519
Next, the Hongwu emperor turned his&nbsp;
sights on the heartland of the Mongols,

06:13:26.520 --> 06:13:35.439
the great steppe itself, and the city that the&nbsp;
Chinese called Ho-Lin, the Mongol capital of

06:13:35.439 --> 06:13:42.599
Karakorum. With vengeance in their hearts, the Ming&nbsp;
marched out into the steppe and arrived at the

06:13:42.600 --> 06:13:52.080
walls of Karakorum in 1372. After a period of&nbsp;
bitter resistance, they occupied the city, as

06:13:52.080 --> 06:13:58.719
the Mingshi recalls. On the 1st of March, the&nbsp;
Duke of Wei was appointed commander-in-chief

06:13:58.719 --> 06:14:05.199
of the expedition against the enemy slaves. They&nbsp;
were to campaign northward into the sandy desert.

06:14:05.199 --> 06:14:12.879
He was to depart from the Yanmen Pass and race&nbsp;
onto Ho-Lin. On the 29th, Li Wen-chung defeated the

06:14:12.879 --> 06:14:19.359
Yuan forces at the Orkhon River. On the 18th&nbsp;
of May, Lan Yu attacked and smashed the Yuan

06:14:19.359 --> 06:14:26.160
hereditary ruler. He captured his younger son and&nbsp;
concubines, princesses, princes, dukes, and others of

06:14:26.160 --> 06:14:35.160
lower rank, totaling several tens of thousands&nbsp;
of people. He then returned to the capital.

06:14:35.160 --> 06:14:41.680
The timeline of the destruction of Karakorum is&nbsp;
uncertain, but it was likely burned and sacked

06:14:41.680 --> 06:14:49.959
again in 1380, although by this point, there would&nbsp;
have been few people left living there. The city

06:14:49.959 --> 06:14:56.840
had always been a figment of one Great Khan's&nbsp;
imagination, and when it lost its status as capital,

06:14:56.840 --> 06:15:05.000
it had been in a state of decline for years. Now&nbsp;
the final death blow was delivered, and though it

06:15:05.000 --> 06:15:11.359
would resurge a number of times, its ruins would&nbsp;
eventually crumble back into the grasses of the

06:15:11.359 --> 06:15:20.359
steppe. In the centuries that followed, its&nbsp;
stones were taken and reused to create the

06:15:20.359 --> 06:15:28.320
Buddhist monastery of Erdene Zu, which now&nbsp;
sits over its ruin. The destruction was so

06:15:28.320 --> 06:15:35.080
total that for centuries, the location of the&nbsp;
city of the Khans was lost, until in the 19th

06:15:35.080 --> 06:15:40.000
century, Russian archaeologists uncovered&nbsp;
certain inscriptions in the area of the

06:15:40.000 --> 06:15:47.320
monastery that identified the site. Today, the&nbsp;
only sign that the city ever stood there at

06:15:47.320 --> 06:15:53.039
all is the mounds of earth covered in the&nbsp;
grasses of the steppe, stretching out to the

06:15:53.039 --> 06:16:00.719
north of the Erdene Zu monastery, and among them, a&nbsp;
single stone tortoise, one of the four that once

06:16:00.719 --> 06:16:09.000
stood at the four corners of the city, symbols&nbsp;
of everlasting eternity. Now it stands alone

06:16:09.000 --> 06:16:34.840
in the grasslands of Mongolia, an ironic statement&nbsp;
about an empire that rose so far and fell so fast.

06:16:36.719 --> 06:16:42.080
Across the rest of the Mongol world, the&nbsp;
dissolution of their rule was sometimes

06:16:42.080 --> 06:16:50.359
gradual, but just as total. In Persia and&nbsp;
the Middle East, the rulers of the

06:16:50.359 --> 06:16:59.478
Ilkhanate descended from the Ilkhan Hulagu, sacker of&nbsp;
Baghdad, would suffer a similar fate. They would

06:16:59.479 --> 06:17:07.199
convert to Islam and adopt many of the ways&nbsp;
of life of their Persian and Arab subjects.

06:17:07.199 --> 06:17:13.558
During their reign, Persia would experience&nbsp;
something of a golden age, creating hybrid

06:17:13.559 --> 06:17:20.359
styles of architecture that would be repeated&nbsp;
around the world, especially in the India of the

06:17:20.359 --> 06:17:28.558
Mughals. They resurrected the language of Persian,&nbsp;
which had until then been supplanted by Arabic

06:17:28.559 --> 06:17:35.199
as a language of administration and literature,&nbsp;
and commissioned a gloriously illustrated copy

06:17:35.199 --> 06:17:43.080
of the epic work known as the Shahnama, or&nbsp;
the Book of Kings, and they commissioned the

06:17:43.080 --> 06:17:50.400
historian Rashid ad-Din to write his work, the&nbsp;
Compendium of Chronicles, the first attempted

06:17:50.400 --> 06:17:58.039
history of the world ever written, and which we&nbsp;
have heard much from in this episode. But their

06:17:58.039 --> 06:18:09.039
time, too, would pass. The ninth and final ruler of&nbsp;
the Ilkhanate was named Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan. He

06:18:09.039 --> 06:18:18.359
died in 1335, either a victim of the Black Death&nbsp;
or poisoned by one of his wives. After that, the

06:18:18.359 --> 06:18:25.718
Ilkhanate disintegrated rapidly into several&nbsp;states,
which were soon swallowed up by the Timurid

06:18:25.719 --> 06:18:34.879
and Safavid empires. The Chaghatai Kharnate, in the&nbsp;
former lands of the Khwarazmian Empire and Kazakhstan,

06:18:34.879 --> 06:18:43.320
also followed a similar fate, and were snatched&nbsp;
up by the warlord named Timur. When his empire

06:18:43.320 --> 06:18:51.599
collapsed in turn, the region was given over to&nbsp;
local powers. During this time, many of the cities

06:18:51.600 --> 06:18:59.639
damaged by the Mongols, like Samarqand and Bukhara,&nbsp;
enjoyed a kind of revival, and became once again

06:18:59.639 --> 06:19:08.039
wealthy trading stops along the Silk Road. But in&nbsp;
the 15th and 16th centuries, as Europeans opened up

06:19:08.039 --> 06:19:15.279
trading routes by sea and bypassed the Silk Road&nbsp;
entirely, these cities slowly began to lose their

06:19:15.279 --> 06:19:26.558
relevance. Eventually, merchants stopped&nbsp;
coming. The booming markets grew quiet,

06:19:26.559 --> 06:19:33.199
and many of these cities were abandoned. The&nbsp;
destructive power of the economy eventually

06:19:33.199 --> 06:19:38.119
left these cities in ruins more&nbsp;
effectively than the Mongols ever had.

06:19:38.119 --> 06:19:49.439
In the western steppe of Kazakhstan,&nbsp;
Ukraine, and Russia, the Golden Horde, founded by

06:19:49.439 --> 06:19:58.160
the descendants of Chinggis Khan's oldest son Jochi,&nbsp;
was the dominant power for three centuries, but it

06:19:58.160 --> 06:20:05.400
eventually weakened under the ravages of the Black&nbsp;
Death and the competing rivalries of the descendants

06:20:05.400 --> 06:20:14.320
of Jochi. Eventually it split into more than&nbsp;
half a dozen smaller Khanates during the

06:20:14.320 --> 06:20:22.000
15th century. The lands were divided between&nbsp;
the Kazakh Kharnate, the Kharnate of Kazan, the

06:20:22.000 --> 06:20:28.320
Astrakhan Kharnate, the Crimean Kharnate, the&nbsp;
Kharnate of Sibir, the Great Horde, the Nogai

06:20:28.320 --> 06:20:34.759
Horde, and the White Horde, and the steppe&nbsp;
once more looked much as it had in

06:20:34.760 --> 06:20:41.359
the time before Chinggis Khan had united&nbsp;
it, a warring mess of competing nomadic

06:20:41.359 --> 06:20:51.199
states. Throughout this time, the Mongols had&nbsp;
favored one Russian city above all others,

06:20:51.199 --> 06:20:59.160
and had allowed it to gather taxes from the whole&nbsp;
region on their behalf. This city was Muscovy, which we

06:20:59.160 --> 06:21:08.000
know today as Moscow. Eventually Muscovy would break&nbsp;
out from under Mongol control, and bring the other

06:21:08.000 --> 06:21:17.520
city states in the region under its banner, until&nbsp;
in 1547 it founded its own kingdom, the Tsardom of

06:21:17.520 --> 06:21:28.000
Russia. The Russian Tsars would&nbsp;
advance into the steppe, now armed with

06:21:28.000 --> 06:21:39.359
muskets. For the first time in nearly 5,000&nbsp;
years, the steppe horse archer was no longer

06:21:39.359 --> 06:21:46.000
the deadliest entity on the planet, and with&nbsp;
the rise of powerful centralized nations, and

06:21:46.000 --> 06:21:54.279
the crack of powder and shot, the retreat&nbsp;
of the nomads quietly began. The Industrial

06:21:54.279 --> 06:22:01.959
Revolution sealed their fate. Soon, railways&nbsp;
would carve through the wilderness, and the

06:22:01.959 --> 06:22:10.639
sound of repeating rifles echoed across the steppe.&nbsp;
These technological innovations finally allowed

06:22:10.639 --> 06:22:17.920
settled peoples to push into the most remote and&nbsp;
untamed territories where once only nomads had

06:22:17.920 --> 06:22:26.639
roamed. Even the fiercest of nomadic&nbsp;
warrior peoples were subdued by this

06:22:26.639 --> 06:22:34.520
new age. The ancient rhythm of nomadic&nbsp;
incursions, which had ebbed and flowed

06:22:34.520 --> 06:22:41.240
for millennia, finally came to an end,&nbsp;
and the wild heart of the steppe grew still.

06:22:48.120 --> 06:23:02.240
In the 170 years or so between Chinggis&nbsp;
Khan's first conquests and the collapse of the

06:23:02.240 --> 06:23:09.679
Yuan Dynasty, the Mongols had reshaped the&nbsp;
structure of the world. Old power centers had

06:23:09.680 --> 06:23:18.760
been swept away, and in their place, new nations&nbsp;
would begin to rise; Russia, Iran, Mughal India, and

06:23:18.760 --> 06:23:26.080
the newly-united China. The Mongols have left&nbsp;
their mark everywhere, from a vast genetic

06:23:26.080 --> 06:23:34.799
legacy to the names that many of us have today.
At this time, the Turco-Mongolian word for ruler,

06:23:34.799 --> 06:23:39.439
Khan, is one of the world's most&nbsp;
popular surnames, belonging to more

06:23:39.439 --> 06:23:46.359
than 23 million people worldwide, and it is&nbsp;
the 12th most common surname in the United

06:23:46.359 --> 06:24:00.359
Kingdom. It's in China that they left&nbsp;
perhaps their greatest legacy. In some ways, the

06:24:00.359 --> 06:24:07.080
Mongols invented the modern concept of China,&nbsp;
uniting its two halves, along with Tibet and

06:24:07.080 --> 06:24:14.959
Manchuria, making up the borders of the modern&nbsp;
nation today. But on the Chinese people, the

06:24:14.959 --> 06:24:21.719
psychological effect of the Mongol conquest&nbsp;
and occupation was immense, and the centuries

06:24:21.719 --> 06:24:30.240
that followed would be characterized by a great&nbsp;
turning inwards. The China of the Song Dynasty had

06:24:30.240 --> 06:24:38.119
been inventive and outward-looking, seeking new&nbsp;
technologies and foreign influences, but

06:24:38.119 --> 06:24:45.199
the Ming Dynasty that took its place was&nbsp;
paranoid and suspicious of change. While

06:24:45.199 --> 06:24:51.160
the Song had experimented with innovative&nbsp;
and modern economic systems, the Ming went

06:24:51.160 --> 06:24:59.240
backwards, reverting to a more feudal society to&nbsp;
deal with the damage left by the Mongols. This

06:24:59.240 --> 06:25:04.920
inward-looking mentality is perhaps nowhere&nbsp;
better demonstrated than in the project

06:25:04.920 --> 06:25:11.760
that would take up much of the 15th and 16th&nbsp;
centuries; that is the building of the Great Wall.

06:25:11.760 --> 06:25:22.639
While China had built defensive walls for&nbsp;
more than a thousand years at this point, it was

06:25:22.639 --> 06:25:31.400
in the Ming period that the true Great Wall as we&nbsp;
know it today took its shape. This snaking line of

06:25:31.400 --> 06:25:38.798
elegant fortifications runs for nearly 9,000 km&nbsp;
across the northern border of China, turning the

06:25:38.799 --> 06:25:48.279
entire land into a fortress. Using an estimated&nbsp;
100 million tons of building material, the Ming

06:25:48.279 --> 06:25:56.478
Great Wall is the equivalent of building the great&nbsp;
pyramid of Giza nearly fifty times. For much of this

06:25:56.479 --> 06:26:03.639
era, the construction of the Great Wall occupied an&nbsp;
enormous part of the labor, economy, and political

06:26:03.639 --> 06:26:11.039
will of successive Chinese governments. The cost&nbsp;
was so great that the Ming diverted funds from

06:26:11.039 --> 06:26:18.359
other parts of their budget, especially from their&nbsp;
fleets of ships. The Ming had inherited one of the

06:26:18.359 --> 06:26:24.599
largest fleets in the world, with thousands&nbsp;
of large vessels, many larger than any ship

06:26:24.600 --> 06:26:32.439
being built in Europe at the time. These had been&nbsp;
used on voyages of exploration to India, Arabia,

06:26:32.439 --> 06:26:39.718
and Africa, but in the 15th century, the Ming&nbsp;
dismantled much of this naval power, and even

06:26:39.719 --> 06:26:48.439
burned some of the ships in harbor to save costs.&nbsp;
The historian James Waterson describes this inward

06:26:48.439 --> 06:26:57.160
turn. After China's painful experience with the&nbsp;
foreign invaders, it is no coincidence that the

06:26:57.160 --> 06:27:03.558
Ming worked hard to seal off the world beyond&nbsp;
their Great Wall, and to build it ever stronger

06:27:03.559 --> 06:27:09.879
in the post-Mongol period. The Ming suffered&nbsp;
a self-inflicted wound by their efforts to

06:27:09.879 --> 06:27:15.680
seclude their state from the rest of the world,&nbsp;
and in doing so, effectively missed out on

06:27:15.680 --> 06:27:28.920
modernity. But while China looked inwards&nbsp;
and built their Great Wall, on the other

06:27:28.920 --> 06:27:34.320
side of the continent, another&nbsp;
people looked outwards. While China

06:27:34.320 --> 06:27:40.279
burned its ships, another people were&nbsp;
building them. These were the people who

06:27:40.279 --> 06:27:47.080
were undoubtedly the biggest winners of the&nbsp;
Mongol invasions, and who were now positioned

06:27:47.080 --> 06:27:53.359
to embark on a wave of conquests of&nbsp;
their own. Those were the people of

06:27:53.359 --> 06:28:08.359
Europe. While Eastern European lands in the&nbsp;
areas of modern Poland, Hungary, and Russia

06:28:08.359 --> 06:28:14.679
had all suffered from Mongol incursions, the&nbsp;
kingdoms of Western Europe in France, England,

06:28:14.680 --> 06:28:21.719
Spain, and Portugal had escaped unscathed, and&nbsp;
on top of that, they had reaped a huge number

06:28:21.719 --> 06:28:31.400
of benefits. The anthropologist Jack Weatherford&nbsp;
makes the following argument. Although never ruled

06:28:31.400 --> 06:28:38.279
by the Mongols, in many ways Europe gained the most&nbsp;
from their world system. The Europeans received all

06:28:38.279 --> 06:28:44.599
the benefits of trade, technology transfer, and&nbsp;
the global awakening without paying the cost of

06:28:44.600 --> 06:28:51.240
Mongol conquest. The Europeans, who had been cut off&nbsp;
from the mainstream of civilization since the fall

06:28:51.240 --> 06:28:58.279
of Rome, eagerly drank in the new knowledge, put on&nbsp;
the new clothes, listened to the new music, ate the

06:28:58.279 --> 06:29:04.039
new foods, and enjoyed a rapidly-escalating&nbsp;
standard of living in almost every regard.

06:29:06.680 --> 06:29:14.479
Europe was fascinated by the Mongols and&nbsp;
their vast world-spanning Empire. In Italy,

06:29:14.479 --> 06:29:20.760
people even started giving their children&nbsp;
Mongol names, with one, Grande Can, meaning

06:29:20.760 --> 06:29:28.080
Great Khan, being especially popular. The Mongols&nbsp;
had caused Europeans to come into contact with

06:29:28.080 --> 06:29:34.359
Chinese technologies that might have otherwise&nbsp;
taken them centuries more to encounter, among

06:29:34.359 --> 06:29:43.039
them, Chinese paper, the compass, and gunpowder.&nbsp;
The Elizabethan English writer Francis Bacon

06:29:43.039 --> 06:29:49.199
commented on the transformative effect that&nbsp;
these Chinese technologies had on European

06:29:49.199 --> 06:29:56.959
society. We should notice the force, effect, and&nbsp;
consequences of inventions which are nowhere

06:29:56.959 --> 06:30:03.959
more conspicuous than in those three which&nbsp;
were unknown to the ancients; namely printing,

06:30:04.520 --> 06:30:10.439
gunpowder, and the compass, for these three&nbsp;
have changed the appearance and state of

06:30:10.439 --> 06:30:18.240
the whole world, first in literature, then&nbsp;
in warfare, and lastly in navigation, and

06:30:18.240 --> 06:30:26.439
innumerable changes have been thence derived&nbsp;
so that no empire, sect, or star appears to

06:30:26.439 --> 06:30:33.919
have exercised a greater power and influence on&nbsp;
human affairs than these mechanical discoveries.

06:30:36.359 --> 06:30:45.519
The Mongol conquests helped Europe in another way,&nbsp;
too; that is in broadening its horizons. The text of

06:30:45.520 --> 06:30:52.279
the travels of Marco Polo was still being printed&nbsp;
in the 15th century when an Italian navigator

06:30:52.279 --> 06:31:01.599
bought a copy in a Genoise bookshop. The text had&nbsp;
a transformative effect on him. This copy he would

06:31:01.600 --> 06:31:07.680
read over and over, with an obsessive&nbsp;
attention to detail, even leaving handwritten

06:31:07.680 --> 06:31:14.959
annotations in its margins. This navigator dreamed&nbsp;
of one day visiting the lands of the Far East

06:31:14.959 --> 06:31:23.160
himself, and the court of the Great Khan that he&nbsp;
had read about. His name was Christopher Columbus,

06:31:23.160 --> 06:31:31.119
and he, too, would change the course of history. In&nbsp;
the journal that he kept on his voyage westwards,

06:31:31.119 --> 06:31:37.920
he wrote to King Ferdinand and Queen Isabella&nbsp;
of Spain that he wanted to reach this far-off

06:31:37.920 --> 06:31:46.520
place. In this present month, in consequence&nbsp;
of the information which I had given Your

06:31:46.520 --> 06:31:53.680
Highnesses respecting the countries of India&nbsp;
and of a prince, called Great Khan, which in our

06:31:53.680 --> 06:32:02.279
language signifies king of kings, Your Highnesses&nbsp;
determined to send me, Christopher Columbus, to

06:32:02.279 --> 06:32:10.478
the above-mentioned countries of India, to see the said&nbsp;
princes, people, and territories, and to learn their

06:32:10.479 --> 06:32:20.080
disposition. With the Chinese invention&nbsp;
of gunpowder, by this point, Europeans

06:32:20.080 --> 06:32:27.119
had already developed or adopted cannons,
muskets, and arquebuses, and with these in the

06:32:27.119 --> 06:32:33.959
coming century, they would conquer vast swathes&nbsp;
of land in the Americas and all around the world.

06:32:33.959 --> 06:32:42.359
The age of European colonialism, and the&nbsp;
following 500 years of European power around

06:32:42.359 --> 06:32:49.519
the globe, all found their roots in the fertile&nbsp;
soil left behind after the inferno of the Mongol

06:32:49.520 --> 06:33:05.039
conquests. In his work, The Canterbury Tales,&nbsp;
the first book published in the English

06:33:05.039 --> 06:33:11.879
language, written around the year 1390, the&nbsp;
author Geoffrey Chaucer relates one legend

06:33:11.879 --> 06:33:18.039
associated with Chinggis Khan, and writes&nbsp;
in the following glowing terms about his

06:33:18.039 --> 06:33:27.119
legacy. This noble king was called Genghis Khan,&nbsp;
who in his time was of so great renown that

06:33:27.119 --> 06:33:33.799
there was nowhere in no region so excellent&nbsp;
a lord at all things. He lacked nothing that

06:33:33.799 --> 06:33:39.199
belonged to a king. As of the sect of&nbsp;
which he was born, he kept his law to

06:33:39.199 --> 06:33:46.039
which he was sworn, and there, too, he was&nbsp;
hardy, wise, and rich, and kept always so well

06:33:46.039 --> 06:33:53.799
royal estate that there was nowhere such&nbsp;another
man. This noble king, this Tartar, Genghis Khan.

06:34:36.639 --> 06:34:45.559
In 1876, the Russian traveler Nikolai Mikhailovich &nbsp;
Przhevalskii traveled to Mongolia, hoping to find

06:34:45.559 --> 06:34:53.879
there traces of the great Khans of old, and perhaps&nbsp;
even find the lost burial place of Chinggis Khan

06:34:53.879 --> 06:35:03.920
himself. But he found himself disappointed at&nbsp;
what he saw. All he found was the vast, empty

06:35:03.920 --> 06:35:09.600
grasslands and deserts, broken&nbsp;
by rocky mounds of stone, and

06:35:09.600 --> 06:35:18.599
the only evidence of past greatness he&nbsp;
could find was in the people's stories.

06:35:18.599 --> 06:35:28.320
The effect of these bare yellow hillocks&nbsp;
is most dreary and depressing when you are among

06:35:28.320 --> 06:35:37.359
them, and can see nothing but the sky and the sand.&nbsp;
No sounds are heard, not even the chirping of the

06:35:37.359 --> 06:35:45.000
grasshopper. The silence of the tomb surrounds&nbsp;
you. No wonder that the local Mongols relate

06:35:45.000 --> 06:35:52.359
some marvelous stories about these frightful&nbsp;
deserts. They tell you that this was the scene

06:35:52.359 --> 06:35:59.398
of the principal exploit of Chinggis Khan, and&nbsp;
here warriors fought against the Chinese, and

06:35:59.398 --> 06:36:06.119
slew countless numbers of people, whose bodies&nbsp;
God caused the winds to cover with the sand

06:36:06.119 --> 06:36:13.639
from the desert. To this day, the Mongols relate&nbsp;
with superstitious awe how groans and cries may

06:36:13.639 --> 06:36:21.080
be heard in the sands of Kuzupchi, from the spirits&nbsp;
of the departed, and that every now and then, the

06:36:21.080 --> 06:36:28.600
winds which stir up the sands expose to view&nbsp;
different treasures such as silver dishes, which

06:36:28.600 --> 06:36:36.000
may not be taken away, because death immediately&nbsp;
overtakes the bold man who would venture to touch

06:36:36.000 --> 06:36:43.920
them. Wherever Przhevalskii traveled,&nbsp;
he found legends about Chinggis

06:36:43.920 --> 06:36:50.279
Khan still circulating on the lips of&nbsp;
Mongol people. Some even told him of a

06:36:50.279 --> 06:36:57.039
prophecy, that the Great Khan would one day&nbsp;
return and once again lead his people to

06:36:57.039 --> 06:37:08.478
greatness. Chinggis Khan's memory is better&nbsp;
preserved in Ordos than in any part of Mongolia.

06:37:08.479 --> 06:37:16.080
We heard more tales here about the conqueror&nbsp;
than anywhere else. The Mongols reckon that 650

06:37:16.080 --> 06:37:26.039
years have elapsed since his death, leaving 150&nbsp;
to 350 years more before his coming resurrection.

06:37:26.039 --> 06:37:32.680
The same people assert that on the very day of the&nbsp;
accomplishments of this miracle, some hero will be

06:37:32.680 --> 06:37:41.039
born in China with whom Chinghiz Khan will do battle,&nbsp;
subdue him, and lead his people from Ordos to what

06:37:41.039 --> 06:37:51.920
is now called the land of the Khalkas, the native&nbsp;
country of the Mongols. And if Przhevalskii hoped

06:37:51.920 --> 06:37:59.920
to find the grave of Chinggis Khan, he would also&nbsp;
be disappointed. If anyone did know where his body

06:37:59.920 --> 06:38:07.959
was to be found, Przhevalskii found that even after so&nbsp;
many centuries, the Mongolian people still weren't

06:38:07.959 --> 06:38:18.920
telling. We could not discover the name of the&nbsp;
temple where Chinghiz Khan is said to be buried.

06:38:18.920 --> 06:38:31.520
The Mongols, for some reason or other, would&nbsp;
not divulge it. In the 20th century, a communist

06:38:31.520 --> 06:38:38.080
government seized power in Mongolia, and&nbsp;
in close cooperation with the Soviet Union, engaged

06:38:38.080 --> 06:38:46.760
in purges of some 30,000 Mongolians, including&nbsp;
thousands of Buddhist monks. Many of the victims

06:38:46.760 --> 06:38:55.039
were from one clan who still traced their descent&nbsp;
back to Chinggis Khan. The Soviets were haunted by

06:38:55.039 --> 06:39:03.160
the ghost of the Great Khan, fearing that he might&nbsp;
become a rallying point for Mongolian nationalists.

06:39:03.160 --> 06:39:09.279
For this reason, they worked hard to destroy&nbsp;
any relics associated with him, closing Buddhist

06:39:09.279 --> 06:39:18.240
monasteries, and trying to erase all memory of the&nbsp;
Great Khan. But the Soviet-aligned government did

06:39:18.240 --> 06:39:26.799
maintain one aspect of Mongolian tradition. For 800&nbsp;
years, successive Mongolian rulers had maintained

06:39:26.799 --> 06:39:33.760
the law against anyone entering the region&nbsp;
of the sacred mountain Burkan Khaldun, the site

06:39:33.760 --> 06:39:43.279
where Chinggis Khan is most likely buried. For&nbsp;
centuries, this land would be known as the Yeke Qorig,

06:39:43.279 --> 06:39:51.519
or great taboo. When the Communists seized power, they&nbsp;
feared that this region would become a pilgrimage

06:39:51.520 --> 06:39:59.320
site and a focus of Mongolian nationalism. For this&nbsp;
reason, the Soviet-aligned government maintained

06:39:59.320 --> 06:40:07.718
the ancient prohibition on entering it. The region&nbsp;
of the great taboo was renamed and called simply

06:40:07.719 --> 06:40:15.920
the Highly Restricted Area. They built a top-secret&nbsp;
air base there for the use of Soviet planes, and

06:40:15.920 --> 06:40:22.199
most likely a stockpile of nuclear weapons, so&nbsp;
that even in the modern era, the land cannot

06:40:22.199 --> 06:40:33.240
be entered without special permissions, and the&nbsp;
grave of Chinggis Khan remains un-found to this day.

06:40:44.760 --> 06:40:50.479
I want to end the episode with a reading from&nbsp;
a piece of Chinese poetry written during this

06:40:50.479 --> 06:41:01.559
time by a poet from the southern Song Dynasty. His&nbsp;
name was Wen Tianxiang. Wen had been a government

06:41:01.559 --> 06:41:08.160
minister in Song China, and after witnessing the&nbsp;
destruction of his land, he led the resistance

06:41:08.160 --> 06:41:17.279
against the Mongol invaders. He was eventually&nbsp;
captured and held in a Mongol prison. Despite

06:41:17.279 --> 06:41:25.279
all the tortures and deprivations that he suffered,&nbsp;
he never wavered in his resistance. It was during

06:41:25.279 --> 06:41:33.240
this time of imprisonment that he wrote one of his&nbsp;
masterpieces, titled Crossing the Sea of Solitude.

06:41:34.600 --> 06:41:41.879
As you listen, consider the contradictions and&nbsp;
paradoxes of this time, a time of discovery and

06:41:41.879 --> 06:41:50.559
exploration, a time of new ideas and unforeseen&nbsp;
encounters, but also a time of incalculable sorrow,

06:41:50.559 --> 06:41:58.119
as the great powers of the world crumbled, and a&nbsp;
new world order took shape. Imagine the hollowed

06:41:58.119 --> 06:42:07.279
halls and shattered walls, the empty markets of&nbsp;
Samarqand, Nishapur, and Bukhara. Imagine the gutted palaces

06:42:07.279 --> 06:42:15.599
and empty temples of Beijing and Hangchow. Imagine&nbsp;
the emptied streets and burned-out houses, the

06:42:15.600 --> 06:42:24.000
crumbling libraries of Baghdad and Aleppo,&nbsp;
and the fallen churches of Novgorod and Kiev,

06:42:24.000 --> 06:42:33.160
and finally, at the end of it all, the windswept&nbsp;
grasses growing through the stones of Karakorum.

06:42:33.160 --> 06:42:39.704
Imagine the world as you know it coming to&nbsp;
an end, and a new one rising from the ashes.

06:42:39.711 --> 06:43:06.439
Through painstaking mastery&nbsp;
of the Classics, I have risen high; but four

06:43:06.439 --> 06:43:14.919
years of raging war have well nigh brought&nbsp;
all round destitution and ruin. My shattered

06:43:14.920 --> 06:43:22.160
country does remind me of willow catkins&nbsp;
swept by wind. In my life I sink or swim

06:43:22.160 --> 06:43:26.920
like duckweed beaten by rain. Through&nbsp;
the frightful shallows we fought our

06:43:26.920 --> 06:43:33.398
way. They tell us now of the frightful&nbsp;
battle never won, but on the lonely ocean

06:43:33.398 --> 06:43:42.959
I could but sigh, for being captured and all&nbsp;
alone. Down through the ages, who that ever lived

06:43:42.959 --> 06:44:03.039
has not met with death? I wish only to leave my&nbsp;
loyal heart shining red in history's great book.

